<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                         *Wallace E. Howell    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Wallace E. Howell, a meteorologist known for  
his attempts to generate rain during a New York drought 50 years 
ago, died June 12. He was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	Howell spent two decades seeding clouds with dry ice and silver  
iodide in efforts to make rain in Canada, Cuba, Peru, the 
Philippines and other parched countries. In the 1960s, he developed 
one of the first snow-making machines for ski resorts. 
</P>
<P>
	Howell's fame came from his work in New York during the water  
shortage of 1949-50. He was hired by New York City in early 1950, 
earning $100 a day. 
</P>
<P>
	The rain came, filling reservoirs to 99 percent of capacity.  
There was even a freak snowstorm in mid-April coined ``Howell's 
snow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Howell was later head of the weather observatory on Mount  
Washington in New Hampshire and spent 15 years with the Federal 
Bureau of Reclamation. 

</P>
<P>
                         *C. Walton Lillehei    	
</P>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Dr. C. Walton Lillehei, a pioneer who  
created many innovative open heart surgery techniques during the 
1950s, died Monday of cancer. He was 80. 
</P>
<P>
	Lillehei was a surgery professor at the University of Minnesota  
and later chairman of the Department of Surgery at the Cornell 
Medical Center-New York Hospital for several years beginning in 
1967. 
</P>
<P>
	Lillehei wrote more than 700 clinical publications and trained  
more than 1,000 cardiac surgeons, including Dr. Christiaan Barnard, 
who performed the first human heart transplant in 1967, and other 
pioneers in heart transplantation. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1955, Lillehei led university researchers in developing a  
machine to oxygenate blood and pump it through the patient's body, 
making open-heart and ultimately heart transplant surgery possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Lillehei worked with Medtronic Inc. cofounder Earl Bakken in  
1957 to develop the first wearable pacemaker for the successful 
treatment of patients with chronic complete heart block. 
</P>
<P>
	He also contributed to the design of four prosthetic heart  
valves, including the widely-used St. Jude Medical Mechanical Heart 
Valve. 

</P>
<P>
                             *Bob Lucas    	
</P>
<P>
	SEBASTOPOL, Calif. (AP) -- Bob Lucas, a jazz pianist who played  
with greats such as Dave Brubeck and Dinah Shore, died Sunday of 
leukemia, two weeks after performing with Eddie Fisher. He was 60. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks ago, a frail Lucas accompanied Fisher in a performance  
in San Francisco that was filmed by Dateline NBC for a piece on 
Fisher's attempted comeback. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucas discovered jazz when his father invited Louis Armstrong to  
stay at the family hotel because other hotels refused to rent a 
room to the black musician. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucas passed up a scholarship at the New York Light Opera  
Company in favor of jazz. He came to California in 1968, playing at 
clubs in the San Francisco area. 
</P>
<P>
	In the late 1970s he took over the foundering Russian River Jazz  
Festival and brought it back to life. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucas was well-known for his charity work, playing at events  
such as AIDS and cancer benefits, dropping by nursing homes or 
anywhere he could gather an audience. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Archbishop Mihail    	
</P>
<P>
	SKOPJE, Macedonia (AP) -- Archbishop Mihail, the head of  
Macedonia's Orthodox Church, died Tuesday. He was 88. 
</P>
<P>
	The archbishop became the head of Macedonia's Orthodox Church  
shortly after the former Yugoslav republic became an independent 
state in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	The Macedonian Orthodox Church was established in 1967, during  
the Communist-run former Yugoslavia, as a splinter from the Serbian 
Orthodox Church, whose seat is in Belgrade. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Mark O'Brien    	
</P>
<P>
	BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) -- Mark O'Brien, a writer who was the  
subject of an Academy Award-winning documentary about his life 
using an iron lung, died Sunday of complications from bronchitis. 
He was 49. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1997 film ``Breathing Lessons: The Life and Work of Mark  
O'Brien,'' described his struggle to live and work on his own. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Brien was 6 years old when he contracted polio and was forced  
to begin using the iron lung. 
</P>
<P>
	He was first published in 1979, when Co-Evolution Quarterly used  
his essay on independent living. Sandy Close, executive editor of 
Pacific News Service, saw the article and hired O'Brien as a 
correspondent. 
</P>
<P>
	Close said O'Brien initially dictated his stories, then used a  
stick in his mouth to press the keys of a typewriter. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, O'Brien co-founded Lemonade Factory, a small press in  
Berkeley that publishes poetry by people with disabilities. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Solly Robins    	
</P>
<P>
	GEM LAKE, Minn. (AP) -- Solly Robins, founder of the law firm  
that won a $6.6 billion settlement in the Minnesota tobacco trial, 
died Monday. He was 86. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last 20 years the Robins law firm has won a $38 million  
settlement for 199 women in the Dalkon Shield cases, $470 million 
representing the government of India against Union Carbide in the 
1984 Bhopal chemical disaster, and $6.6 billion in a 1998 
settlement against the tobacco industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The firm, founded in 1938, now has more than 250 lawyers and  
offices in Minneapolis, Atlanta, Los Angeles, Boston, San 
Francisco, Chicago and Washington. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Joaquin Rodrigo    	
</P>
<P>
	MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Joaquin Rodrigo, one of Spain's best known  
composers, died Tuesday. He was 97. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodrigo was blinded by diphtheria at three, and as a child  
learned to play piano and violin with the help of Braille. 
</P>
<P>
	It was in Paris in 1939 that Rodrigo composed the ``Concierto de  
Aranjuez'' for guitar, shortly before returning to Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	The melodic piece, named after a town 30 miles southeast of  
Madrid dominated by a royal summer palace, was first performed in 
the northeastern city of Barcelona in 1940. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodrigo received several awards during his lifetime, including  
the Prince of Asturias prize for the arts in 1996. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
