<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alcoa Earnings Rise in 2nd Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Alcoa reported its second-quarter earnings  
rose 15.9 percent, a gain the No. 1 aluminum maker attributed to 
productivity improvements. 
</P>
<P>
	The company earned $240 million, or 64 cents a share, up from  
$207.1 million, or 62 cents a share, in the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Alcoa's earnings were a penny over the expectations of analysts  
surveyed by First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales rose 12.4 percent to $4.03 billion from $3.58 billion a  
year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said shipments of aluminum products in the second  
quarter were 1.1 million metric tons, up 28 percent from 866,000 
metric tons in the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Alain Belda, the company's chairman and chief executive, said  
the company's earnings reflected productivity improvements in the 
United States and in overseas operations. 
</P>
<P>
	First-half earnings came to $461.1 million, or $1.25 a share, up  
from $417 million, or $1.25 a share, in the first half of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	First-half sales rose to $8.02 billion from $7.03 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Alcoa shares fell nearly 4 percent, or $2.37 1/2, to close at  
$61.37 1/2 on the New York Stock Exchange. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
