<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mass. Gov. Announces Drug Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Some Massachusetts seniors would pay a basic  
premium and get unlimited prescription drug coverage once their 
bills exceed $1,500, according to a proposal by the governor. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Paul Cellucci's plan calls for seniors who earn more than  
150 percent of the federal poverty line to pay $49 a month in 
premiums. After a $1,500 annual deductible, all prescription costs 
would be covered by the plan. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal comes on the heels of President Clinton's proposed  
Medicare overhaul, which calls for universal coverage for 
prescription drugs for Medicare recipients and the elimination of 
patient co-payments for preventive services. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Cellucci's $50 million plan, elderly people who make below  
150 percent of the poverty line -- which comes to about $12,360 for 
an individual -- would pay no premiums and get unlimited coverage 
after paying a $750 annual deductible. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal, outlined Tuesday, must compete with rival plans  
adopted in the state Legislature. A final budget is being forged in 
a conference committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The state now has a $30 million program that helps low-income  
elderly people pay for prescriptions, but officials acknowledge it 
is not adequate. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Richard Moore, chairman of the Senate Health Care  
Committee, called the governor's proposal ``a good first step.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Becky Derby, a spokeswoman for Health Care for All, said her  
organization had qualms about the proposal, including Cellucci's 
description of it as only a temporary program. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
