<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Palmer Disses Cart Use in Golf  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- If you want to get Arnold Palmer  
going, ask him about golf carts. 
</P>
<P>
	The 69-year-old is playing in the U.S. Senior Open, where golf  
carts are taboo. If he had his way, they'd be banned at all Senior 
events. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am so strong on not having golf carts in competitive golf,''  
Palmer said Wednesday. ``I am almost 70 years old and I tell you 
what. I'd rather drop dead out there before I get in a golf cart 
and I mean it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer said part of the challenge of golf is the endurance  
required to play 18 holes day after day. Riding in a cart removes 
that part of the test, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Walking is part of the game,'' Palmer said. ``It is a physical  
thing and golf is physical. If you don't believe me, just look at 
Tiger Woods and David Duval. They are both physical specimens. They 
do a lot to stay that way. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guys that do not do that and do not keep themselves in  
some kind of physical condition are not going to be as competitive 
as the guys that are in good physical condition. It is just like 
every other sport.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer isn't opposed to carts entirely. For the weekend golfer,  
they're just fine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that our golf clubs around the nation are surviving  
because we have golf carts and we have golf cart revenues and we 
have people that are playing golf on a day-to-day basis that are 
not physically able to play if they couldn't ride,'' Palmer said. 
``I think golf carts have lent a great deal to the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just not in tournaments.  
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *HOT HALE:* Defending champion Hale Irwin's appearance at the  
Senior Open rekindled memories of his visits to Iowa as a defensive 
back at the University of Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	Irwin played at Iowa State twice during those years, and  
Colorado won both times. The most memorable visit came in his 
senior year. 
</P>
<P>
	It was one of those miserably cold Midwestern afternoons with a  
biting wind blowing across the plains. The Iowa State players had 
charcoal heaters to keep them warm. The Colorado bench had no such 
accoutrements. 
</P>
<P>
	``So I am over there and make a tackle on the sideline,'' Irwin  
recalled. ``It's slick and then we just start sliding. Into the 
bench we go. I'm waiting for things to quit falling and Frank 
Bosch, who was a defensive tackle, comes over and with one hand, 
grabs me by the back of my shoulder pads and just picks me up. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, what are you doing. He says, you're burning. All the  
coals had fallen on my neck and my jersey was smoldering.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irwin also is on fire now, though in a different way. He has won  
three of his last five tournaments and finished sixth in another. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SMILING IRISH EYES:* Christy O'Connor is still savoring his  
victory in last week's State Farm Senior Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Connor said his daughter figured there had been 135 calls to  
their home in Ireland since Sunday and dozens of telegrams from 
well-wishers congratulating him on his first Senior Tour victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``In my locker, guys down here are joking that there were more  
stickers on my locker than they have ever seen in their lives,'' he 
said. ``So yes, it has been great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And O'Connor still gets warm feelings when he recalls the  
ovation he received walking up to the last hole on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you don't love that, you don't love golf,'' he said. ``When  
you come up to the 18th hole and you see people who have paid to 
come and watch you stand and applaud, I think that is the greatest 
feeling anybody could ever have.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *IOWA TIES:* Three of the competitors have ties to Iowa, which  
has never before had a gold tournament of this magnitude. 
</P>
<P>
	When Jack Nicklaus withdrew, it cleared the way for former  
Bettendorf resident Richard Karl to get in. Karl, a pro from 
Galena, Ill., was the first alternate in qualifying at the Wakonda 
Club in Des Moines on June 16. 
</P>
<P>
	He lost a sudden-death playoff with Dick Clemens, who spent  
three years as basketball coach at Clarke College in Dubuque. 
Clemens, who lives in East Dubuque, Ill., is a teaching pro at 
Eagle Ridge Resort in Galena. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Rubin, an amateur from Barrington, Ill., attended the  
University of Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TWIN CELEBRATION:* Larry Laoretti, won the 1992 Senior Open,  
would have two reasons to celebrate if he captured this year's 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	The tournament ends Sunday, when Laoretti will turn 60.  
</P>
<P>
	If Laoretti did win, it would be a rarity on the Senior Tour,  
where the younger players dominate. Of the 572 tournaments 
contested since the Senior Tour started in 1980, 87 percent have 
been won by golfers between the ages of 50 and 55. Thirty-seven 
percent have been won by players who were 50 or 51. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the law of the land,'' said Allen Doyle, 51, who has  
won three tournaments in his first full year on the Senior Tour. 
``The old can't play with the young.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
