<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Air Canada Strike Talks Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Air Canada presented its flight attendants with a  
revised contract offer Wednesday as a midnight strike deadline 
approached that could ground the airline. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no guarantee the new proposals would produce a deal,  
but both sides -- and a federal mediator -- expressed hope that an 
agreement could be reached to avert a strike. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither side would discuss details of how the new offer might  
resolve the main outstanding dispute, over pension benefits. The 
5,100 flight attendants, members of the Canadian Union of Public 
Employees, say the pension plan they have is inadequate. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Canada, which handles about 60,000 passengers a day on 660  
to 700 flights, says it will halt all its flights in the event of a 
strike. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline was operating normally Wednesday, but has stopped  
taking reservations for flights from Thursday through July 14. It 
is offering refunds or exchanges, subject to availability, on all 
tickets already purchased for travel during that period. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Canada's regional carriers -- AirBC, Air Ontario, Air  
Alliance and Air Nova -- would continue to operate normally during a 
strike. Air Canada said customers traveling on codeshare flights 
operated by its partner airlines -- including United Airlines, 
Lufthansa, SAS, Air New Zealand, EVA Air and Royal Jordanian -- 
would not be affected by a strike. 
</P>
<P>
	The labor dispute comes just as Canada's largest airline has  
just started to emerge from the effects of last September's pilots 
strike. That dispute shut down Air Canada for two weeks, alienating 
customers and burdening the airline with a big 1998 loss. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
