<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Danish Flights Grounded on Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) -- Scandinavian Airlines System ground  
crews at Copenhagen's Kastrup Airport staged a four-hour wildcat 
strike today to protest possible cost cutting measures. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 70 SAS flights from northern Europe's busiest airport  
were canceled to destinations including London, Frankfurt, 
Budapest, Vienna and Tel Aviv, Israel. The strike by check-in 
staff, baggage handlers and administrative staff also spilled over 
to other airlines using Kastrup Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,000 SAS employees joined the strike, which meant travel  
chaos for hundreds of people on summer vacation, business and other 
trips. 
</P>
<P>
	``We resume work because of customers. We don't want to  
disappoint them,'' ground personnel union spokesman Nicholas 
Fischer said after work resumed at 5 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	SAS management efforts to bring down operating costs led to the  
strike. The strikers rejected plans to restructure the company and 
cut jobs among the 10,000 employees in the three Scandinavian 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	The Danish ground personnel sent a letter on Wednesday to the  
SAS management in Stockholm, Sweden, warning new strikes could take 
place if they don't put aside the restructuring plans. 
</P>
<P>
	The carrier which is jointly owned by Denmark, Sweden and  
Norway, is looking into ways to reduce operating costs by $430 
million a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Kastrup Airport served 17 million passengers last year.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
