<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Broker Sentenced to Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Despite a prosecutor's plea for a more lenient  
punishment, a broker at a now-defunct investment firm that stole 
$75 million from clients was sentenced to nine years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``A substantial number of the crooks he was dealing with will  
soon be in prison,'' Assistant District Attorney John Moscow told 
the judge before sentencing. 
</P>
<P>
	State Supreme Court Justice Edward McLaughlin imposed the  
sentence on Roman Okin, 31, of Manhattan, who had worked for A.R. 
Baron &AMP; Co. The firm was created solely to steal its customers' 
money, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Okin, jailed for the past 13 months, pleaded guilty in May 1998  
to enterprise corruption and began helping in the prosecution of 
co-defendants and the recovery of some of the stolen money. 
</P>
<P>
	Okin was among 14 Baron brokers charged in 1997 in a 174-count  
indictment that accused them of lying to investors, making 
unauthorized trades, forging documents, and manipulating stocks and 
markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Moscow said 13 of the defendants have pleaded guilty and one,  
John McAndris, was convicted after trial. McLaughlin sentenced 
McAndris, 57, of Montvale, N.J., to five to 15 years in prison, the 
longest sentence imposed in the Baron case. 
</P>
<P>
	After explaining to McLaughlin that Okin's help prevented most  
of the other defendants from being able to stage a viable trial 
defense, Moscow suggested a sentence of one to three or two to six 
years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Expressing his regret, Okin said, ``I am very sorry for the  
crimes I committed. I am sorry for all the people I hurt. I wish I 
had not made those mistakes. Along the way, I lost my boundaries of 
right and wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McLaughlin said that however sincere Okin's apology might be, he  
is sure that the defendant's guilty plea and expressions of 
contrition were, at the outset, ``self-centered,'' offered in hopes 
of leniency. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge said sentences for co-called ``white-collar'' crimes  
rarely reflect ``the enormous illegality and the purposeful 
deceit'' that occurs. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine-year maximum sentence McLaughlin imposed means that  
Okin must serve at least three years in prison and that he will be 
eligible for parole in 23 months. The judge could have sentenced 
him to 25 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Baron opened in July 1991 and closed in July 1996 after years of  
complaints. When the indictments were handed up, District Attorney 
Robert Morgenthau estimated that Baron had stolen $75 million from 
8,000 clients. 
</P>
<P>
	The district attorney said then that Baron was a place where  
``every conceivable form of dishonesty was used,'' and which ``was 
created and existed for no other reason than to line the pockets of 
its executives and employees at the expense of unsuspecting members 
of the public.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 21:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mercedes-Benz, Lexus Score High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Mercedes-Benz and Lexus rated highest in the  
latest crash tests of midsize sport utility vehicles performed by 
the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety. 
</P>
<P>
	The group gave its ``best pick'' rating to the 1999  
Mercedes-Benz M-class and Lexus RX300, based on its frontal offset 
crash test in which the vehicles were driven at 40 mph into a 
deformable barrier. 
</P>
<P>
	In the latest test, six 1999 SUVs with new designs were rated.  
The worst performer was the Mitsubishi Montero Sport, which was 
rated poor for a major collapse of the driver-passenger 
compartment. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a huge difference between the best and worst  
performers,'' Brian O'Neill, institute president, said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Other models tested were the popular Jeep Grand Cherokee, which  
was rated marginal, and the Dodge Durango and Land Rover Discovery 
II, which were rated acceptable. 
</P>
<P>
	The institute's tests are particularly demanding because just  
the driver's side of a vehicle strikes the barrier, forcing a 
relatively small portion of the vehicle to absorb the crash energy. 
The federal government's crash tests involve driving vehicles into 
a rigid barrier with the full width of the front end making 
contact. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Neill said the Mercedes' frame held up particularly well,  
keeping the occupant compartment intact with little or no 
intrusion. By contrast, the instrument panel in the Montero Sport 
was pushed toward the driver dummy, reducing the space available 
for the safety belt and air bag to prevent injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, intrusion into the foot well contributed to the  
likelihood of serious leg injuries in the Montero Sport, O'Neill 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitsubishi spokesman Kim Custer said the Montero Sport meets or  
exceeds federal safety standards. The government does not use a 
frontal offset crash test, but Custer said the institute's results 
showed that vital areas of the body -- the head, neck and chest -- 
were protected in the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has not yet tested the '99 Montero Sport.  
</P>
<P>
	O'Neill said vehicle designs are being improved to provide  
stronger protection for the occupant compartment as a result of 
crash tests performed in the United States and other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``The two best performers are among the newest designs in the  
vehicle group we tested,'' O'Neill noted. ``This likely had a lot 
to do with their good performances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The latest test results, combined with earlier tests for nine  
other models with still-current designs, provide ratings for the 
most popular midsize SUVs on the market. Among the models tested 
earlier, only the Toyota 4Runner earned the same good overall 
rating as the Mercedes and Lexus SUVs. 
</P>
<P>
	The institute notes that the energy a vehicle must absorb in a  
crash test increases with the vehicle's weight, so its tests are 
more demanding of heavier vehicles such as SUVs. But occupants of 
SUVs and other heavier vehicles in real-world, two-vehicle crashes 
typically fare better than people in cars. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	The institute's test results are available on the World Wide Web  
at www.highwaysafety.org. NHTSA's test results are available at 
www.nhtsa.dot.gov. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
