<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Imposes Tariffs on Lamb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton Administration is imposing penalty  
tariffs on foreign lamb in an effort to protect U.S. producers 
threatened by imports from New Zealand and Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning next week, a border tax of 9 percent will be imposed  
on the first 31,851 metric tons, the amount of lamb imported last 
year. Shipments above that will carry a 40 percent tariff, the 
White announced Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This package has been carefully designed to help achieve  
sustained competitiveness for the U.S. industry and is fully 
consistent with our international trade obligations,'' the White 
House said in a statement released in South Dakota, where President 
Clinton was visiting an Indian reservation. 
</P>
<P>
	American ranchers had complained that current tariffs of less  
than 1 percent were too low to protect them from foreign 
competitors flooding the U.S. market with their exports. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia and New Zealand account for 95 percent of the lamb  
imported into the United States. Importers have contended that 
higher tariffs would violate World Trade Organization rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian Prime Minister John Howard, who is scheduled to visit  
the United States next week, said in Canberra that ``there is no 
rational foundation for the American decision.'' He said the U.S. 
action ``strikes at the credibility of its rhetoric'' in support of 
free trade. 
</P>
<P>
	But the U.S. industry hailed the announcement, which included an  
adminstration offer to spend $100 million over the next three years 
to help U.S. sheep producers become more competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the adjustment package is provided as intended we will be  
in a much better position to compete at the end of the relief 
period,'' said Cathy Cummins, an official with the American Sheep 
Industry Association, headquartered in Denver, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Sen. Craig Thomas of Wyoming, a leading lamb  
producing state, said he was pleased Clinton decided to protect the 
domestic industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``You always want more and want it sooner, but this is a  
critical decision that could make the difference for family 
ranchers and small communities throughout the West,'' Thomas said 
in a statement. ``Placing a sufficient level of trade restrictions 
on Australia and New Zealand will hopefully help bring our U.S. 
lamb industry back from the brink.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton acted after the U.S. International Trade Commission  
ruled in a trade case filed by the American Sheep Industry 
Association and other industry groups that U.S. producers were 
being harmed by a surge in lamb imports. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration has also moved to impose higher tariffs on  
various types of foreign steel after U.S. steel companies 
complained that cheaper imports were causing thousands of layoffs 
and had forced three companies into bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
	Several domestic industries are seeking similar relief as the  
U.S. trade deficit this year heads significantly higher than the 
record $169 billion in 1998. While the overall U.S. economy has 
withstood shocks from the global financial crisis, American 
manufacturers and farmers have been battered by lost export markets 
and cheaper imports. 
</P>
<P>
	The tariffs on imported lamb will drop to 6 percent in the  
second year and 3 percent in the third and final year. And the 
31,851 metric ton quota level -- roughly 70 million pounds -- will 
rise by 857 metric tons in the second year and another 857 metric 
tons in the third years, the administration said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lamb imports above those levels will face a 40 percent tariff  
the first year, a 32 percent tariff the second year and a 24 
percent tariff the third year. 
</P>
<P>
	The top 10 sheep-producing states in order of production are  
Texas, California, Wyoming, Colorado, South Dakota, Utah, Montana, 
Idaho and Iowa, according to the Agriculture Department. It said 
there are 74,700 sheep producers in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
