<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Smokers Score Major Win vs. Tobacco  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Tobacco companies were dealt a major setback today  
as a jury found that cigarette makers produced a defective product 
that causes emphysema, lung cancer and other illnesses in a ruling 
that could expose the industry to billions of dollars in damages. 
The verdict affects as many as half a million Florida smokers and 
the heirs of those who died. The jury's decision could prove to be 
the industry's most dire courtroom loss yet, since the plaintiffs 
are seeking at least $200 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady Defends Senate Bid  
</P>
<P>
	WEST DAVENPORT, N.Y. (AP) -- First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton  
defended her bid to run for a Senate seat from New York by 
declaring that it is not as important as where she is from but what 
she stands for. Mrs. Clinton said New Yorkers had some questions 
about what she believes in and the skills and interests that she 
would bring to the job. And she said she would address them. 
Advisers don't expect her to formally declare her candidacy until 
September, at the earliest. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Meets American Indians  
</P>
<P>
	PINE RIDGE, S.D. (AP) -- President Clinton today declared that  
the United States can no longer afford to ignore poverty and 
unemployment among American Indians. Visiting Oglala Sioux on the 
Pine Ridge Reservation, Clinton seemed almost disbelieving as 
Geraldine Blue Bird explained her living situation in a house and a 
nearby trailer. The tribe's president said Blue Bird's Igloo 
neighborhood is typical of housing conditions on the reservation. 

</P>
<P>
	Nichols Seeks New Bombing Trial  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Terry Nichols' lawyers today asked for a new trial  
in the Oklahoma bombing, arguing that the government withheld FBI 
documents that could have helped his defense. Defense attorney 
Michael Tigar said there are 43,000 documents still hidden in FBI 
files. Prosecutors countered that they turned over 12,000 pertinent 
FBI files and that the others wouldn't have changed the verdict. 
Nichols, 44, is serving a life sentence for the 1995 bombing of a 
federal building that killed 168 people. 

</P>
<P>
	Cool Front Breaks Heat Wave  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Three days of broiling heat that killed 21  
people in the East and Midwest gave way to cooler weather today, 
bringing relief to hundreds of thousands of New York City residents 
who spent the night in a blackout. Consolidated Edison, the city's 
power utility, blamed the huge outage on massive use of air 
conditioners and fans. Most people had power restored by this 
afternoon. The heat spell brought wilting humidity and record 
temperatures over 100 degrees to many urban areas. 

</P>
<P>
	Feds Want Mercury Out of Vaccines  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government is about to ask manufacturers  
to remove from vaccines a type of mercury used as a preservative 
since the 1940s, citing concern that small infants now need so many 
immunizations that they may get too much of the chemical. Parents 
should not worry because the move concerning the preservative 
thimerosal is strictly a precaution, vaccine experts said. 

</P>
<P>
	Congo Cease-Fire Plan Approved  
</P>
<P>
	LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) -- African foreign and defense ministers  
signed a draft cease-fire plan today to end the 11-month-old civil 
war in Congo, a conflict that has drawn in soldiers from five 
countries and threatened stability in Central Africa. The agreement 
goes into effect 24 hours after it is signed, possibly next week, 
by heads of the six nations involved in the war, leaders of the 
three Congolese rebel groups and other regional and organizational 
leaders. 

</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! Posts Profit Increase  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Yahoo! Inc. reported second-quarter profits  
and revenues that easily beat Wall Street expectations today, 
helped by a sharp increase in visitors to its leading network of 
Web sites. Excluding the cost of buying Internet companies such as 
GeoCities, Yahoo! said it earned $28.3 million, or 11 cents a 
share, in the quarter ended June 30. Revenues soared 156 percent to 
$115.2 million from $45 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Closes at New High of 11,187.36  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks reached record territory today as the Dow  
Jones industrial average closed up 52.24 at 11,187.36. Declining 
issues on the New York Stock Exchange led advancers 1,693-1,279. 
The Nasdaq was up 6.31 to 2,743.09, also a record. 

</P>
<P>
	NL All-Star Reserves Selected  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The National League selected 16 first-time  
All-Stars today as their pitchers and reserves. Making their first 
appearance in the midsummer classic will be: Atlanta's Kevin 
Millwood and Brian Jordan; Houston's Jose Lima, Billy Wagner and 
Mike Hampton; Paul Byrd and Mike Lieberthal of Philadelphia; Dave 
Nilsson and Jeromy Burnitz of Milwaukee; St. Louis' Kent 
Bottenfield; Cincinnati's Sean Casey; Florida's Alex Gonzalez; San 
Francisco's Jeff Kent; Pittsburgh's Ed Sprague; Arizona's Luis 
Gonzalez; and Montreal's Vladimir Guerrero. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  
  	   	
</P>
