<HEADLINE> Wheat, Soybeans Up; Corn Mixed / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat and soybean futures prices edged higher  
early today on the Chicago Board of Trade, while corn futures were 
mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	Futures prices opened mixed as investors consolidated their  
positions following sharp losses a day earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans were expected to face continued pressure today  
from perceptions farmers will harvest bumper crops this fall 
following near-ideal growing weather. Those perceptions were 
reinforced by U.S. Agriculture Department weekly crop reports that 
showed more than 70 percent of both the corn and soybean crops 
nationwide were in good to excellent condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean prices now are hovering at 27-year lows, while corn  
prices have slipped to their lowest in nearly 12 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures were facing pressure from perceptions winter wheat  
harvest is picking up after weeks of rain-caused delays. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 3/4 cents to $2.63 3/4 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1/2 cent to $2.04 1/4 a bushel; December oats rose 1/2 
cent to $1.08 1/2 a bushel; November soybeans rose 1 cent to $4.22 1/2 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and pork bellies futures were mostly lower on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange, while lean hogs advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle fell .42 cent to 62.45 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .33 cent to 77.02 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs rose .35 cent to 44.85 cents a pound; August pork bellies fell 
.82 cent to 34.90 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
