<HEADLINE> Calif. Neighbors Chase Down Suspect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- A group of neighbors formed a human  
shield to try to stop a suspect in a fatal hit-and-run, then chased 
him in their cars and held him until police arrived. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said the car driven by Gerald Weirton, 36, allegedly  
struck 13-year-old Gabriel Allen Swenor as he was playing Sunday 
with friends on a dead-end street. The boy was thrown 20 to 30 feet 
and died. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time Weirton circled back to exit the street, a crowd of  
about 30 neighbors had formed a human shield, but the driver pushed 
his way through. One man who reached into the truck was dragged 
about two blocks before he fell from the vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	Neighbors hopped in their cars and followed the suspect. They  
finally surrounded him at a convenience store. 
</P>
<P>
	``He tried to run, but they grab him,'' police Lt. John Kane  
said. ``They sit on him and try to hold him there until police 
arrive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weirton was jailed on suspicion of hit-and-run, drunken driving  
and other offenses. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
