<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Barnesandnoble.com Selling Music </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In a race to keep pace with online rival  
Amazon.com, Barnesandnoble.com launched a music superstore today, 
including thousands of titles from artists ranging from pop 
sensation Ricky Martin to jazz legend Duke Ellington. 
</P>
<P>
	The music store will be part of barnesandnoble.com's newly  
redesigned bookselling Web site, which was also launched on 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the new music store, shoppers can choose from all types of  
music, including some harder to find categories, such as retro 
swing or Brazilian jazz. The store will also have a tremendous 
selection of classical music. 
</P>
<P>
	The store will contain more than 20,000 artist biographies, more  
than 50,000 music reviews and album ratings, as well as editorial 
suggestions on artists with similar music styles. 
</P>
<P>
	Barnesandnoble.com's move into music comes more than a year  
after Amazon.com added a vast music selection to its site and 
quickly became the leading music retailer on the Internet, toppling 
CDNow. 
</P>
<P>
	It also faces competition from Borders.com, which also sells  
music and books on its site, and traditional music retailers, such 
as Tower Records, which are moving into cyberspace. 
</P>
<P>
	Barnesandnoble.com did sell a small selection of music on its  
site before, but the new music store greatly expands its offerings. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not the first,'' said Jonathan Bulkeley, chief  
executive at barnesandnoble.com. ``But we aren't too late. This 
party will go on for the next 30 or 40 years ... if not longer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like many of its competitors, barnesandnoble.com will make songs  
available for downloading to home computers, although this will not 
be an important part of the site at first. This week, 
barnesandnoble.com will offer a previously unreleased live 
recording from Jewel for digital download to promote its new site. 
</P>
<P>
	Shoppers at the music store will also be able to find  
music-related books, sheet music, videos and magazines. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 14:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Football DT's Gift Made Into Film </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Daniel Huffman watches on the sidelines of a high  
school football field as movie stars film a scene in ``The Daniel 
Huffman Story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's way too strange,'' the Florida State student says.  
</P>
<P>
	Not many 20-year-olds have movies made about them. But not many  
did what Huffman did -- give up his football career by donating a 
kidney to his grandmother. 
</P>
<P>
	Huffman's act of love occurred three years ago. That was the  
summer before his senior year at high school in Rossville, Ill., 
the small town where his grandparents raised him following his 
parents' divorce. 
</P>
<P>
	His grandmother, Shirlee, badly needed a kidney transplant.  
There were fears she might die while waiting, perhaps more than a 
year for a suitable donated kidney. 
</P>
<P>
	So Daniel decided to make the donation himself, even though  
losing one of his two kidneys meant he would have to give up 
football and other contact sports forever. He was a starting 
defensive tackle on the Rossville team, and had to shelve plans to 
play in college. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, there's been a lot of good news for Huffman. His  
grandmother is now healthy, and he got a full scholarship to 
Florida State as a student trainer with the football team. That 
deal came thanks to Seminoles coach Bobby Bowden, who first heard 
Huffman's story when each of them was honored at a football awards 
ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Huffman is the subject of a movie being filmed in Toronto:  
``A Gift of Love: The Daniel Huffman Story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It is to be televised on the Showtime cable network this fall,  
although producer Daniel Paulson said it also might be released in 
movie theaters. 
</P>
<P>
	Paulson said he immediately envisioned a film after reading  
about Huffman's saga. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody is worried these days about young people and drugs  
and sex and violence, and President Clinton says Hollywood is not 
doing its part,'' Paulson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a movie that really goes against that grain -- it's a  
true profile in courage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Huffman is played by Elden Henson, one of the stars of the  
``Mighty Ducks'' movies. The grandmother is played by Debbie 
Reynolds, whose preparations included a visit to the Huffman home 
in Rossville that set the small town agog. 
</P>
<P>
	``My grandma was just completely thrilled,'' Huffman said.  
</P>
<P>
	Huffman was invited to the Toronto set this week, and has had a  
chance to meet Henson, Reynolds and others involved in the 
production. He and his fiance even were allowed to be extras in a 
scene showing fans watching a Rossville football game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm having a great time,'' Huffman said. ``Talking to the  
actors portraying your life -- it's unbelievable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He praised Henson's performance, offering just one  
tongue-in-cheek suggestions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe he should make the hits harder -- make me look mean.''  
</P>
<P>
	Also on hand was Bowden, who plays himself in the movie. He  
almost turned down the role to preserve his family's summer 
vacation, but decided he owed it to Huffman and to the school to 
participate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here's a kid -- he probably had a future in football, and he  
gave up his kidney for his grandmother,'' Bowden said. ``You don't 
see young people doing things like that -- I just never heard of 
anything more valiant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Huffman, who will be a junior this fall, said he enjoys his work  
with the Florida State team, which enables him to travel with the 
squad on road games. Bowden suggested Huffman might have a future 
as a professional sports trainer, but Huffman said he is enjoying 
being an English major and might have a try as a sports publicist. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the movie, Huffman hopes it moves those who see it.  
</P>
<P>
	``I hope it will make people think more about organ donation,''  
he said. ``They'll become more educated about it and sign organ 
donor cards.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He insists his act was not as heroic as his admirers contend.  
</P>
<P>
	``If you love someone and you can help them, any way you can,  
you're going to do it,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
