<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oakland Port Shut Down By Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Dock workers virtually closed down the  
Port of Oakland for a second day Wednesday, forcing cargo-laden 
ships to slow down across the Pacific Ocean or wait at anchor in 
San Francisco Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	Tractor-trailers also backed up for half a mile outside the  
port, which handles 33 shipping lines and 12 percent of West Coast 
shipping, as 1,400 dock workers stayed off the job over what they 
termed a safety issue. 
</P>
<P>
	The work stoppage delayed deliveries of everything from cotton  
and refrigerated fruit from California's farm regions to computer 
components from Silicon Valley to automobile parts from factories 
in the Midwest, a port spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have 11 ships that aren't being loaded or unloaded,'' port  
spokeswoman Roberta Bradley said Wednesday. At least four more lay 
at anchor in the bay, unable to unload cargo from Asia, Hawaii and 
the continental United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The port has been able to unload trucks onto the docks, so  
perishable cargo in refrigerated trucking containers was being 
hooked up to generators to prevent spoiling, Ms. Bradley said. 
</P>
<P>
	The work stoppage was spontaneous and not directed by union  
leaders negotiating a new West Coast contract with the Pacific 
Maritime Association, according to Steve Stallone, a spokesman for 
Local 10 of the International Longshore and Warehouse Union. But 
the union isn't about to tell its rank-and-file to return to the 
docks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not telling people to just go back to work, not 'til the  
dispute is settled,'' Stallone said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Longshore workers quit working Tuesday morning after the  
association refused their request to hire a second ``signalman'' to 
keep watch as the port's 12 massive cranes transfer trucking 
containers between tractor-trailers and the huge cargo vessels. 
</P>
<P>
	By all accounts, the work stoppage was limited to the Port of  
Oakland, although Stallone said longshore workers in Los Angeles 
and Long Beach were refusing to work overtime or during lunch in 
sympathy with the Oakland dock workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Dock work continued normally in San Diego, Seattle and Portland,  
Ore., said association spokesman Phil Resch. 
</P>
<P>
	A walkout could have a huge economic impact if it does spread,  
according to the PMA, which represents management at all West Coast 
ports. 
</P>
<P>
	An analysis by the Berkeley Roundtable on the International  
Economy concluded that a five-day shutdown of all West Coast ports 
would cost the national economy an estimated $3.9 billion and 
result in the loss of nearly 12,000 jobs. West Coast ports handle 
more than half of the containerized cargo moving in and out of the 
United States every year. 
</P>
<P>
	Resch said he thought the walkout would be limited to Oakland,  
however. 
</P>
<P>
	That's bad enough news for the local economy, Ms. Bradley said.  
``We're hoping that ships are not diverted from the Port of 
Oakland, because the port is a major economic engine for the whole 
Bay area,'' she said. ``We need those ships to get in here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Contract talks ended July 1 for the Fourth of July holiday, with  
an understanding they would resume this week. Resch said the 
association hasn't heard from the union since, but Stallone said 
union negotiators are studying the latest management offer. 
</P>
<P>
	That proposal includes a 32 percent boost in pension benefits to  
future retirees and a 15 percent raise for those currently retired. 
</P>
<P>
	Pay in 1998 averaged $99,000 for dock workers, $117,617 for  
clerks and $156,251 for foremen, according to the association. 
Stallone said these figures represent total employer costs, 
including taxes and benefits. He said actual salaries are far 
lower. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
