<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Critic Says IOC Ready To Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The International Olympic Committee ``seems  
committed to the process of reform'' after its worst scandal, a 
leading critic of the committee's operations said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Ken Duberstein, a former White House chief of staff and  
vice-chairman of an ethics inquiry that blasted IOC actions, said 
he came away from a recent meeting with committee leaders convinced 
of their intent to make meaningful changes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We felt reasonably comfortable, having listened to their words  
and looked into their eyes, that they were serious,'' he said in a 
telephone interview from his Washington office. 
</P>
<P>
	Duberstein's comments were the strongest so far in support of  
IOC reform measures from those who had criticized the committee in 
the wake of the million-dollar vote-buying scheme involved in Salt 
Lake City's winning bid for the 2002 Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	At a Senate Commerce Committee hearing on the scandal in April,  
Duberstein said the IOC's reaction to the Mitchell commission was 
``to say the least disappointing'' and ``raises serious doubts 
about the commitment to reform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, after initially repelling outside suggestions on ways of  
eliminating corrupt practices, the IOC appeared to now accept the 
seriousness of the problem and the need for independent help to fix 
the process and ``burnish their reputation,'' Duberstein said. 
</P>
<P>
	Duberstein and George Mitchell, the former Senate majority  
leader who headed the inquiry that found the IOC fostered a 
``culture of improper gift giving'' and blamed it for the scandal, 
met in London for 1 1/2 hours last weekend with the committee's top 
two leaders -- president Juan Antonio Samaranch and director general 
Francois Carrard. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a meeting I think they sought,'' Duberstein said,  
noting that he and Mitchell were in the area on other business 
while the IOC officials were in London for the Wimbledon finals. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the IOC described the meeting -- the first between  
the two factions -- as ``most constructive and very encouraging.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It also said that all of the Mitchell commission's  
recommendations, from selection of members to term limits to 
including more athletes, had been ``integrated into the reform 
process'' by IOC 2000, an 80-member commission due to recommend a 
new structure and code for the international committee by the end 
of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he agreed with the IOC's characterization, Duberstein  
said that Samaranch and Carrard had taken pains to go over the 
Mitchell report ``recommendation by recommendation, point by 
point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The senator and I came away encouraged that they are taking  
the need for reform seriously,'' he said. ``I really do think and 
the senator really does think that they seem committed to the 
process of reform. 
</P>
<P>
	``We encouraged them to keep on the path and to have the  
programs ready in the autumn. ... What we need to focus on is what 
the IOC does in the long run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	IOC 2000, whose members include former Secretary of State Henry  
Kissinger, is to make preliminary recommendations in September or 
October, with the full IOC acting on the proposed changes in 
December. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell has convinced congressional leaders to delay any action  
on measures to tie up the IOC's billion-dollar income from U.S. TV 
networks and sponsors until the IOC votes. Duberstein said that he 
could informally brief Sens. John McCain and Ted Stevens, the IOC's 
harshest critics on Capitol Hill, when Congress returns from a 
Fourth of July recess. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
