<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cos. Can Advertise Health Benefits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Starting Thursday, manufacturers of cereals  
and breads rich in whole grains can advertise that those foods help 
fight heart disease and cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Cereal maker General Mills asked the government to allow  
Cheerios, Total, Wheaties and other qualifying foods to advertise, 
on the food's package, that eating a diet high in whole-grain foods 
-- that also is low in fat -- may reduce the risk of heart disease 
and certain cancers. 
</P>
<P>
	Foods rich in dietary fiber already can make certain  
disease-fighting health claims. But General Mills cited a 1989 
conclusion by the National Academy of Sciences that whole grains 
mix other important nutrients with fiber to be disease-fighting, 
too. 
</P>
<P>
	The Food and Drug Administration accepted that conclusion, so  
beginning Thursday General Mills and any other maker of a whole 
grain-rich food can start advertising the benefit. 
</P>
<P>
	To qualify, a food must contain 51 percent or more whole grain  
ingredients by weight. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, only 7 percent of Americans eat the three servings of  
whole grain a day recommended for optimal nutrition, General Mills 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company cited a recent survey showing consumer confusion  
over just what constitutes whole grain, and cautioned that just 
because a bread looks dark doesn't mean it qualifies. Check the 
label -- the first ingredient listed should be a whole grain, such 
as ``whole grain oats,'' ``whole grain wheat'' or ``whole wheat.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 03:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boston Politicians Wish King Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Two Massachusetts politicians teamed up to send  
their best wishes to a fellow Red Sox fan -- Stephen King. 
</P>
<P>
	King, recovering from injuries he suffered after being struck by  
a van last month, won't be able to make it to Fenway Park for the 
All-Star Game on July 13. 
</P>
<P>
	So Gov. Paul Cellucci and Boston Mayor Thomas M. Menino on  
Tuesday signed a giant get-well card for King, a season ticket 
holder, at the Boston Public Library. 
</P>
<P>
	King is a rabid Red Sox fan who combined his two interests in  
his latest scary story, ``The Girl Who Loved Tom Gordon,'' a 
reference to the baseball team's ace relief pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all love Tom Gordon,'' Menino wrote on the giant Styrofoam  
card, which will remain at the library for members of the public to 
sign for at least a few more weeks. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
