<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Touring New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DAVENPORT, N.Y. (AP) -- Greeted by competing sides telling  
her to ``go home Hillary'' or ``you go girl,'' prospective Senate 
candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton began her first full-scale 
campaign tour into New York today. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton has been to New York a dozen times this year as the  
nation's first lady, but today's trip was her first since formally 
declaring that she is considering making the Senate race. 
</P>
<P>
	For her first official campaign appearance, Mrs. Clinton chose  
the homestead of the man she hopes to succeed, Sen. Daniel Patrick 
Moynihan. It is the first stop on what aides describe as a 
summerlong ``listening tour'' of the state. 
</P>
<P>
	At her arrival at the Binghamton Airport, Mrs. Clinton was  
greeted by about 50 supporters, including state Democratic 
Chairwoman Judith Hope and former state Democratic Chairman John 
Burns. Outside the airport, about three dozen supporters waved 
placards while farther along the road a tractor-trailer carried a 
sign that read ``go home Hillary'' in large letters. 
</P>
<P>
	Her aides said Mrs. Clinton, the first-ever first lady to seek  
public office, hopes to blunt charges she is a political 
carpetbagger, having never lived or worked in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Witno fanfare, Mrs. Clinton's campaign on Tuesday filed a single  
page with the Federal Election Commission in Washington, declaring 
that she had formed a committee to explore a Senate race. That 
enables her to raise and spend money for political travel, polling 
and advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	Moynihan's decision to retire after 24 years in the Senate  
cleared the way for her Senate bid. 
</P>
<P>
	The race to replace Moynihan is being eyed on the Republican  
side by New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and two congressmen 
from Long Island, Rick Lazio and Peter King. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani formed a Senate exploratory committee in April.  
</P>
<P>
	Relations between the Clinton administration and Moynihan have  
not always been warm. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, Moynihan became the first Senate Democrat to call for  
appointment of an independent prosecutor to investigate President 
and Mrs. Clinton's involvement in the Whitewater real estate 
venture. Two years later, while criticizing the president's backing 
of welfare reform legislation, the senator said ``the current batch 
in the White House ... have only the flimsiest grasp of social 
reality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's decision to visit the Moynihan homestead brought  
a flurry of activity to the normally placid place. Workmen 
constructed an outdoor platform to hold the more than 200 reporters 
and television crews, some from as far away as Asia and Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, we're cleaning out the barn in case it rains tomorrow  
... It's full of pigeon guano,'' the senator's wife, Liz, said on 
the eve of Mrs. Clinton's arrival. 
</P>
<P>
	``It'll be better on Thursday,'' she added wearily.  
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's four-day swing through eastern and central New  
York, a traditional GOP stronghold, has generated enthusiasm from 
many Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans were poking fun.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's the `I'm-not-a-carpetbagger tour,''' veteran New York GOP  
strategist Jay Severin proclaimed. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent independent polls, showing Mrs. Clinton either trailing  
or tied with Giuliani, indicate her political team has its work cut 
out for it. 
</P>
<P>
	A June poll from the Quinnipiac College Polling Institute found  
that 53 percent of registered voters statewide do not believe Mrs. 
Clinton understands the issues and problems facing New York, up 
from 43 percent in a March poll from the Hamden, Conn.-based 
institute. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans, including Giuliani, have been making much of the  
fact that Mrs. Clinton is an outsider. 
</P>
<P>
	State Assembly Majority Leader Michael Bragman, a Syracuse-area  
Democrat helping arrange Mrs. Clinton's four-day New York trip this 
week, said he has told her that it will be a very difficult race in 
large part because of the carpetbagger issue. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
