<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- A strike by tens of thousands of  
truckers entered its third day Wednesday, snaring traffic on key 
highways across Argentina. 
</P>
<P>
	Government security forces helped working truckers circumvent  
the job action by more than 200,000 unionized truck drivers, who 
are protesting a new tax on automobiles, boats and aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	Striking truckers idled their vehicles in long columns alongside  
national highways. Although the trucks did not block those routes, 
Interior Minister Carlos Corach complained that the strikers were 
slowing traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	Truckers complain that the new tax -- to raise $700 million for  
much-needed increases in teachers' salaries -- amounts to thousands 
of dollars in added levies on their vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Truckers have said the strike, originally scheduled to end late  
Wednesday, could go on until the tax was lifted. 
</P>
<P>
	In Buenos Aires, the government's national security council met  
on the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, ruling party lawmakers in the lower house of  
congress debated proposals for drastically cutting back the new tax 
or finding an exemption for the truckers. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- Brazil has softened its opposition to a  
two-year coffee export plan aimed at keeping prices up, producers 
said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil agreed to discuss the two-year program with other members  
of the Association of Coffee Producing Countries, which is meeting 
in the capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Details of the plan were not released. Earlier, Brazil had  
pushed to maintain one-year export targets. The plan can hardly 
work without Brazil, the world's No. 1 producer and exporter of 
coffee. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1998-99 coffee year that ended in June, members agreed to  
limit coffee exports to 51 million 132-pound bags, with Brazil 
exporting 15 million. But with a bumper harvest of 34.6 million 
bags, Brazil actually shipped a record 21 million bags. 
</P>
<P>
	For the current year, Brazil's share of exports is expected to  
remain at 15 million bags, even though its harvest shrank to 24.8 
million bags. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico's governing party has put $6.1 million  
spending limit on the four candidates for its first-ever 
presidential primary -- but will not punish candidates who violate 
the limits, Mexican media reported Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission overseeing the primary process for the  
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, set limits of $4.7 
million in monetary contributions and 13 million pesos $1.4 million 
for other donations. 
</P>
<P>
	The party won't limit the amount an individual can contribute,  
but will require that the candidates report the information. 
</P>
<P>
	The PRI, which has governed Mexico for its entire 70-year  
history, will select its nominee for the 2000 presidential election 
in a November primary. Previously, PRI candidates were selected by 
the outgoing president. 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition parties have accused the PRI of greatly exceeding  
spending limits in the 1994 presidential election. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- A hospital in southeastern Brazil said  
Wednesday it may have erroneously informed more than 100 people 
that they had AIDS after it discovered that five of them were not 
infected with the deadly HIV virus. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hospital das Clinicas in Belo Horizonte, 340 miles northeast  
of Sao Paulo, said of the 540 people that tested positive between 
August 1998 and May 1999, 120 may not be infected at all. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinical director, Dr. Henrique Gama Torres said the results of  
the other 420 who tested positive in earlier tests at the hospital 
or in independent labs, ``were reconfirmed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torres said HIV positive and healthy blood samples may have been  
mixed together in the lab due to human error. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) -- A Dallas man has abandoned his  
second attempt to make a 3,100-mile trip to Hawaii on a wooden 
raft, after the raft was unable to withstand bad weather. 
</P>
<P>
	A four-man crew led by John Haslett of Dallas left Friday night  
from Costa Rica's Pacific coast in an attempt to trace a route 
believed to have been used by a pre-Columbian tribe. 
</P>
<P>
	``After a night of heavy storms, the raft was forced onto a  
rocky reef and was destroyed,'' Haslett's wife, Annie, told The 
Associated Press in an e-mail message Tuesday. ``With no finances 
and time left in the schedules of the crew, the expedition has been 
called off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 46-foot raft, named ``La Endurancia'', was made of balsa  
wood, bamboo, hemp strands and two canvas sails. It was a close 
replica to that used by the Mantenos, a little-known tribe dating 
back to 500 B.C. that lived in what is now Ecuador. Some scholars 
believe that the Mantenos had a maritime empire that traded with 
the Aztecs in Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Haslett was inspired by Thor Heyerdahl, the Norwegian  
ethnographer who described his 1947 raft crossing from Peru to 
Polynesia in the book ``Kon Tiki.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
