<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fleet Meeting Draws Hundreds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Lunita Mustafa burst into tears as she spoke of  
her fear that the acquisition of BankBoston by Fleet would result 
in a megabank uninterested in providing services to people in 
low-income neighborhoods. 
</P>
<P>
	Rarely does a discussion of banking inspire such emotion, but  
Mustafa worries a decline in low-income mortgages would cut the 
number of homeowners working to keep her neighborhood safe and 
vibrant. Crime and violence can plague neighborhoods of renters who 
don't live in one place long enough to take pride in it, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Five years ago there was a wild beast in our community and it  
was devouring our children,'' said Mustafa, of Boston's Mattapan 
neighborhood. ``Today, I hear they're going to unleash that beast 
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mustafa joined hundreds of homeowners, politicians and activists  
Wednesday who expressed their concerns to the Federal Reserve Board 
about the possible repercussions of the proposed merger between 
Fleet Financial Group Inc. and BankBoston Corp., which would create 
the nation's eighth-largest bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the most vocal critics of the merger accused Fleet, in  
particular, of having a lackluster track record of lending in 
low-income areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Connecticut Treasurer Denise L. Nappier said that in the wake of  
Fleet's 1995 acquisition of Shawmut National Corp., loans to low- 
and moderate-income borrowers in her state have been halved. 
</P>
<P>
	She also noted that many of the branches the banks plan to sell  
off to meet antitrust requirements are in poor neighborhoods, and 
she worried that some could be closed down. 
</P>
<P>
	And the attorneys general of Massachusetts and Connecticut told  
the board they were concerned the combined company, to be known as 
Fleet Boston, would stifle competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``This proposed merger would create a behemoth,'' said  
Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal, who spoke of the 
deal's ``enormous peril and threat to competition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bank executives said the $16 billion deal was prompted by a  
desire to maintain a New England-controlled bank in a rapidly 
consolidating industry. They said combining the two banks would 
reduce costs and lead to better service. 
</P>
<P>
	``By increasing in size, banks achieve the economies of scale  
that allow us to invest more in technology and people, so that we 
can develop superior products and services,'' said Terry Murray, 
chairman and chief executive officer of Fleet Financial Group. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank officials also pointed to a program they say will put $14.6  
billion into neighborhoods over five years, mostly through small 
business lending, affordable housing and community development 
lending programs in the seven states where the combined bank would 
do business. 
</P>
<P>
	The two banks currently have a total of 1,625 branches in  
Massachusetts, Connecticut, Rhode Island, Maine, New Hampshire, New 
York and New Jersey. The two banks plan to sell 292 New England 
branches to comply with federal antitrust requirements. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
