<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cool Front Breaks Heat Wave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Three days of broiling heat that killed 23  
people in the East and Midwest gave way to cooler weather 
Wednesday, bringing relief to hundreds of thousands of New York 
City residents who spent the night in a blackout. 
</P>
<P>
	Consolidated Edison, the city's power utility, blamed the huge  
outage on massive use of air conditioners and fans. Most people had 
power restored by Wednesday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-day heat spell, beginning Sunday, brought wilting  
humidity and record temperatures over 100 degrees to many urban 
areas. A cold front finally brought lower temperatures to much of 
the region. Temperatures in Concord, N.H., dropped 19 degrees in 
just four minutes when the front arrived there. 
</P>
<P>
	The front reached New York during the night, reducing the city's  
high on Wednesday afternoon to 91 degrees with 27 percent humidity. 
The day before, the thermometer hit a record 101 and nearly double 
the humidity. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten deaths in New York City were blamed on the weather.  
Pennsylvania listed seven heat-related deaths, New Jersey four, and 
Illinois two. 
</P>
<P>
	As utilities reported scattered blackouts in the East, Con Ed  
shut off the power to upper Manhattan late Tuesday after 
high-voltage cables burned out and a small fire damaged a 
substation. The move plunged the area in darkness and robbed people 
of their ability to keep cool. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Rudolph Giuliani jumped on Con Ed, accusing it of not  
being prepared for the emergency and threatening to sue for the 
cost of the 500 police officers sent to patrol against looting. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in an age of high technology. We're a city that has  
predictably high usage of electricity in warm weather,'' Giuliani 
said. ``I mean everybody can figure that out, right?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of people slept outside, on fire escapes and sidewalks,  
because their apartments were too hot. 
</P>
<P>
	Police reported just nine arrests and only a handful of stores  
broken into, in contrast to the widespread looting and arson during 
the citywide blackout in 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	Many stores in the area blacked out Tuesday night were unable to  
open Wednesday, and many lost perishable merchandise. 
</P>
<P>
	At a grocery called La Mundial, chickens thawed quickly as the  
temperature topped 70 degrees in the basement freezer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to lose all the meat,'' said Reso Infante, manager  
of La Mundial. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers also saw big losses.  
</P>
<P>
	At Seaford, Del., Allen Family Foods Inc. lost 33,000 chickens  
from Saturday through Monday, said Tom David, director of live 
operations. The company has more than 20 million birds in the field 
at any one time. 
</P>
<P>
	Salisbury, Md.,-based Perdue Farms Inc., which bills itself as  
the nation's third-largest poultry producer, said it had not 
tallied its losses. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the area's growers produced more than 600 million birds  
last year and it would take a loss of millions of birds to affect 
the price of poultry, said Bill Satterfield, executive director of 
the Delmarva Poultry Industry Inc in Georgetown, Del. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
