<HEADLINE> Lott Holds Up Holbrooke Nomination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott himself is  
among three senators now blocking the long-delayed nomination of 
Richard Holbrooke to be U.N. ambassador, congressional and 
administration officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott and Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., are doing it secretly,  
said the officials, speaking on the condition of anonymity. Sen. 
Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, is the third, but he announced his 
``hold'' on the veteran diplomat's nomination late last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott, R-Miss., and McConnell are using the delaying technique to  
apply pressure on the White House to nominate an Ohio law professor 
for a position on the Federal Election Commission, said the 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The professor, Bradley A. Smith of Capital University in  
Columbus, had been recommended by Republican Senate leaders for a 
Republican vacancy on the commission, which is evenly divided 
between Democrats and Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Traditionally, their recommendation likely would be accepted.  
But Common Cause and other public-interest groups have waged a 
campaign to persuade President Clinton not to make the nomination, 
saying Smith's writings demonstrate hostility to campaign-finance 
laws he would be sworn to uphold. 
</P>
<P>
	McConnell is chairman of the Senate GOP committee that helps  
elect Republicans to the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesmen for neither Lott nor McConnell could be reached today  
for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott said last week said that Holbrooke's nomination ``has some  
problems right now,'' and his spokesman, John Czwartacki, cited 
``irreconcilable holds'' on the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	However, until now, only the identity of Grassley had been known  
among those blocking the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	By Senate tradition, any senator can block a nomination, at  
least temporarily, by putting a ``hold'' on it, which can be 
anonymous. 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley, who has sought to overhaul that practice by requiring  
senators to announce such holds publicly, is blocking the 
nomination for a different reason. He contends that a government 
official who worked at the U.N. mission in New York was demoted and 
transferred to a lesser job in Washington in retaliation for her 
telling members of Congress about waste and inefficiency at the 
United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department has said that the official, Linda Shenwick,  
was reassigned because of unsatisfactory job performance, not 
because she was a whistle-blower. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for Grassley, Jill Kozeny, said today that  
``nothing has changed'' and that the Grassley hold remains. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``holds'' are just the latest obstacles in the course of  
Holbrooke's more than yearlong effort to win confirmation. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of that delay was caused by the administration's own ethics  
background investigations into Holbrooke. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke was approved last week by the Senate Foreign Relations  
Committee. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
