<HEADLINE> Wheat, Soybeans Up; Corn Mostly Off / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat and soybean futures advanced Wednesday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade, while corn futures finished mostly 
lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat and soybeans bounced higher, recovering from sharp losses  
a day earlier, as investors consolidated their positions. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans are expected to face continued downward pressure in  
coming days, however, from expectations for a bumper crop. The 
government already is predicting this year's production will set a 
new record, but some agronomists are predicting the near-ideal 
growing weather will boost that figure even more. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures saw light buying despite continued harvesting of  
the winter wheat crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures succumbed, however, after the U.S. Agriculture  
Department reported 77 percent of the nation's crop was in good to 
excellent condition as of last week. That's up from the 66 percent 
reported at this time a year ago, which helped reinforce 
perceptions that fall production will be larger than originally 
estimated. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers also were reporting phenomenal growth and few pest  
problems in Illinois and Iowa, the two largest corn-growing states. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for September delivery rose 2 cents to $2.49 1/4 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1/2 cent to $2.04 1/4 a bushel; December oats rose 1 
cent to $1.09 a bushel; November soybeans rose 1 cent to $4.22 1/2 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while  
pork futures advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle fell .52 cent to 62.35 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .53 cent to 76.82 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs rose 2 cents to 46.50 cents a pound; August pork bellies rose 
1.25 cents to 36.97 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
