<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yahoo! Posts Profit Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Yahoo! Inc. reported second-quarter profits  
and revenues that easily beat Wall Street expectations on 
Wednesday, helped by a sharp increase in visitors to its leading 
network of Web sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding the cost of buying Internet companies such as  
GeoCities, Yahoo! said it earned $28.3 million, or 11 cents a 
share, in the quarter ended June 30. That was up from a profit of 
$1.5 million, or 1 cent a share, in the second quarter of 1998, 
also excluding one-time charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues soared 156 percent to $115.2 million from $45 million.  
</P>
<P>
	The results easily beat the 8-cents-a-share profit and $103  
million revenue forecast by Wall Street analysts. 
</P>
<P>
	Including the expense of acquisitions, the Santa Clara,  
Calif.-based Yahoo! lost $15 million, up slightly from the $14.3 
million it lost in the same period the year before. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were pleasantly surprised,'' said Tim Koogle, company chief  
executive officer. His explanation was simple: ``We've got a big 
audience and they're consuming a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But few investors seemed to care about red ink at Yahoo!, whose  
market cap totals $34.1 billion. In after-hours trading, Yahoo!'s 
stock rose to $172.75, up from $167.08 1/4 at the close of the Nasdaq 
Stock Market. Yahoo! stock had fallen $8.06 1/4, or 5 percent, in 
profit-taking ahead of the report. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo's earnings reflected exponential growth at the company.  
Excluding one-time charges, net income for the first six months of 
1999 was $48.2 million, or 18 cents a share, up from $1 million, or 
zero cents a share, for the same period in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, more than 80 million people visited the Yahoo! network  
of Web sites. Combined traffic on Yahoo!'s network increased to an 
average of 310 million page views per day, up from 235 million in 
March 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo!, whose network of sites is the most frequently visited,  
features everything from chat rooms to news and search services. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
