<DOCNO> APW19990707.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 19:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Committee Proposes $113M in Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The Olympic host city won't be dressed up  
with banners, and athletes won't have a game room after $113 
million in budget cuts to be proposed Thursday by the Salt Lake 
Organizing Committee's staff. 
</P>
<P>
	President Mitt Romney and chief operating officer Fraser Bullock  
said they'll ask the board's management committee to whack nearly 8 
percent from the $1.43 billion budget for the 2002 Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	It would mean that a $300 million shortfall in funding, made  
worse by this year's Olympic scandal, would be trimmed to $187 
million. ``We believe it's achievable,'' Bullock told the SLOC 
finance committee Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Olympic organizers are going after corporate sponsors as well as  
donors to make up the difference. 
</P>
<P>
	The cuts will be proposed in a management committee meeting  
Thursday but not voted on until September. The new budget would be 
$1.34 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're confident we're not going to be leaving unpaid bills for  
taxpayers or anyone else,'' Romney said during a press conference 
Wednesday. ``We're back on track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed cuts -- more drastic than $84 million in cuts Romney  
proposed after just a few weeks on the job last spring -- stem from 
a dollar-by-dollar analysis of the budget, Bullock said. He joined 
the SLOC in April and also is chief financial officer. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea, Bullock said, was to slice everything out of the  
budget not necessary to putting on great games for the athletes and 
leaving a legacy for Utah's youth. 
</P>
<P>
	SLOC's managers actually are proposing $169 million in cuts, but  
$56 million of those are offset by added costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of that was mistakes in the original budget written last  
year, but it also includes unforeseen expenses like $5 million in 
legal expenses because of the U.S. Justice Department's 
investigation of Salt Lake's bid committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Executives of the bid committee, the predecessor to the SLOC,  
have been accused of spending lavishly on International Olympic 
Committee members during the city's quest for the games, sparking 
scandal and now reform in the Olympic world. The Justice Department 
has been investigating for more than seven months but has brought 
no criminal charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The executives also have tagged $72 million of the $113 million  
in proposed cuts as expenses they'd like to restore if the money 
can be found. The budget keeps a $136 million contingency in case 
expenses are higher than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed cutbacks are diverse.  
</P>
<P>
	There would be no information booths for spectators unless some  
group in the community steps forward, and the SLOC would spend $5 
million less on opening, closing and other ceremonies. 
</P>
<P>
	The SLOC would cut $2.3 million out of its budget for housing  
games officials, including a portion of IOC members' rooms, and 
$300,000 out of the opening IOC session before the games. 
</P>
<P>
	Although an uproar from athletes caused Romney to back off from  
his earlier suggestion that the Utah Winter Sports Park be closed 
at long stretches before the Olympics, the park will skip building 
renovations and equipment purchases to save more than $3 million. 
The committee is scheduled to buy the park from the state July 14. 
</P>
<P>
	The SLOC will make only what publications are required under the  
host city contract, and those will be in black and white, Bullock 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of test events -- athletic contests that give staffers  
a chance to practice -- will be cut from 56 to 52, and the full 
staff, including volunteers, will work at only 17 of those, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee hopes to save marketing costs by selling tickets  
via the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Only those employees who really need to learn from the 2002  
Sydney, Australia games will attend, and when members of the 
Olympic community come to Utah, they can expect fewer dinners. 
</P>
<P>
	Bullock said the budget analysis has been good for pinpointing  
ways money doesn't need to be spent. For example, $5.4 million is 
proposed to be cut from the telecommunications budget, in part 
because a sponsor donated excess cellular phones that bus drivers 
can use rather than radios. 
</P>
<P>
	An expensive and sophisticated software program for tracking  
personnel, which has failed at two prior games, can be replaced 
with off-the-shelf business software, Bullock said. ``I said, 
`simplify, simplify, simplify.''' 
</P>
<P>
	More than half of the cuts are proposed in two areas: getting  
rid of $38 million worth of inflation cushion and saving $30 
million in staff expenses, essentially 18 percent of what was 
budgeted. 
</P>
<P>
	Bullock said the committee hasn't yet put a number on the  
proposed staff size, since volunteers -- many of them executives on 
loan -- will replace workers and some of the savings comes in hiring 
people later than planned. The SLOC had expected to employ 750 when 
the games opened. 
</P>
<P>
	On the revenue side, Bullock said staff is considering selling  
more tickets. At present, 55 percent of the 1.6 million event 
tickets will be up for sale after the world's Olympic community and 
media use 45 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Though opening ceremony tickets will be steeply priced, 70  
percent of the tickets will be $100 or less, Bullock said. 
</P>
<P>
	And each night, the medals ceremony will be free.  
</P>
<P>
	``When we looked at the budget, we said, `Let's make sure we  
allow the citizens of Utah to participate,''' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 16:20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers Re-sign Broadcast Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Los Angeles Lakers coaches and players and  
even the team owners have changed over the years, but the NBA team 
has had one constant for 34 years -- the voice in the broadcast 
booth. 
</P>
<P>
	Chick Hearn, 82, signed a new two-year contract Wednesday and  
will build on his amazing streak of having called 3,114 consecutive 
Lakers games. 
</P>
<P>
	Hearn is a member of both the Basketball Hall of Fame and the  
American Sportscasters Hall of Fame. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
