<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Insurance Catastrophe Claims Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- U.S. property/casualty insurers will pay about  
$3.25 billion to homeowners and businesses for property losses from 
13 catastrophic events in the second quarter of 1999, down from 
$4.5 billion for 16 catastrophic events in the same period a year 
ago, an industry group reported Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the industry's catastrophic losses in the second quarter  
stemmed from deadly tornadoes and tropical storms that moved 
through Oklahoma and 17 other states in early May, said Insurance 
Services Office Inc.'s Property Claims Services unit. Those storms 
cost $1.5 billion in property damage. Oklahoma sustained the 
biggest loss -- about $955 million. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first half of 1999, the insurance industry has paid  
about $5.1 billion on about 2.1 million claims for 18 catastrophic 
events, according to Insurance Services. That's about $460 million 
less than the $5.5 billion in losses in the first half of 1998. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
