<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N. American BMW Head Joining Ford </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Victor Doolan, president of BMW of North America  
Inc., will resign at month's end to join a former BMW AG colleague 
who's overseeing Ford Motor Co.'s new luxury car group. 
</P>
<P>
	Doolan, 58, has been in charge of the German automaker's sales,  
distribution and marketing activities in the United States since 
1993. He announced his resignation Wednesday and Ford confirmed a 
short time later that he would join the world's No. 2 automaker. 
</P>
<P>
	He was hired away by Wolfgang Reitzle, the former product  
development chief at BMW AG who joined Ford to run its premier 
automotive group in March. The unit is in charge of Ford's luxury 
brands: Lincoln, Jaguar, Volvo and Aston Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford said Doolan's title will be executive director of North  
American marketing and distribution strategy. Spokesman John 
Spelich said he did not know where Doolan would be based. 
</P>
<P>
	BMW of North America said in a brief statement that Tom Purves,  
chairman and chief executive of BMW US Holding Corp., will serve as 
interim president until a successor is named for Doolan. 
</P>
<P>
	The maker of high-performance sports and luxury cars has seen  
its U.S. sales double since Doolan was named president. Last week 
it reported its best first half ever, with sales up 17 percent over 
the first six months of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Reitzle left BMW earlier this year in a management shakeup that  
also resulted in then-chairman Bernd Pischetsrieder's ouster. 
Reitzle had been considered Pischetsrieder's heir apparent at the 
German automaker. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford president Jac Nasser has been bringing in more outside  
executive talent to Ford as it tries to strengthen its No. 2 
position worldwide and challenge the leadership of General Motors 
Corp. Like the other U.S.-based auto companies, Ford traditionally 
had promoted from within. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
