<HEADLINE> Islanders Sign Two Players </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP) -- The New York Islanders signed free agent  
defenseman Jamie Heward and center Chris Ferraro on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Heward, who played for the Nashville Predators last season,  
finished with six goals and 12 assists in 63 games. Four of his six 
goals came on the power play. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got a terrific shot and will see some power play time,''  
Islanders general manager Mike Milbury said. ``He'll be a nice 
complement to our defensive unit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Heward played 25 games for Toronto (1-4-5), and was in the  
Philadelphia Flyers' farm system when he was chosen by the 
Predators in the expansion draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferraro, who grew up on Long Island, played for Edmonton's farm  
team in Hamilton, Ontario, last season and led the team in goals 
(35), points (76) and game-winning goals (nine). The 26-year-old 
also played two games with Edmonton and scored a goal. Previously, 
Ferraro played for the New York Rangers and Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the deals were not disclosed.  
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, I feel like the luckiest person alive,'' Ferraro, a  
draft pick of the Rangers in 1991, said. ``I was an Islander fan 
growing up, watching the Mike Bossys, the Bryan Trottiers, the 
Billy Smiths, the Denis Potvins ... and the Butch Gorings, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goring is the Islanders new coach.  
  	   	
</P>
