<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 15:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Plunges Into N.Y. Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DAVENPORT, N.Y. (AP) -- Plunging into her race for the  
Senate, Hillary Rodham Clinton brushed aside criticism Wednesday 
that she is a carpetbagger in New York. ``What I am for is maybe as 
important, if not more important, than where I am from,'' the first 
lady said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton said New Yorkers had some ``very legitimate  
questions'' about what she believes in and the skills and interests 
she would bring to the job. And she said she would address them. 
</P>
<P>
	She pledged that she would be a ``strong and effective advocate  
on behalf of the people of New York.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the first question she was asked about a specifically New  
York issue -- a trade-related query about a new bridge between New 
York and Canada -- she deferred to retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick 
Moynihan, her host for the campaign kickoff and the man she hopes 
to succeed. ``Well, I'm going to let the expert speak on that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He answered briefly that the issue was being reviewed.  
</P>
<P>
	While Moynihan has often been at odds with the Clinton  
administration, he wholeheartedly endorsed Mrs. Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope she will go all the way,'' he said, after giving the  
first lady a tour of the schoolhouse office on his family farm. ``I 
mean to go all the way with her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton created an exploratory committee on Tuesday that  
allows her to raise and spend money for a campaign for the 
Democratic Senate nomination in New York. Advisers don't expect her 
to formally declare her candidacy until September, at the earliest. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton is expected to be unopposed in her quest for the  
Democratic nomination. On the Republican side, the Senate seat is 
being eyed by New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and two 
congressmen from Long Island, Rick Lazio and Peter King. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent polls show Mrs. Clinton tied with or trailing Giuliani.  
</P>
<P>
	Asked to respond to Mrs. Clinton's remarks, the mayor said, ``It  
doesn't make sense for me to respond to someone exploring and 
listening and announcing that they're going to explain to us at 
some point in the future what they're for. When she explains what 
she's for and if I'm running against her then I will respond to 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added: ``Everybody in the city and state knows what I'm  
for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton is the first first lady to seek elected office. Her  
exploratory committee will pay for her campaign travel, including 
reimbursing the federal government for use of aircraft. However, 
Mrs. Clinton will continue to get taxpayer-funded Secret Service 
protection. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked how she could run for office and fulfill her duties as  
first lady, she said, ``It is not so dissimilar from someone, for 
example, being in Congress and running for the Senate, or being a 
governor and running for another office.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three senators, one House member and one governor are running  
for president this time. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton, on a poverty tour, called the first lady  
after her news conference to ask about her campaign debut and to 
wish her well, her aides said. 
</P>
<P>
	At a 1 1/2-hour education event at the State University of New York  
at Oneonta, Mrs. Clinton called for civility in politics. ``When 
people are debating issues where the pressure is to scream and 
insult that is a real turn-off for most citizens,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think she's off to a great start,'' said Sheila Simon, an  
employee at SUNY-Oneonta who was carrying a sign reading 'New York 
needs a first lady.' 
</P>
<P>
	Democrat Jennifer Chase of Oneonta said she wouldn't vote for  
Mrs. Clinton. ``I don't think she should be senator from a state 
she's never lived in. She should go back to Arkansas and maybe run 
for senator there,'' she said. ``She obviously has family problems 
and ought to take care of those.'' 
</P>
<P>
	From Mrs. Clinton's arrival at the Binghamton airport Wednesday  
through a host of stops, she felt firsthand the strong emotions her 
candidacy is generating in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the Binghamton airport, about three dozen supporters  
waved placards. Spotting them and, emulating her husband's campaign 
style, she stopped her eight-vehicle motorcade to wade into the 
crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	At her campaign stops, some demonstrators carried signs or  
chanted, ``Go home, Hillary.'' Supporters yelled, ``Run, Hillary, 
run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton appeared relaxed and at ease.  
</P>
<P>
	She said she thought the carpetbagger question, raised by  
Republicans including Giuliani because she has never lived or 
worked in New York, was a fair one. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I have some real work to do to get out and listen and  
learn from the people of New York and demonstrate that what I'm for 
is maybe as important, if not more important, than where I'm 
from,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she planned to spend the next months listening to New  
Yorkers to learn more about the issues important to the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them, she said, were providing ``good quality'' education  
and health care and ``making sure the economy is built in a way 
that creates good jobs in every region in the state of New York.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A June poll from the Quinnipiac College Polling Institute found  
that 53 percent of registered voters statewide do not believe Mrs. 
Clinton understands the issues and problems facing New York, up 
from 43 percent in a March poll from the Hamden, Conn.-based 
institute. 
</P>
<P>
	Moynihan and Mrs. Clinton delivered their remarks to more than  
200 reporters and cameramen gathered at his farm. More than 30 
television crews recorded the event staged amid the rolling hills 
outside Oneonta. 
</P>
<P>
	She was questioned about some of the investigations that have  
plagued the Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	On Whitewater, she said, ``I think that New Yorkers will make  
their own judgments about that. I think we've moved beyond all of 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She sidestepped a question, however, about whether she sees  
herself as a victim of the Monica Lewinsky scandal and whether she 
would benefit from a sympathy vote. ``I'm looking forward to 
meeting with New Yorkers, and I think they'll have a lot to tell me 
about what they think about me and the positions that I have.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 10:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cool Front Breaks Heat Wave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- More than half a day after the lights went out  
and air conditioners quit, 200,000 Manhattan residents waited today 
for the end of a blackout that struck during a record heat wave 
blamed for more than a dozen deaths around the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though a cold front had brought relief from the sweaty  
misery across the Midwest and Northeast, other New York City 
neighborhoods were in danger of blackouts today, Consolidated 
Edison warned. Police headquarters had to briefly use backup 
generators. 
</P>
<P>
	Record high temperatures and power demands were set again  
Tuesday in the mid-Atlantic and Northeast as utilities scrambled to 
keep electricity flowing around flaming transformers and melting 
power lines. 
</P>
<P>
	``It feels like somebody's thrown buckets of hot water in your  
face,'' said Pat Renaghan, an elevator operator in a subway station 
at 168th Street in New York City. ``Sometimes when you take the 
elevator down, the air feels so thick you feel like you could chew 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For today, highs only in the 70s and 80s were forecast in much  
of New England and in the 90s farther south. Con Ed reported an 
all-time record demand for power in the New York City area on 
Tuesday at 11,850 megawatts. 
</P>
<P>
	People slept outside in the streets in parts of upper Manhattan  
because a widespread blackout left them with no way to ventilate 
their apartments. 
</P>
<P>
	``People stayed outside until dawn,'' said resident Winton  
Nunez, 35. ``It was impossible to stay indoors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That blackout affected about 68,000 business and residential  
customers above 155th Street in Manhattan -- an area of about 250 
blocks with some 200,000 residents, Con Edison spokesman Joe Petta 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, damaged feeder cables meant that three other  
sections of the city, including Manhattan's Lower East Side and 
parts of Queens and Brooklyn, were in danger of losing power, Con 
Ed president J. Michael Evans warned today. 
</P>
<P>
	At New York Police Department headquarters, on the edge of the  
Lower East Side, most elevators were shut down briefly to conserve 
electricity and emergency generators were briefly put into 
operation. Nearby City Hall and the Wall Street area were not 
affected. 
</P>
<P>
	Other outages affected hundreds of thousands of customers across  
the Northeast and mid Atlantic regions. A generator failure at a 
Dagsboro, Del., power plant belonging to Conectiv forced that 
utility to impose rolling blackouts -- shifting, 20-minute shutdowns 
-- on 400,000 of the utility's 1 million customers in New Jersey, 
Delaware and Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	In Manhattan, a line of mattresses and sofa cushions lined the  
sidewalk along 188th Street where Juan Lora, his wife, another 
couple and six children had slept outside. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no other option,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't stay inside. I had sweat dripping down my face,''  
said Berki Cepeda, who also slept outside. 
</P>
<P>
	The police department sent 500 officers to patrol the  
neighborhoods and direct traffic off streets where signal lights 
didn't work. Police reported a handful of attempted store break-ins 
and nine arrests, a sharp difference from the 1977 blackout that 
affected the whole city and led to widespread looting. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Rudolph Giuliani accused Con Ed of not being prepared.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're in an age of high technology. We're a city that has  
predictably high usage of electricity in warm weather. I mean 
everybody can figure that out, right?'' the frustrated mayor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Con Ed's president refused to respond to the criticism.  
</P>
<P>
	The intense heat had contributed to at least 18 deaths: seven in  
Pennsylvania, three in New York City, four in New Jersey, two in 
Massachusetts and two in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	The emergency room of South Ocean County Hospital in Manahawkin,  
N.J., treated more than 400 victims of heat stroke and heat 
exhaustion in three days. 
</P>
<P>
	The welcome cold front bringing slightly cooler and markedly  
drier air from the Midwest arrived in deadly fashion Tuesday, 
triggering violent storms in upstate New York and New England. 
Falling trees killed three people in upstate New York, New 
Hampshire and Massachusetts. 
</P>
<P>
	The temperature dropped from 91 to 70 in just four minutes  
Tuesday afternoon in Concord, N.H. 
</P>
<P>
	The storms caused still more power outages that affected  
thousands of utility customers, including 75,000 in upstate New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, high temperature records fell before the sun even  
reached its peak as Atlantic City, N.J., hit 98 before noon, with 
humidity of about 40 percent. The mercury hit record highs of 102 
at Newark, N.J.; 101 in New York; 102 in Raleigh-Durham, N.C.; and 
103 at Washington's Reagan National Airport. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 14:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Packers' Shareholders Sound Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- The Green Bay Packers can remain  
financially competitive at Lambeau Field for four more years, team 
president Bob Harlan told more than 7,000 shareholders gathered 
today for the team's annual meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	After that, Harlan said the Packers either must build a new  
stadium or make more than $75 million in renovations to Lambeau 
Field in order to keep up with the spiraling salaries and signing 
bonuses of the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	``We make no threats, we have no leverage,'' Harlan said. ``But  
we must find a way to remain competitive in the NFL's changing 
financial situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Packers' second outdoor shareholders meeting at Lambeau  
attracted fans representing over 56 percent of the shares in the 
league's only publicly held franchise. The 90-minute session 
featured a detailed overview of the upcoming season and reports 
from several team departments. 
</P>
<P>
	Packers officials called it the largest annual corporate meeting  
in America. 
</P>
<P>
	The shareholders also were invited to ask questions from the  
stands. Hot topics ranged from the stadium situation to the 
possibility of allowing Wisconsin residents to contribute part of 
their tax refund to their favorite team. 
</P>
<P>
	Team treasurer John Underwood assessed the team's financial  
state and called 1999 ``a dramatic reality check.'' The team 
disclosed last month in its annual report that despite record 
earnings, the Packers experienced a small negative cash flow that 
would have been much larger if not for the Cleveland Browns' $16 
million one-time expansion fee. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the Packers have sold out every game at Lambeau Field  
since 1960, the aging stadium has neither the amenities nor the 
seating capacities to allow the team to keep pace in a league in 
which 21 of the 31 teams have new or renovated home fields. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I listen to the people and the fans who contact me and  
write me, their preference is to stay in Lambeau Field,'' Harlan 
said. ``... But we also recognize that changes will have to be 
made, and we have some decisions to make.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Packers and the NFL have determined the team's revenue from  
playing at Lambeau Field will only keep pace with the rest of the 
league for four more years, Harlan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Green Bay leases its private boxes for about half of the  
league's average price, and Lambeau Field's infrastructure is well 
behind that in other stadiums. In particular, the team said it 
needs to make more money from concessions, seat licenses and club 
seating. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholders repeatedly asked Harlan why the team couldn't  
simply add a second deck to Lambeau Field, allowing most of the 
40,000 people on the team's season-ticket waiting list to generate 
revenue by buying the new seats. Harlan explained that the NFL's 
revenue-sharing policy gives 40 percent of ticket sales money to 
the visiting team. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're really in an education mode right now,'' Harlan said.  
``You try to tell them, but I'm not sure they got the message.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team's second annual meeting has already become a favorite  
event among the team's faithful fans, who traveled from all corners 
of the country to Green Bay. Many wore T-shirts or hats with the 
word ``Shareholder'' printed boldly across the front. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Ron Wolf also gave a detailed assessment of the  
team's roster. He said negotiations with top wide receiver Antonio 
Freeman were ongoing, and he denied reports the Packers were 
considering trading the All-Pro. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're doing everything in our power to make sure he signs with  
us and we don't have a Dorsey situation,'' Wolf said, referring to 
running back Dorsey Levens' holdout last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Kick returner Desmond Howard, the Packers' 1997 Super Bowl MVP  
who re-signed with the team last month after two years in Oakland, 
received an ovation each time his name was mentioned by Wolf. 
</P>
<P>
	The first shareholders meeting, held last year, attracted 18,707  
of the more than 100,000 Packers shareholders. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 05:40:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teens Charged With Throwing Bomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LINCOLN PARK, Mich. (AP) -- Two 13-year-old boys were charged  
with making a bomb that injured 5-year-old twin girls. 
</P>
<P>
	The girls were playing Friday in the yard of their baby sitter  
when the boys rode up on bicycles, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the boys asked, ``Do you want some pop?'' and rolled what  
looked like a bottle of soda toward the girls. One of the girls 
picked up the bottle but was startled by its fizzing. She dropped 
it and both sisters turned to run when it exploded. 
</P>
<P>
	The girls were struck by aluminum, plastic and chemical debris  
from the blast that sent shrapnel as far as 30 feet away, according 
to the police report. They were treated at a hospital and released. 
</P>
<P>
	The bomb was made from ingredients that included drain cleaner  
and aluminum foil, police said. The boys reportedly told police 
they got the bomb recipe from the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The boys were charged with assault with intent to do great  
bodily harm and placing an explosive device with intent to injure. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 12:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
