<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Looking for an Upset </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- In a state that loves to humble  
presidential front-runners, Bill Bradley is seeking an upset. 
</P>
<P>
	The former New Jersey senator and professional basketball player  
is walking New Hampshire's main streets and strolling around its 
beach communities, engaging in traditional retail politics as he 
battles Vice President Al Gore for the Democratic presidential 
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you run for office, where you begin is in somebody's  
living room,'' Bradley said. ``They look at you and they take your 
measure. Now you're running for president, and you begin in the 
same place. You begin in living rooms.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore has more money, more endorsements and the power and  
prestige of the White House, led by resident fund-raiser 
extraordinaire Bill Clinton. He leads Bradley in opinion polls. A 
late June CNN-Gallup-USA Today survey gave the vice president a 64 
percent to 28 percent lead with a margin of error of plus or minus 
5 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you ask Democrats who they feel is the person who can  
best lead them into the next century, who had the leadership and 
the values and the vision to take them into the next millennium, 
overwhelmingly it's Al Gore,'' Gore campaign spokesman Roger 
Salazar said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Bradley can't be counted out. It's the former New York Knick  
playing a game of one-on-one, and making enough of his shots to 
remain in competition. Indeed, Bradley calls it the first 
one-on-one, 11-month primary in history. 
</P>
<P>
	While Gore raised more than $18 million through June 30, Bradley  
took in more than $11 million, giving him enough to wage a 
competitive campaign. His fund-raising efforts have been helped by 
many prominent sports figures he befriended while playing 
basketball, and has raised much of his money from lawyers and 
investment bankers. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore has most of the Democratic establishment behind him, but  
Bradley has plenty of supporters as well. In Concord last month, 
standing in front of the State House during their lunch break for 
one of those made-for-television press opportunities, 18 Democratic 
state lawmakers endorsed him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want someone to be our next president who is not only  
intelligent but somebody who can identify with all people, someone 
who doesn't have glitz but someone who seems real,'' said one of 
the 18, state Rep. Marilyn Fraser, who represents Concord. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley talks about his background at every stop. Meeting with  
officials of a Concord community development group, he mentioned 
his father the banker, whose proudest achievement was that he 
didn't foreclose on anyone during the Depression. At a nearby music 
school, Bradley talked about how he joined the Air Force marching 
band because it meant he didn't have to clean latrines. 
</P>
<P>
	What he hasn't done so far is talk about many issues. Despite  
his 18 years in the Senate, Bradley is better known as a former 
professional basketball player, and he has refused to offer 
specifics until this fall on anything but gun control -- he 
responded to the Littleton, Colo., shootings by calling for 
licensing handguns like automobiles. 
</P>
<P>
	Nor is he willing to talk about Gore.  
</P>
<P>
	``The premise of my campaign is not to look at the other guy.  
The premise of my campaign is to look at the future,'' Bradley 
said. ``What all Democrats want is somebody who can win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many Democrats say Bradley's apparent strength is nothing more  
than an indication that Gore, despite all his years in politics, is 
having problems getting his campaign under way. 
</P>
<P>
	``There seems to be a general feeling that Gore just hasn't  
gotten his political act together,'' said Mark Grossman, a New York 
Democratic political consultant. ``It's a perception among 
Democrats. It's a concern among Gore supporters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, an undercurrent of dissatisfaction with the  
Clinton administration remains among Democrats, and Gore is paying 
the price. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unfortunate to the vice president, but there is a general  
feeling that because he's been part of the Clinton administration, 
some of the Clinton scandals are falling on Gore,'' said Rep. James 
Curran, who has endorsed Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, voters here pride themselves on their independence,  
and aren't about to anoint Gore so quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to take our time and make up our own minds,'' said  
one undecided Democrat, lobbyist Jim Monahan. ``I don't think it's 
disrespect to look beyond incumbency. There's a tradition of 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Grossman expected Gore to right his campaign long before  
the first delegates are selected. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this business, the primaries are light years away,''  
Grossman said. ``This is going to be looked at really as just a 
glitch on the radar screen, and an insignificant glitch at that, 
once people really begin to focus on the 2000 race.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
