<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 1st Lady Becomes Candidate Hillary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- At the Baseball Hall of Fame, the  
transformation of first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton into candidate 
Hillary Rodham Clinton was much in evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	She autographed the baseballs handed to her, she hugged the  
babies and she worked the crowds Wednesday as she began her first 
full-scale political trip into New York since forming her Senate 
exploratory committee on Tuesday. Even her advisers noticed the 
difference. 
</P>
<P>
	``She seems to be enjoying it,'' state Democratic Chairwoman  
Judith Hope said. ``I think her political instincts are extremely 
fine. She seems to know when to give you a hug or kneel down and 
talk to a baby.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Friend Mandy Grunwald, a media consultant who worked on  
President Clinton's campaigns and is now advising Mrs. Clinton, 
said, ``You can talk about it and plan it, but until you actually 
get out and do it, you never are quite sure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Mrs. Clinton, Wednesday was a day packed with a half-dozen  
events spread across 10 hours, not including the impromptu visit to 
the Unadilla rest stop along Interstate 88 between Binghamton and 
Oneonta. It was there that the first lady ran into Melinda Filidei 
from Galveston, Texas, and her two young daughters, Heather and 
Haileigh. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got H-names, I've got an H-name,'' Mrs. Clinton told  
the youngsters. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowds were everywhere along the route. Several dozen  
sign-waving supporters stood outside the Binghamton airport. Mrs. 
Clinton halted her motorcade and, taking a page out of her 
husband's campaign notebook, waded into the group. As they chanted 
``Run, Hillary, Run,'' she told them, ``Thank you all, so much.'' 
One carried a sign saying: ``You go, girl.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But there were also plenty of not-so-friendly signs along the  
way. A tractor trailer, ferried to Binghamton by an Albany-area 
Republican, carried the message ``Go Home, Hillary'' on its side. 
</P>
<P>
	It was clear evidence of the extreme emotions her Senate  
candidacy in New York has generated. ``Carpetbagger'' signs greeted 
the woman who has never lived or worked in New York and now wants 
to replace fellow Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan in the Senate. 
He is retiring at the end of next year. 
</P>
<P>
	It was at Moynihan's family farm near Oneonta that Mrs. Clinton  
made it clear on Wednesday that she understood a transformation was 
under way. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's new for me is being on this side of the microphone and  
talking for myself,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	She also answered the carpetbagger charge at Moynihan's farm.  
</P>
<P>
	``What I am for is maybe as important, if not more important,  
than where I am from,'' she said, pledging to be a ``strong and 
effective advocate on behalf of the people of New York.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Moynihan has often been at odds with the Clinton  
administration, he wholeheartedly endorsed Mrs. Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope she will go all the way,'' he said, after giving the  
first lady a tour of the schoolhouse office on his farm. ``I mean 
to go all the way with her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moynihan and Mrs. Clinton, the first wife of a president to run  
for public office, delivered their remarks to more than 200 
reporters and photographers gathered at his farm. More than 30 
television crews recorded the event staged in the rolling hills 
outside Oneonta. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton is expected to be unopposed in her quest for the  
Democratic nomination. On the Republican side, the Senate seat is 
being eyed by New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and two 
congressmen from Long Island, Rick Lazio and Peter King. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent polls show Mrs. Clinton tied with or trailing Giuliani.  
</P>
<P>
	Asked to respond to Mrs. Clinton's remarks, the mayor said, ``It  
doesn't make sense for me to respond to someone exploring and 
listening and announcing that they're going to explain to us at 
some point in the future what they're for. When she explains what 
she's for and if I'm running against her, then I will respond to 
that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
