<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Launches N.Y. Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DAVENPORT, N.Y. (AP) -- Launching her historic campaign for  
the Senate, Hillary Rodham Clinton pledged today to be a ``strong 
and effective advocate on behalf of the people of New York.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She was immediately asked to address criticism that she is a  
``carpetbagger'' for choosing to seek election from a state where 
she has never lived or worked. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I am for is maybe as important, if not more important  
than where I am from,'' Mrs. Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton was introduced by the man she hopes to succeed,  
retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan. ``I hope she will go all the 
way,'' he said, after giving the first lady a tour of his farm. ``I 
mean to go all the way with her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moynihan and Mrs. Clinton delivered their remarks to more than  
200 reporters and cameramen gathered at the farm. More than 30 
television crews recorded the event staged amid the rolling hills 
outside of Oneonta. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's exploratory committee will pay for her New York  
trip, including reimbursing the federal government for use of 
aircraft. However, Mrs. Clinton will continue to get 
taxpayer-funded Secret Service protection during the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	After leaving the Moynihan farm, Mrs. Clinton stopped at Brooks'  
House of Bar-B-Que in Oneonta for lunch. Just inside the door 
several people yelled, ``Go home, Hillary.'' A larger number told 
the protesters, ``You go home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, appearing eased and relaxed, described her  
campaign tour of New York as a ``listening tour'' that will bring 
her in touch with ordinary New Yorkers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to be listening very hard,'' she said. ``I'm going  
to be learning a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I care deeply about the issues that are important in this  
state that I've already been learning about and hearing about,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them, she said, were providing ``good quality'' education  
and health care and ``making sure the economy is built in a way 
that creates good jobs in every region in the state of New York.'' 
She criticized the Republican Congress over welfare reform. 
</P>
<P>
	The only first lady to run for public office, Mrs. Clinton  
pledged to make sure that New York gets its fair share from 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	On a New York-specific question about trade with Canada, she  
deferred to Moynihan, saying, ``Well, I'm going to let the expert 
speak on that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the time the first lady announced her candidacy, President  
Clinton was aboard a helicopter, on his way to an Indian 
reservation in Pine Ridge, S.D. as part of his national poverty 
tour. After her news conference, he called his wife to find out how 
her campaign debut had gone and to wish her well, aides said. 
</P>
<P>
	At her arrival at the Binghamton Airport, Mrs. Clinton was  
greeted by about 50 supporters, including state Democratic 
chairwoman Judith Hope and former state Democratic chairman John 
Burns. Outside the airport, about three dozen supporters waved 
placards while further along the road a tractor-trailer carried a 
sign that read ``Go home Hillary'' in large letters. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton spotted the supporters and, emulating her husband's  
campaign style, stopped her eight-vehicle motorcade to visit 
briefly with the group. 
</P>
<P>
	As the supporters shouted ``Run Hillary, Run,'' Mrs. Clinton  
said, ``Thank you all, so much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton formed a committee Tuesday to explore a run for the  
Senate. That allows her to raise and spend money for political 
purposes, like a full-fledged candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I run, I would be a strong and effective advocate on behalf  
of the people of New York,'' she said today. 
</P>
<P>
	She is not expected to face any opposition for the Democratic  
nomination. On the Republican side, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani 
and Reps. Rick Lazio and Peter King are considering Senate races. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent polls show Mrs. Clinton either tied or trailing Giuliani.  
</P>
<P>
	Although Mrs. Clinton has incredible name recognition by virtue  
of her position as first lady, some of the Clinton administration's 
baggage followed her as she launched her Senate campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about the Whitewater investigation, Mrs. Clinton said, ``I  
think that New Yorkers will make their own judgments about that. I 
think we've moved beyond all of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On fulfilling her duties as first lady while running a Senate  
campaign, she said, ``You know, it is not so dissimilar from 
someone, for example, being in the Congress and running for the 
Senate, or being a governor and running for another office.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A June poll from the Quinnipiac College Polling Institute found  
that 53 percent of registered voters statewide do not believe Mrs. 
Clinton understands the issues and problems facing New York, up 
from 43 percent in a March poll from the Hamden, Conn.-based 
institute. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans, including Giuliani, have been making much of the  
fact that Mrs. Clinton is an outsider. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
