<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Delta Wants To Polish Reputation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- In other places, folks complain about the  
weather. In Atlanta, if it's not about traffic, the griping is 
probably about Delta Air Lines. 
</P>
<P>
	The hometown carrier, Georgia's largest private employer with  
nearly 31,000 employees, has been trying to reverse a plummet in 
its reputation for customer service. 
</P>
<P>
	But Delta-bashing is a popular sport, and area newspapers  
frequently have columns and letters harping on the latest affronts. 
</P>
<P>
	``From most of what I hear,'' said Christopher McGinnis, who  
produces a newsletter for frequent travelers and writes a weekly 
column for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, ``that as much as the 
upper echelon of Delta would like to think that things are getting 
better, the rank-and-file travelers think it's just as bad, if not 
worse, than before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perception of airline service overall has been declining  
steadily in the United States. Department of Transportation 
statistics show air travel complaints have risen the past three 
years, up 28 percent in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong economy means more people are flying, which also means  
longer lines and more crowding. And Delta, which dominates 
Atlanta's busy Hartsfield International Airport with more than 600 
flights daily, has the added burden of an early 1990s cost-cutting 
wave that submerged its image of friendly efficiency and Southern 
hospitality. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think for a company like Delta or Coca-Cola or a few other  
companies that are part of the fabric of the community, the 
expectations are very, very high,'' said Vicki Escarra, named last 
year to the newly created Delta position of executive vice 
president for customer service. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of our customers are remembering what we were like,''  
said Ms. Escarra, a native Atlantan who joined Delta as a flight 
attendant 25 years ago. ``So we're going to have to work four times 
as hard to regain their confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leo F. Mullin, a Chicago utilities executive who became the  
first Delta chief executive officer from outside the airline, told 
shareholders at his first annual meeting in 1997 that rekindling 
employee morale and ``correction of shortcomings'' in customer 
service would be priorities. 
</P>
<P>
	He has invested hundreds of millions of dollars in new  
technology and refurbishing, while reshaping Delta's management. 
He's brought in executives from other airlines and even other 
industries -- and he put Delta veteran Escarra in charge of 
improving all stages of customer service. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was involved when Delta was great as far as service, so I  
know what that was like,'' she said. ``And I went through the tough 
times. I'm very passionate about seeing it get turned around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Delta, the nation's largest carrier in terms of passengers, was  
in June awarded Aviation Week and Space Technology magazine's award 
as the ``Best-Managed Major Airline'' for 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	But regular fliers quickly cite continued misfires -- a change  
last year making it harder to get upgrades; cutting out free 
sandwiches on many flights; a short-lived $2 surcharge on tickets 
not booked at Delta's Web site, and another short-lived move to 
charge ``popular prices'' for drinks in airport Crown Rooms. 
</P>
<P>
	The weekly Atlanta Business Chronicle in May ran a cartoon with  
a message board showing ``customer service-delayed...customer 
relations-canceled'' and a passenger saying: ``This must be the 
Delta counter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Escarra agreed that perception continues to be a problem and  
that ``we need to do a better job of telling our story: Yes, we did 
have problems, but here's where we are currently, and let us tell 
you what we have planned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes you have gaffes that will happen,'' said Andy Deane,  
a Delta captain and spokesman for the pilots' union, which has been 
critical of Delta management. ``I think overall, Mullin's team has 
done a pretty good job of addressing customer satisfaction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal figures released on July 6 showed that Delta ranked  
fourth among U.S. carriers in each of three categories; on-time 
arrivals, fewest mishandled bags, and fewest customer complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Escarra said from that base of improvement, fliers will see  
a series of changes, large and small, over the next two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta is beginning to roll out technology to speed check-in and  
boarding, including software that will provide information to both 
Delta agents and customers with a card swipe, as well as enable 
agents to manage seat inventories with a few keystrokes. 
</P>
<P>
	Digital message boards and television monitors in key airports  
will provide faster, more complete information on the status of 
flights, Delta says, and check-in kiosks and two-stage security 
checks will reduce lines. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta also plans to post ticket agents at some Atlanta mass  
transit stations, provide close airport parking for regular fliers, 
and even offer a limousine service. 
</P>
<P>
	And Ms. Escarra said, with the new technology will come a series  
of small, but important improvements, ranging from breakfasts for 
morning travelers, free drinks or discounts for customers who had 
service problems, and making sure employees smile, greet customers 
by name, and thank them for their business -- ``the things we used 
to do day in and day out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Delta has even produced its own, critic-free newspaper, called  
``The Atlanta Journey-Destination.'' It tells the story of how 
Delta became ``the greatest airline in the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's dated July 22, 2001.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
