<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reputed Mob Associate Get 8 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A reputed associate of the Bonanno crime family  
who used mob clout to force Wall Street brokers to promote the 
stock of an Arizona company has been sentenced to eight years in 
prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Eugene Lombardo, 47, apologized Tuesday for his role in a 1997  
conspiracy that made participants more than $1.3 million in illicit 
profits. The case was the largest ever to involve mobsters trying 
to manipulate stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to apologize to the courts and my family for putting  
them through all of this,'' said Lombardo, one of four men who 
admitted attempting to manipulate the price of HealthTech 
International Inc., of Mesa, Ariz., owner of health and fitness 
centers. 
</P>
<P>
	Lombardo also was ordered to pay $200,000 in restitution and was  
told to avoid organized crime members. 
</P>
<P>
	The value of the company's stock rose after the participants  
made a deal with the company's chairman and then brokers convinced 
unwitting buyers that the stock was worth eight times more than it 
was. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, a federal jury convicted HealthTech chairman Gordon  
Hall, 45, of racketeering, securities fraud and wire fraud. He 
awaits sentencing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
