<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> World Cup To Be Soccer Showcase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- An expected sellout crowd of 90,000,  
including President Clinton, watching the United States and China 
play for the Women's World Cup title in the historic Rose Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't set it up any better,'' forward Cindy Parlow said  
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The pageantry, the raucous fans and the world's two best teams  
make Saturday's final at the Pasadena stadium a showcase event for 
women's soccer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody's talked about this World Cup as history in the  
making and it's because of all those things,'' forward Tiffany 
Milbrett said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The point I like is there were 80,000 people watching the  
men's World Cup final. There's going to 90,000 watching the women's 
World Cup final,'' she said. ``All those things knock the boots off 
everybody because they weren't expecting it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1994 men's World Cup final, Brazil defeated Italy on  
penalty kicks after regulation ended in a scoreless tie in front of 
a sellout crowd at the Rose Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still remember the fabulous atmosphere, but the game still  
lagged behind,'' FIFA communications director Keith Cooper said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You ask most people what they thought of the final of 1994,  
they'll say disappointed because there were no goals and they 
finished on penalties. The game's got to be good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parlow predicted a low-scoring final because the United States  
and China play well-organized defense. But that doesn't mean 
viewers will be yawning. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both teams love to attack, love to take chances going forward  
and that's very exciting for the fans,'' she said. ``Both teams 
will attack at all costs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	United States coach Tony DiCicco said a lot of goals aren't  
necessary to create a memorable game. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as there's attacking soccer and teams trying to score  
goals and plays by the goalkeepers and near-misses, it doesn't have 
to be a lot of goals,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be two teams that are fit, that are ready, that  
are going to go out to win this game and they're not going to hold 
anything back,'' he said. ``They're going to play attractive 
soccer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because many of the Americans and Chinese have worked years to  
reach this level, Milbrett said, ``We don't have to make sure we're 
reminding each other to play high level, it's just going to be 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``At the end of the day, it always comes down to the game,''  
FIFA's Cooper said. ``I'm pretty confident that Saturday's going to 
be a good day.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
