<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clashes in Iraq After Executions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Tribesmen in southern Iraq have clashed with  
army soldiers and militiamen of the ruling Baath Party after three 
clan members were executed, two Iraqi opposition groups said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The London-based Iraqi Communist Party and the Iran-based  
Supreme Council for Islamic Revolution in Iraq said the tribesmen 
killed several party members, including two senior security 
officials, in a retaliatory attack Sunday against their offices in 
the town of Rumaitha. 
</P>
<P>
	The following day, army units from President Saddam Hussein's  
forces were sent to attack residential areas where members of Albu 
Hassan tribe live, the two groups said in separate statements faxed 
to The Associated Press in Cairo. 
</P>
<P>
	Heavy battles ensued and the defenders were able to repulse the  
army attack, inflicting heavy losses among the soldiers, they said, 
adding that more Iraqi troops were being sent from neighboring 
provinces. 
</P>
<P>
	They said the clashes erupted after the execution of the three  
tribesmen men on alleged charges of drug trafficking. The tribesmen 
denied the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Tensions in southern Iraq have been high since the Feb. 19  
assassination of the Muslim Shiite leader Ayatollah Mohammed Sadiq 
al-Sader. 
</P>
<P>
	Iraqi dissidents have reported clashes since al-Sader's death in  
several parts of the country, including the capital, Baghdad. The 
government admitted that there have been disturbances but blamed 
them on Iran-based opposition groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Rumaitha, 150 miles south of Baghdad, is in the heartland of the  
mainly Shiite Muslim southern Iraq and is a hotbed for opposition 
to Saddam's Sunni Muslim government. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
