<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ericsson CEO Resigns; Shares Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- The chief executive of L.M. Ericsson  
resigned today as the global telecommunications company took steps 
to revitalize performance. 
</P>
<P>
	The resignation of Sven-Christer Nilsson, who also held the  
position of president, resigned, was effective immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	Ericsson said Nilsson's job will be split between two other  
Ericsson veterans. Lars Ramqvist, chairman of the board, was named 
CEO, while Kurt Hellstroem, executive vice president-Asia Pacific, 
was named president. 
</P>
<P>
	Ericsson B shares on Stockholm's exchange dropped by more than 8  
percent on the news. 
</P>
<P>
	Ericsson said in a statement that ``the measures are intended to  
improve profitability and long-term growth in the company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ericsson is one of the leading providers of telecommunications  
equipment, specializing in mobile phones. The company has more than 
100,000 employees in 140 countries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
