</P>
<P>
	Fla. Jury Finds Tobacco Cos. Liable  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The jury in the first class-action lawsuit by  
smokers ever to go to trial found today that cigarette makers 
produced a defective product that causes emphysema, lung cancer and 
other illnesses -- a ruling that could expose the industry to 
billions in damages. The jury, which deliberated over a complicated 
10-question verdict form for eight days, will return in the next 
phase to determine damages. Their decision could prove to be the 
industry's most dire courtroom loss yet, since the plaintiffs are 
seeking at least $200 billion. The lawsuit was filed in 1994 on 
behalf of as many as 500,000 sick Florida smokers and the heirs of 
those who died. 

</P>
<P>
	Hackers Become an Increasing Threat  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Computer hacker victims in recentl weeks have  
included the White House, FBI, U.S. Senate (twice) and the Army's 
main Web site, but experts warn of an emerging threat to consumers 
from the next generation of technology. This technology includes 
new high-speed connections to the Internet over cable TV or and new 
digital phone lines that are permanently logged on. Higher speeds 
carry higher risks: Hackers even thousands of miles away could 
anonymously probe household computers over the Internet and rummage 
through private e-mail, documents and bank records. ``It vastly and 
immediately multiplies the amount of poorly protected computers on 
the Internet ripe for the picking,'' said Lucas Graves, an analyst 
with Jupiter Communications, a research company in New York. 

</P>
<P>
	Search Engines Lag Behind Internet  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Internet search engines are not keeping pace  
with the explosive growth of the Web. A study found that search 
engines -- which enable a computer user to find information by 
typing in a word or combination of words -- cover a diminishing 
fraction of Web pages and take The study of 11 search engines was 
conducted by computer scientists Steve Lawrence and C. Lee Giles at 
the NEC Research Institute in Princeton, N.J. 

</P>
<P>
	Barnesandnoble.com Selling Music  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In a race to keep pace with online rival  
Amazon.com, Barnesandnoble.com launched a music superstore today, 
including thousands of titles from artists ranging from pop 
sensation Ricky Martin to jazz legend Duke Ellington. The music 
store will be part of barnesandnoble.com's newly redesigned 
bookselling Web site, which was also launched today. In the new 
music store, shoppers can choose from all types of music, including 
some harder to find categories, such as retro swing or Brazilian 
jazz. The store will also have a large selection of classical 
music. Barnesandnoble.com shares ended at 17 11/16, up 7/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Air Canada Strike Talks Continue  
</P>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Air Canada presented its flight attendants with a  
revised contract offer today as a midnight strike deadline 
approached that could ground the airline. There was no guarantee 
the new proposals would produce a deal, but both sides -- and a 
federal mediator -- expressed hope that an agreement could be 
reached to avert a strike. Neither side would discuss details of 
how the new offer might resolve the main outstanding dispute, over 
pension benefits. The 5,100 flight attendants, members of the 
Canadian Union of Public Employees, say the pension plan they have 
is inadequate. 

</P>
<P>
	German Firm Investing in Web Cos.  
</P>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Industrial giant Siemens plans to use  
profits from the sale of two units to finance acquisitions of U.S. 
Internet companies, a Siemens spokesman said today. Siemens 
announced earlier this year it would launch public offerings of 
stock in its Siemens Matsushita Components, and its semiconductor 
business, Infineon Technologies, between October and next March. 
The spokesman did not identify potential buying targets. 

</P>
<P>
	DuPont To Close Six Plants  
</P>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- DuPont will close six plants in the wake  
of its $1.8 billion takeover in March of Herberts, a leading 
European manufacturer of automotive and industrial paints. The 
consolidation will eliminate 500 manufacturing positions and 800 
corporate, marketing and staff positions, DuPont said. The plants 
to be closed are located in Caieiras, Brazil; Piobesi, Italy; 
Dagenham, England; Ocoyoacac, Mexico; Porto, Portugal; and Saffle, 
Sweden. 

</P>
<P>
	Opryland Hotel Lays Off 160  
</P>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Opryland Hotel is laying off 160 of its  
4,600 employees, Gaylord Entertainment Co. announced today. 
Officials said the layoffs were done to redirect savings into new, 
undisclosed opportunities and expand existing businesses. Those 
laid off include both managerial and hourly employees in several 
departments. ``Our hotel occupancy, which consistently outstrips 
the hospitality industry, continues ahead of last year's pace, ... 
said Dave Jones, president and chief executive officer of the 
Opryland Hospitality Group, part of Nashville-based Gaylord. 
Conventions represent 80 percent of the 2,884-room hotel's 
business. 

</P>
<P>
	Thai Auto Plant Makes 28,000 Trucks  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Ford and Mazda's joint assembly plant  
in Thailand has produced 28,000 vehicles in its first year of 
operations and Since production began July 1, 1998, AutoAlliance 
has exported 18,694 pickups, about evenly split between the two 
brands, making the venture the second-largest auto exporter after 
Mitsubishi. 

</P>
<P>
	Berlin Power Co. To Cut Jobs, Costs  
</P>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- The Berlin electrical utility, Bewag,  
said today it will eliminate up to 4,000 jobs, or about half of its 
work force, over the next three years as part of an effort to cut 
costs by $555 million. The utility said pressure to reduce prices 
required that it cut costs to maintain its market share of 80 
percent in Berlin and 5 percent in Germany. Bewag is facing 
pressure in its home market, with Germany's largest utility RWE AG 
having made Berlin a key expansion target. 

</P>
