<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 23:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Excess Military Property Probed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Every year, the military marks more than $20  
billion worth of excess property for transfer to other agencies or 
sale, but some of it just disappears from Pentagon records. 
</P>
<P>
	Items costing $2.7 billion, including sensitive weapons parts  
and equipment that might be pilfered, were sent for disposal but 
never recorded as received by any disposal offices in fiscal 1998, 
according to congressional investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon acknowledges the problem but says it's more  
clerical than criminal. 
</P>
<P>
	A General Accounting Office report cites only one incident where  
military personnel determined a likely theft -- the disappearance of 
a $424 camera lens. Most of the discrepancies are due to faulty 
record-keeping, problems with data entry into computers or other 
clerical failures, it concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	Items that should have received special military handling such  
as communications equipment, aircraft components and gun parts, or 
items that could easily have been pilfered constituted about half 
the property that disposal offices listed as not received, the GAO 
said in reporting on its examination of in-transit records. 
</P>
<P>
	The report was the third in a series of congressional inquiries  
into problems with disposal of surplus military equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	A report last year found that some of the $22 billion worth of  
equipment sold in fiscal 1997 may have caused the leaking of 
sensitive military technology to U.S. and foreign buyers. A year 
earlier, a GAO report found billions of dollars worth of property 
was being destroyed that might have been sold for civilian use 
without compromising security or flight safety concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Pentagon efforts to reform its complex system for  
disposing of surplus property, problems persist, the new report 
concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	``Management controls over excess property being shipped to  
disposal are not working effectively, leaving the property 
vulnerable to loss or undetected theft,'' said the report, sent to 
Rep. Floyd Spence, chairman of the House Armed Services Committee. 
Copies also went to Defense Secretary William Cohen and to the 
heads of the armed services. 
</P>
<P>
	The report included a response from Defense Deputy  
Undersecretary Roger W. Kallock, who said the department concurs 
with its conclusions and is addressing its recommendations for 
closer control of excess military equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon ``believes the property is not being lost and that  
most record discrepancies are due to administrative errors,'' the 
report notes, but it adds that the administrative problems are 
``systemic and widespread.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 12:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Are Mixed; Dow Up 3.49 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were mixed today as the market  
awaited second-quarter corporate earnings reports. Rising bond 
yields also pushed stocks down. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 3.49 at 11,138.61. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed, having shifted in and out  
of positive territory throughout the session. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 
500 index was up 2.30 at 1,390.42, and the Nasdaq composite index 
was down 4.57 at 2,732.21. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street analysts expect mostly robust earnings reports from  
U.S. companies, whose profits continue to grow along with the 
nation's economy. Analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. expect 
earnings for the companies on the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 list to 
rise 11.4 percent for the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	But with market indexes near record levels, analysts say  
investors may punish any companies that miss or merely meet 
published estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market is waiting to sink its teeth into some solid  
numbers,'' said Alan Ackerman, senior vice president at Fahnestock 
&AMP; Co. ``Having moved up sharply last week, the market is just 
marking time until we see exactly what these second-quarter numbers 
look like.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts believe last week's stunning gains, which produced  
records for most major indexes and a 586.68-point gain in the Dow, 
were fed by the expectation of strong earnings. This week, as the 
first few reports hit the market, there may be little room to 
extend gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, Waste Management plunged 19 3/8 to 34 3/16 after saying it  
expects to miss Wall Street estimates by as much as 12 cents per 
share. 
</P>
<P>
	Alcoa, meanwhile, proved that good news isn't always enough,  
falling 2 3/16 to 60 15/16 after reporting earnings of 64 cents per 
share, a penny ahead of expectations. Alcoa, considered a cyclical 
stock that thrives in times of economic growth, has been the 
strongest gainer among Dow components so far this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! fell 9 1/16 to 166 1/16, continuing a slide that began  
Tuesday afternoon. The Internet search engine provider was to 
report earnings after the market closed today, and while Wall 
Street has called for earnings of 8 cents per share, traders said 
Yahoo! might be hurt if it missed the ``whisper number'' of 9 cents 
per share. 
</P>
<P>
	Whisper numbers are unofficial forecasts circulated among  
traders and on Internet trading sites. 
</P>
<P>
	The initial public offering of Musicmaker.com benefited from  
renewed interest in new Internet stocks. The Web-based company, 
which lets customers create customized compact discs, was priced at 
14 and rose to 23 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Rising bond yields held stocks lower. This afternoon, the yield  
on the 30-year Treasury bond was at 6.07, up from 6.03 percent late 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 614.41 million 
shares, ahead of Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 0.25 at 654.52, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was off 2.41 at 802.48. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000, which measures the performance of smaller  
companies, fell 4.54 to 452.01. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
