<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASCAR Driver Atwood Becoming Name </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- At 18 years old, Casey Atwood already  
has some of the habits of a veteran NASCAR driver, both on the 
track and in the winner's circle. 
</P>
<P>
	Exhibit A: After 76 laps on the tail of leader Jeff Green in  
Sunday's Diehard 250 Busch Series race in Milwaukee, Atwood bumped 
him out of the way on the last lap to win. Green called it a cheap 
shot. Atwood called it racing. 
</P>
<P>
	Exhibit B: After becoming the youngest winner in Busch Series  
history, Atwood played it cool without an exuberant celebration. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just didn't want to get on top of my car and jump up and  
down like an idiot,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oh, I was excited. Probably the most excited I've ever been in  
racing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Atwood won't turn 19 until Aug. 25. Before Sunday's victory he  
was already the youngest driver ever to win a Busch Series pole, 
that coming last season when he was 17. He also won the Diehard 250 
from the pole. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a big thrill to win that first one,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Green, who is third in the Busch Series points standings, said  
the last-lap bump from Atwood was unwarranted and vowed never to 
forget it. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's just part of it,'' Atwood said. ``Jeff would have done  
the same thing to me if he'd been in my place. I've seen him do it 
to other drivers lots of times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The victory gives Atwood $269,930 in winnings for the season.  
He's been in 17 of the 18 Busch Series races, with four finishes in 
the top five. He's ranked 10th in the standings. 
</P>
<P>
	Atwood isn't satisfied.  
</P>
<P>
	``We've had some bad luck and I've torn up some cars,'' he told  
The Tennessean. ``We've had to spend a lot of time fixing them. 
Hopefully I can keep from wrecking so much, and that will give the 
crew more time to work on other things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Atwood ran 13 Busch races last year, so he isn't officially a  
rookie. Still, he's seeing some tracks for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's still learning, which makes it all the more amazing that  
he's been able to do so well,'' said Clarence Brewer, owner of the 
Brewco Motorsports team that Atwood races for. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just think what he'll be capable of once he gets some  
experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Brewer said, Atwood's relative success does not change  
the timetable for graduating him to Winston Cup racing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to stick with our plan, which is to concentrate on  
the Busch Series this season,'' Brewer said. ``Next year if things 
go right we might try a Cup race or two. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a whole new game on that level. ... When Casey moves up,  
we want to do it right.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 08:52:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  U.S. To Suggest Mideast Peace Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and his Mideast mediators  
are likely to move in quickly with their own peace proposals now 
that Israel's new prime minister, Ehud Barak, has formed a 
government and put peacemaking with the Arabs at the top of his 
agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	At Clinton's invitation, Barak will come here for talks at the  
White House July 15 and July 19, planning also to meet with 
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Secretary of Defense 
William Cohen, as well as key members of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has declared Israel's key to security is peace with all  
its neighbors -- a formula Barak says has his highest priority. 
</P>
<P>
	In a gesture of urgency, Clinton said he would outline his views  
right after talking to Barak, and then went on to touch on two of 
them: support for Palestinian aspirations for a homeland and for 
Palestinian refugees living wherever they like. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak rejected Clinton's statement on refugees as unacceptable  
and called for clarification. The president has not reopened the 
red-hot subject, but administration officials in a damage-control 
operation told Israel privately that the refugee problem could be 
decided only through negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also called on Israel to carry out the land-for-security  
accord he helped reach in October at the Wye River talks in 
Maryland between Benjamin Netanyahu, then Israel's prime minister, 
and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wye River accord calls for Israel to relinquish an  
additional 13.1 percent of the West Bank. Netanyahu halted after 
giving up 2 percent, saying Arafat had failed to hold up his end of 
the bargain when he didn't root out terrorist cells on land already 
under the Palestinian Authority's control. 
</P>
<P>
	While Clinton and other U.S. policy-makers habitually say all  
land-for-peace decisions are up to the parties and the United 
States would not presume to impose terms on them, a private push or 
even a nudge in one direction or another can be telling. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak spoke briefly to Clinton by telephone Monday night,  
telling him he intended to meet first with Arafat, Egyptian 
President Hosni Mubarak and King Abdullah of Jordan before visiting 
Washington. Today, Barak's office issued a statement that he would 
be in Washington late next week to confer with Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	In public, Barak is asserting a determination to pursue peace  
accords. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know we have thousands of problems on the public agenda,''  
he said, ``Nothing is more important in my view than that supreme 
mission ... putting an end to the 100-year conflict in the Middle 
East.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He appears willing to negotiate with Syria as well as with the  
Palestinians. And, like Netanyahu, Barak would like to find a way 
to close down the Israeli security zone inside southern Lebanon. 
</P>
<P>
	At a minimum, Syria wants to get back all of the Golan Heights,  
the strategic plateau along Israel's northern border that it lost 
in the 1967 Six-Day war. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak, as military chief of staff, proposed retaining at least  
some of the land as a security barrier. But later, he served as 
foreign minister in the government led by Shimon Peres that advised 
Syria in U.S.-mediated talks it could have the Golan Heights for 
the right terms. 
</P>
<P>
	It is not clear where Barak stands now on that contested  
enclave, nor how much of the West Bank he would give to the 
Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
	He has said he wanted to resume the stalemated negotiations, but  
also that he was unwilling to share sovereignty over Jerusalem or 
uproot all the Jewish settlements on the West Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Arafat is aiming for a state with its capital in Jerusalem.  
Clinton has come within a whisker of endorsing Palestinian 
statehood and has blocked transfer of the U.S. Embassy to Jerusalem 
from Tel Aviv. 
</P>
<P>
	In selecting his Cabinet, the new prime minister has made moves  
that suggest he may not be as conciliatory to the Arabs as the 
Clinton administration might wish. 
</P>
<P>
	Peres, the former prime minister who played a key role in  
land-for-peace deals, was denied his bid to oversee negotiations 
and given a minor post as head of a new regional development 
ministry. Yossi Beilin, an architect of the landmark Oslo accords 
with the Palestinians, did not get the plum assignment he was 
looking for, either. 
</P>
<P>
	David Levy, foreign minister in two Likud-led governments, will  
be Barak's foreign minister. Levy is inclined to take a tougher 
line than either Peres or Beilin did in reaching out to the 
Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Peres stepped forward Tuesday with a declaration that  
Barak would resume talks quickly with all Arab parties. 
</P>
<P>
	``Barak is a man of his word, and what he has said, he will  
do,'' Peres told reporters at a conference in Cairo. ``It will not 
take too long before we shall see the renewal of the peace 
process.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
