<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nashville Sound: George Jones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Beating the odds one more time, George  
Jones is back from the dead and working the room. 
</P>
<P>
	The greatest living country music singer is trying to drum up  
support for his new album, ``Cold Hard Truth,'' by talking up a 
roomful of radio programmers, who for years have refused to play 
his new music. As always, his silver hair is shellacked into place, 
and loyal wife Nancy is by his side. He gamely grins and greets the 
radio guys as though they were long-lost cousins. 
</P>
<P>
	A session of interviews at a recording studio is being held to  
take advantage of the disc jockeys' presence in town for the 
International Country Music Fan Fair, an annual festival that 
brings thousands of fans to Nashville. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, 67, is his own best salesman as he poses for photos.  
</P>
<P>
	``You're big ol' boys, ain't you,'' he observes cheerfully, arms  
thrown around two hearty deejays, while waiting for the camera to 
click. 
</P>
<P>
	The two men are truly large, and they serve as a sharp contrast  
to the thin and frail Jones, who almost died in March after he 
crashed his Lexus into a concrete bridge near his home. An open 
pint of vodka was found in the wreckage, and he later pleaded 
guilty to driving while impaired and violating Tennessee's open 
container law. He was fined $550 and ordered to seek treatment for 
alcoholism. 
</P>
<P>
	``I died twice,'' Jones said. ``My heart stopped twice going to  
the hospital.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His liver was severely lacerated, a lung collapsed and he later  
developed pneumonia. But he pulled through and appears on the way 
to a full recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got to believe there's something to it,'' Jones said. God  
has kept him here for a reason, ``For one more job or something. So 
I'm gonna search my soul for that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones has spent much of his life a slave to drugs and alcohol,  
but for more than a decade before the crash he says he limited 
himself to an occasional glass of wine with dinner. 
</P>
<P>
	He's not sure why he was drinking the day of the accident,  
though he says he had had a very hard year, overshadowed by the 
death of his former wife and partner, Tammy Wynette. He also left 
longtime record label MCA and helped his current wife with a 
serious illness. 
</P>
<P>
	He says he drank less than a half-a-pint of vodka the day of the  
accident. ``Of course, it didn't take much to get me impaired, 
because I hadn't drank in so long,'' he says. ``I was on the phone 
talking to my daughter and reaching over trying to rewind the 
(cassette) tape ... and just for a second I took my eye off the 
road.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even while a heavy drinker and drug abuser, Jones was a great  
artist. Many consider him the finest country music singer of all 
time, based on more than 150 hits like ``He Stopped Loving Her 
Today,'' ``A Good Year for the Roses'' and ``If Drinkin' Don't Kill 
Me (Her Memory Will).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones was born in a log cabin in Saratoga, Texas. As a child, he  
sang for money on the streets of Beaumont, Texas. He was a devotee 
of Hank Williams, Roy Acuff and Lefty Frizzell, and his early 
records sounded much like Williams'. 
</P>
<P>
	His hit, ``Why Baby Why,'' got him signed to Mercury Records in  
Nashville. Later, he began specializing in honky-tonk ballads like 
``She Thinks I Still Care'' and his famous ``A Good Year for the 
Roses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1969, he married Wynette and they became a hit duo. The  
teaming of two of country music's most popular singers on songs 
that seemed to mirror their private lives couldn't miss. ``We're 
Not the Jet Set,'' they sang, but fans nicknamed them ``The 
President and First Lady of Country Music.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Jones became increasingly lost in a fog of drugs and alcohol  
-- one tale has him driving his lawn mower to the liquor store 
because Wynette hid all his car keys so he couldn't get any booze. 
The marriage fell apart and Jones and Wynette divorced in 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early 1980s, while continuing to abuse alcohol and drugs,  
his career still flourished. In 1980, he recorded his latter-day 
signature song, ``He Stopped Loving Her Today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The turning point in his personal life came in 1983 when Jones  
wed Nancy Sepulvado, who gradually got him off drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	To the surprise of many, the support of radio stations gave out  
on him before his health. By the late '80s, Jones and many of his 
peers had been replaced by a new generation of stars like Garth 
Brooks. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones left MCA in 1998 after a string of poor-selling albums.  
Then Wynette, with whom he had renewed a friendship and worked with 
again after years of acrimony, died after battling various 
illnesses for much of her life. 
</P>
<P>
	The same year, Nancy Jones started experiencing excruciating  
headaches and it took some time for doctors to find the proper 
treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	While all this was going on, Jones was working on ``Cold Hard  
Truth.'' He considered it his best album in years, but wondered if 
radio stations would pass him by again. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident may have helped Jones get more attention from the  
country music radio stations that had ignored him for so long. 
</P>
<P>
	``The realization that George Jones could have died has had a  
powerful impact with radio,'' said Evelyn Shriver, president of 
Jones' new record label, Asylum. ``But it wouldn't have mattered if 
this weren't such a brilliant album.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Cold Hard Truth'' is full of heartache in classic Jones  
fashion, reminiscent of his 1970s work with producer Billy 
Sherrill. The single ``Choices'' is currently rising on the charts. 
</P>
<P>
	``This album is not about trying to make George Jones seem  
hip,'' producer Keith Stegall said. ``It's just about making a 
classic George Jones album.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although it was recorded before the accident, the apparent  
references to it are spooky. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you weren't drinking, the music on this album might lead  
you back to it,'' Nancy Jones said jokingly. 
</P>
<P>
	``Choices,'' is about living with the consequences of one's  
actions. ``Sinners &AMP; Saints'' rebukes people who are too 
judgmental. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's only one difference between sinners and saints,''  
Jones sings. ``One is forgiving and the other one ain't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones loves it.  
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe the stuff that I've been doing before just wasn't up to  
par,'' he said. ``It's hard to get a hit song from a writer if they 
know already they're not going to get any radio play. ... 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that's all radio was looking for, for George Jones to  
come back with some good stuff and today's sound. And I just want 
to thank them for giving the old man another chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in country music ...  
</P>
<P>
	INTERNET COUNTRY: The Country Music Hall of Fame is getting two  
new homes. Ground was broken June 17 on a new building in downtown 
Nashville. And the museum and library has struck a deal with 
country.com to put its archives on line. That means Web surfers can 
now pull up biographies, exhibit highlights and other information. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
