<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lott Holds Up Holbrooke Nomination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate confirmation continues to look like a  
receding target for Richard Holbrooke in his long quest to be U.N. 
ambassador. 
</P>
<P>
	Four senators, including Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,  
are now known to have placed ``holds'' on the veteran diplomat's 
nomination, putting off a floor vote for an indeterminate period. 
And more naysayers may be waiting in the wings. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke, an investment banker and veteran diplomat, was  
announced for the post in June 1998. When the Senate Foreign 
Relations Committee approved the nomination late last month, a full 
year later, it finally looked like clear sailing. 
</P>
<P>
	But that was not to be.  
</P>
<P>
	Two senators -- Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, and George Voinovich,  
R-Ohio -- have made their positions on the nomination public. Two 
others, Lott and Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., took their delaying 
actions without public comment. 
</P>
<P>
	And, according to several Senate Republican aides, at least two  
more senators are working behind the scenes in an effort to block 
or further delay the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	The holds basically are unrelated to Holbrooke's qualifications  
for the job. Lott and McConnell are trying to apply pressure on the 
White House to nominate an Ohio law professor for a ``Republican'' 
position on the Federal Election Commission, congressional and 
administration sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	The professor, Bradley A. Smith of Capital University in  
Columbus, had been recommended by Republican leaders for the 
vacancy on the commission, which is divided between two Democrats 
and two Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott spokesman John Czwartacki declined to comment on the holds.  
By tradition, any senator can block, at least for a time, any 
nomination, anonymously if he or she chooses. 
</P>
<P>
	However, on the subject of the FEC vacancy, Czwartacki said  
presidents traditionally give leaders of the other party the 
prerogative of picking their party's FEC representatives. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never seen a White House that tried to pick the other  
party's nominees,'' Czwartacki said. 
</P>
<P>
	Voinovich is seeking to delay the nomination for other reasons.  
</P>
<P>
	Not only does Voinovich want to make sure there is a recorded  
vote on the nomination, but ``he has concerns about Holbrooke's 
nomination for policy reasons,'' said Mike Dawson, a spokesman for 
Voinovich. 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley publicly put a hold on Holbrooke to protest what he  
contends is State Department retribution against a government 
employee at the U.N. mission in New York for telling members of 
Congress about waste and inefficiency at the international 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Democrats said they hoped the delays would be  
short-lived, and characterized the new holds as an attempt by GOP 
leaders to exert leverage over the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke, a former ambassador to Germany and assistant  
secretary of state, is the architect of the 1995 Bosnia peace 
accord. 
</P>
<P>
	At the White House, spokesman Barry Toiv called Holbrooke  
``supremely qualified'' for the position. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is essential to our national interest that he be put in  
place and the Senate ought to vote on his nomination as soon as 
possible,'' Toiv said. 
</P>
<P>
	Czwartacki, the Lott spokesman, said last week that there seemed  
to be ``irreconcilable holds'' on Holbrooke. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Wednesday, he was a little more upbeat. ``I never cease  
to be amazed at how log jams can be broken around here,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 16:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
