<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Billions For Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The International Monetary Fund on Wednesday  
approved a $4.12 billion loan for Mexico that is part of a larger 
package of credits. It is designed to help the country avert 
economic turmoil during and after next year's presidential 
elections. 
</P>
<P>
	An IMF spokesman said the loan, to be disbursed in seven  
installments, will be available to Mexico over 17 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Mexican officials said last month they had obtained $23.7  
billion in international credits and refinancing to protect the 
country when it holds presidential elections in July 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, the country's economy has suffered during  
presidential transition periods -- a tendency blamed on the collapse 
of short-term strategies to prop up the economy during a campaign 
and investor wariness about a new government. 
</P>
<P>
	The package includes $6.8 billion in credits from the United  
States and Canada, Mexico's partners in the North American Free 
Trade Agreement. The World Bank is expected to provide $5.2 billion 
and the Inter-American Development Bank $3.5 billion. Mexico will 
also receive $4 billion from the U.S. Export-Import Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The assistance package put together in Washington in mid-June is  
designed to help the Mexican government meet $8 billion in debts 
owed to foreign lenders over the next two years, including $6 
billion to the IMF. 
</P>
<P>
	Mexican financial officials have said they would turn to  
official sources for funding to meet these debts because 
international capital markets have been demanding a high risk 
premium on any Mexican debt. 
</P>
<P>
	President Ernesto Zedillo's administration has vowed to try to  
prevent a recurrence of election-related economic unrest. Three 
weeks after Zedillo took over in December 1994, Mexico's peso 
plunged sharply, causing a financial crisis from which the country 
is still trying to recover. 
</P>
<P>
	While Mexico's economy is generally considered to be less  
vulnerable than it was in 1994, the political situation is more 
volatile. 
</P>
<P>
	The Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, which has  
governed Mexico since 1929, faces unprecedented competition and is 
planning its first-ever national primary to choose a candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Some polls show an opposition party candidate, Guanajuato Gov.  
Vicente Fox, leading in the race for the presidency. But the PRI 
won a crucial electoral battle Monday in the country's most 
populous state that will bolster its chances in the presidential 
voting. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 12:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
