<DOCNO> APW19990707.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 08:00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: VW Entering Luxury Car Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAMBURG, Germany (AP) -- Volkswagen AG, Europe's biggest  
automaker, plans to build two luxury sedans to compete with 
DaimlerChrysler AG's Mercedes-Benz and grab a share of the high-end 
market by selling them for less, a trade magazine said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The biweekly Auto Zeitung said the development names for the two  
new cars are D1 and Passat Plus. Volkswagen declined to comment on 
the report. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the report, the D1, to be built in Dresden, will be  
powered by a 12-cylinder engine. It is to be available in late 2000 
and cost less than the $77,000 for a comparable Mercedes S500. 
</P>
<P>
	The somewhat smaller Passat Plus is planned for a mid-2000  
debut. The sedan will have a more powerful engine and a wheelbase 
about 5 inches longer than the current Passat, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Passat Plus is to cost less than the $35,020 of comparable  
Mercedes E-class models with V6 engines, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	In another move, VW plans to present expanded engine options for  
its New Beetle models at the Frankfurt auto show in the fall, the 
report said. And it said the New Beetle convertibles, which VW has 
said it is thinking about building, would go on sale in late 2001. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
