<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed mostly lower  
Wednesday, as investors sold off stocks to reap profits from recent 
gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 91.83  
points, or 0.51 percent, to close at 17,958.90. On Tuesday, the 
average closed down 84.33 points, or 0.47 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei fell as investors cashed in for the second  
consecutive day after the average closed above 18,000 on Monday for 
the first time in almost two years. Prices had soared after a Bank 
of Japan survey showed a rise in business confidence. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong stocks also closed lower, dragged down by two large  
blue-chip companies whose prices fell after they made big stock 
sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index fell 115.7 points, or 0.8 percent,  
to close at 14,257.44. On Tuesday, the index had lost 134.13 
points, or 0.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	After their share sales, telecommunications provider Cable &AMP;  
Wireless HKT fell 6.5 percent and China Resources Enterprises Ltd. 
plunged 8.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In Seoul, shares surged for a third straight day as funds  
continued to flow into the market. The rapid pace of the country's 
economic recovery, expectations of stable local interest rates and 
better than expected half-year corporate results all boosted the 
market to a four-year high. 
</P>
<P>
	The Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 16.55 points, or 1.7  
percent, to 1,005.98, its highest level since Oct. 18, 1995, when 
it closed at 1,006.70. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the U.S. dollar slipped against the  
Japanese yen as foreigner investors sold dollars for yen to buy 
Japanese stocks, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.96 yen in late trading in Tokyo, down 0.12  
yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and also below its late New York 
level of 122.02 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian shares plummeted 2.3 percent, as political  
uncertainty triggered across-the-board selling by local and foreign 
investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The JSX Composite Index closed down 15.81 points at 665.771.  
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares ended mostly lower as retail investors  
continued to dump shares seen as overpriced. The Straits Times 
Index closed at 2,144.53 points, down 30.98 points, or 1.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Prices closed slightly higher as investors funneled cash  
into plastics and textile stocks that had trailed recent market 
advances. The market's key Weighted Stock Price Index closed up 
15.58 points, or 0.18 percent, at 8,470.07. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand shares closed higher, underpinned by  
gains in market leaders Carter Holt Harvey Ltd. and Telecom Corp. 
of New Zealand Ltd. The benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 10.33 
points, or 0.4 percent, to 2,171.03. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine stocks closed lower as investors continued to  
cash in on recent blue chip gains. The 30-company Philippine Stock 
Exchange Index closed down 12.04 points, or 0.5 percent, at 
2,598.32. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed lower on negative  
sentiment in the gold sector after gold auctioned Tuesday by the 
Bank of England fetched disappointing prices. The All Ordinaries 
Index ended down 14.6 points, or 0.5 percent, at 3,067.3. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian stocks closed lower, with investors  
cashing in on recent gains and the release of May industrial output 
data. The Composite Index, which tracks 100 key stocks, closed at 
839.52 points, down 6.76 points, or 0.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai shares closed lower, tracking falls in other  
regional markets. The Stock Exchange of Thailand index fell 10.71 
points, or 2.03 percent, to end at 516.11. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
