<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Washington Tourists Take the Heat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Cory Van Dam plopped to the floor of the U.S.  
Capitol on Tuesday, pressing his bare legs against the eternally 
cool stone. His red-faced brother Andrew wilted on a bench nearby 
while their father reviewed what the family has learned about the 
United States on their long-planned trip to Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``Boise is as far east as we're ever going to live,'' declared  
Bill Van Dam, laughing. 
</P>
<P>
	Heat and humidity, after all, are as much a part of the history  
of Washington as the monuments and government buildings that the 
Van Dams and thousands of other tourists devotedly visited in the 
three-digit heat. In the shade, it hit 102. 
</P>
<P>
	The city tried to help with fire hydrants equipped to shower  
water on anyone wanting to get soaked. One sprayed coolness at the 
base of Capitol Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	But there was no sanctuary quite like the marble-and-stone halls  
of the Capitol, which has been air-conditioned since 1929. A statue 
in the building's Statuary Hall honors the father of interior 
coolness, Dr. John Gorrie of Florida, who invented ``mechanical 
refrigeration'' in 1851. 
</P>
<P>
	Shielded by the stately dome from what felt like 110-degree heat  
Tuesday, the Van Dams wondered what it was like back home in Idaho. 
Answer: A blissful 83 degrees, with a light, dry wind. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're glad we came, because the alternative would have been  
not coming, and there's a lot here that we wanted to see,'' Van Dam 
said. ``But, man! It's hotter than I ever could have imagined.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Van Dams' day began with an 8 a.m. tour of the White House  
as the temperature edged merely into the 80s. Then it was on to the 
Rayburn House Office Building, where they received a guided tour 
mostly of the inside of Capitol Hill, courtesy of a heat-conscious 
friend who works for Rep. Michael Oxley, R-Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Azevedo family of San Diego, Calif., had the full  
Washington experience. As the temperature back home hovered just 
below 70 degrees, the Azevedos walked at least a half-mile up 
Independence Avenue to the Capitol, stopping along the way to dunk 
each other's heads under public water fountains. 
</P>
<P>
	Then they stood in line to get inside the Capitol. It was noon  
before the family of five was ushered across the sizzling blacktop 
of Capitol Plaza and up 36 stairs to the Rotunda. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosalie Azevedo dropped onto a bench a few feet from the Van  
Dams and fanned herself with a piece of paper. Her three children 
and husband Paul wandered around, gazing at the paintings nearby. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're off to the Air and Space Museum next,'' she said --  
another hike down Independence Avenue. But the family had a 
strategy. ``This time, we know where to walk under the big trees.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
