<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Equestrians Deny Bribery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Japanese Equestrian Federation today denied  
bribery was involved in the $29,000 an Olympic rider gave to three 
of its officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Federation head Shozo Hara acknowledged the money presented a  
``serious problem.'' He said the federation will decide on any 
penalties, including possible expulsion, at a meeting next Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hara said the money from Yoshinaga Sakurai was intended as a  
gift, payments to set up a training camp for Sakurai and a loan. 
</P>
<P>
	Sakurai also denied the cash was intended to get him a berth on  
the Japanese team for the Barcelona Olympics. Hara said the 
payments did not influence selection of the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no wrongdoing. It was carried out fairly,'' Hara  
said. ``But the fact that money was involved is extremely serious. 
It was a thoughtless act.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The federation carried out an in-house investigation after the  
national Mainichi newspaper reported this week that Sakurai had 
paid the federation officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said expulsion was the only way the federation has to  
punish its members, but other ways may have to be created as new 
policy. 
</P>
<P>
	The federation denied another Mainichi report that the parents  
of an equestrian rider gave $6,500 to an official to help with 
their son's bid to compete in the 1996 Atlanta Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The official denied receiving the money and the parents of the  
unidentified athlete also denied giving the money, according to the 
federation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have these reports that are incredible and when we  
investigate, the facts turn out to be different. The reports have 
hurt the reputation of the federation,'' Hara said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials denied that cash gifts were common in the federation.  
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, the IOC asked for an investigation into gifts  
that Nagano city officials gave committee members who were 
selecting a host city for the 1998 Winter Games. Nagano officials 
found no wrongdoing in the city's successful bid. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
