<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Lawmakers Plan Budget Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and congressional leaders  
plan to meet at the White House next week to discuss their dueling 
proposals for what to do with the $2.9 trillion in 10-year budget 
surpluses that both sides now project. 
</P>
<P>
	White House officials have issued an invitation for Monday. But  
the timing may change to accommodate lawmakers out of town for the 
July Fourth recess, said White House and top Capitol Hill aides. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides said the discussions will focus on revamping Medicare  
and Social Security for the baby boomers' retirement and on 
Clinton's proposal to create a new, voluntary prescription drug 
benefit for the disabled and those 65 and over. Also on the table 
will be both sides' proposals for tax cuts and domestic and defense 
spending. 
</P>
<P>
	It appears unlikely that the meeting would lead to early,  
full-blown budget negotiations btween the two sides. Clinton will 
have leverage over Republicans this fall, when spending bills that 
will keep huge federal agencies open arrive at his desk, and there 
seems little reason for him to give ground beforehand. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides say they want to use the $1.9 trillion portion of the  
projected surplus to reduce the accumulated national debt, which 
would indirectly help Social Security by reducing federal interest 
payments and strengthening the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans want to use the bulk of the rest for a tax cut.  
Clinton wants to use the non-Social Security surplus for Medicare, 
other domestic programs, debt reduction and a modest tax cut. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
