<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico To Increase Duty-Free Limit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EL PASO, Texas (AP) -- Businesses along the Texas-Mexico border  
from El Paso to Brownsville could benefit from a change in Mexican 
customs charges, but just around Christmas. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mexican government announced Tuesday that it will raise its  
duty-free limit on U.S. goods to $300 during the Christmas 
holidays, but only for Mexican nationals who live more than 100 
miles from the border. Everyone else will be kept to the $50 limit. 
</P>
<P>
	The new duty-free limit will be in effect from Dec. 1 to Jan.  
10, one of the border's biggest shopping periods. 
</P>
<P>
	Although it was greeted here with enthusiasm, some business  
owners said it falls short of what they had hoped for because of 
the distance restriction. 
</P>
<P>
	Alonso Flores, spokesman for the Central Business Association,  
told the El Paso Times that anything to improve duty-free shopping 
was appreciated. He added, however, that ``we have a free trade 
agreement with Mexico, and we need to remove all the barriers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, Mexico allows just $50 worth of U.S. goods duty-free  
per person per trip, with a limit of $400 a month. The United 
States has a duty-free limit on merchandise from Mexico of $400 per 
person per month. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the North American Free Trade Agreement went into effect  
in 1994, the $50 limit has been a sore point between the two 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, Mexico refused to raise the limit, arguing that to do  
so would give U.S. businesses an unfair advantage over their 
Mexican counterparts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
