<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sound Bites: Audio Reviews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	``50-Odd Dollars'' (Razor &AMP; Tie) -- Fred Eaglesmith  

</P>
<P>
	Fred Eaglesmith can do sensitive as well as most anybody when  
he's so inclined, but lately many of his tales of lives on the 
fringe and loves gone bad have been enveloped in a loud, frenzied, 
hard-country, surf guitar-meets-bluegrass. And then he hangs out 
with the Clash style that has been known to blow the roof off small 
buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	That said, ``50-Odd Dollars'' is mostly a rock 'n' roll album  
and might offend some of the folk fans who have accepted Eaglesmith 
as one of their own. And it's the kind that demands you turn your 
stereo up all the way. But lyrically, it covers much of the same 
territory as earlier albums, with Eaglesmith spinning his tales in 
an economical style that says more with fewer words. ``I walk 
around in shoes,'' moans the brokenhearted country boy in ``Rodeo 
Boy,'' and those five words capture his plight perfectly. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By Eric Fidler, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Press On'' (Risk/Small Hairy Dog) -- June Carter Cash  

</P>
<P>
	While the relaxed, homespun feel might put some off, June Carter  
Cash and a small group of outstanding musicians have made a 
wonderful album, full of the sort of hilarity, hard truth and rough 
beauty country radio is so allergic to but which country music at 
its finest does so well. Cash mixes spiritual numbers with a goofy 
tale of life in New York City and a funny piece of advice to a 
granddaughter who wants to be an actress. She also recaptures 
``Will the Circle Be Unbroken'' from sing-along territory. ``Press 
On'' is highly recommended for fans of real country and folk. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By Eric Fidler, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Simple Gearle'' (Gearle Records) -- Stacey Earle  

</P>
<P>
	The many pleasures of ``Simple Gearle'' unfold slowly, growing  
richer as the songs take on familiarity with repeated listening. 
There's nothing flashy about the arrangements, playing or singing -- 
just heartfelt words from a singer with a plainspoken voice and 
simple musical arrangements. ``Simple Gearle'' is a charming album 
that stakes out a spot where folk and country meet. It is sure to 
appeal to fans of early Nanci Griffith or Iris Dement. And yes, 
Stacey Earle is Steve Earle's sister. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By Eric Fidler, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Milk'' (Curve) -- Swoon  

</P>
<P>
	``Milk'' is not about songs so much as it is about mood. And in  
a genre in which different artists increasingly sound alike, Swoon 
is able to stand apart with ``Milk,'' a spooky, ethereal journey 
through the best electronic instrumental music trip-hop has to 
offer. 
</P>
<P>
	The trio consists of a computer programmer/keyboardist who calls  
himself Flanj, a guitarist who goes by the name hood and a drummer 
named mr. b. They make a nice transition from the piano-dominated 
``Slouch,'' which opens the disc and sets the tone of laid-back 
angst, to the nervy ``Pepsi, cigarettes, and all that,'' which 
starts off sounding like just another movie track, but becomes 
addictive with its sinuous beat. 
</P>
<P>
	An inspired and sublime effort.  
</P>
<P>
	-- James Pilcher, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Mirrorball'' (Arista) -- Sarah McLachlan  

</P>
<P>
	It would only figure that one of the driving forces behind  
Lilith Fair, one of the most successful concert tour concepts ever, 
would release a live album of her own. But the surprising thing is 
that Sarah McLachlan's ``Mirrorball'' isn't the Canadian singer's 
vocal range and power. Rather the way the songs themselves stand up 
to live treatment is the delight of the record. The opening 
``Building a Mystery'' turns into a fiery anthem; the sweetly sung 
ballad ``I Love You'' is given an added dimension by the live 
arrangement; and ``Sweet Surrender,'' one of McLachlan's best-known 
songs, is turned into a stripped-down rocker that still retains its 
sophistication. Lilith Fair proved that women can be live rock 
attractions, and ``Mirrorball'' shows why McLachlan was the best 
person to carry the message. 
</P>
<P>
	-- James Pilcher, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Come by Me'' (Columbia) -- Harry Connick Jr.  

</P>
<P>
	On his latest collection of vocal jazz, Harry Connick Jr. adds a  
little something else, namely himself. After his failed electric 
jazz-funk-fusion experiment, ``She,'' Connick has refocused himself 
on what he does best, taking almost full control of this project 
and his 16-piece big band and a full orchestra. And he doesn't miss 
a step, whether it be a cover of the Henry Mancini standard, 
``Charade'' (which features some of the most confident vocal 
phrasing of Connick's career), or his cute rhyming on ``Nowhere 
With Love.'' The music itself may not be original -- a takeoff on 
what Frank Sinatra perfected halfway through the century. But by 
taking it -- and himself further -- Connick has made himself into an 
American original. 
</P>
<P>
	-- James Pilcher, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``14:59'' (Lava/Atlantic) -- Sugar Ray  

</P>
<P>
	Sugar Ray is one of those bands that you love to hate. Or you  
hate to love, depending on your perspective. Two years ago, it was 
the can't-get-it-out-of-your-head summertime single ``Fly.'' Now, 
the California quintet is back with more on ``14:59,'' which has 
already produced three mindlessly catchy songs in ``Every 
Morning,'' ``Falls Apart'' and ``Someday'' that radio can't seem to 
get enough of, and therefore, neither can listeners. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sugar Ray can't be faulted for being able to come up with  
great hooks that include light power chords mixed in with some rap 
bravado. And the band does stretch out on the punky ``Aim for Me'' 
and the Brian-Wilson influenced ``Ode to the Lonely Hearted.'' With 
an album such as this, it would be easy to dismiss Sugar Ray as 
nothing but ear candy. But they've now produced three top-selling 
albums. 
</P>
<P>
	It's time to look forward to 2001 -- or brace for it.  
</P>
<P>
	-- James Pilcher, Associated Press Writer.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
