<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dukakis Takes on London Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- In a city accustomed to bravura performances from  
theatrical Dames like Judi Dench and Maggie Smith, London can add 
an American showstopper to its ranks in the stooped, graying form 
of Olympia Dukakis. 
</P>
<P>
	Offstage, there's nothing remotely hunched about Dukakis, a  
vigorous actress now in her 60s (she won't give her exact age) who 
remains best known for her Academy Award-winning role 12 years ago 
as Cher's voluble Italian mama in ``Moonstruck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But as the title -- and only -- character of Martin Sherman's new  
play ``Rose,'' Dukakis must hold both the stage and an audience for 
more than two hours as she unfolds a sprawling, personal narrative 
that also touches on the collective experience of European Jewry 
throughout the 20th century. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rose,'' which opened June 24 in the Cottesloe, the smallest of  
the National's three playhouses, will run in repertory at the 
complex until September. 
</P>
<P>
	When we first see her on stage, taking her seat on a bench that  
she won't leave during either of two substantial acts, Rose looks 
back reluctantly on a life in which, as she recalls dryly, she 
experienced her first period and her first pogrom the same month. 
</P>
<P>
	Husbands come and go, as do cities and countries that she has  
either fled or feared. Somehow, through it all, Rose survives to 
become an 80-year-old Miami grandmother who finds herself sitting 
shiva -- the Jewish ritual of mourning -- for a 9-year-old girl who 
was shot in the head. (To give the girl's identity would spoil a 
major surprise of the play.) 
</P>
<P>
	``Rose'' is the first play in three years by Sherman, the  
expatriate American dramatist of ``When She Danced,'' ``Some Sunny 
Day'' and ``A Madhouse in Goa.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A longtime resident of west London's Notting Hill neighborhood,  
the Philadelphia-born Sherman previously dealt with the Holocaust 
in what remains his best-known play, ``Bent,'' about the 
persecution of homosexuals in the World War II death camps. 
</P>
<P>
	At least superficially, ``Rose'' is a lighter piece that often  
wears its humor on its sleeve (``I like to be au courant,'' Rose 
says of her fondness for Ben and Jerry's peanut butter vanilla ice 
cream). But behind the levity is a requiem for an identifiably 
Jewish compassion and empathy that, Sherman suggests, may not last 
into the next century. 
</P>
<P>
	Or as her son, Abbie, angrily tells her, ``Your shadows will  
choke us to death.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dukakis' films include ``Steel Magnolias'' and the ``Look Who's  
Talking'' series. On TV, she was the pot-smoking earth mother, Mrs. 
Madrigal, in the two ``Tales of the City'' sagas. She is also first 
cousin to Michael Dukakis, the failed presidential candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	For Dukakis, who talked about her work early one evening during  
previews of the play, ``Rose'' marks a new career challenge at a 
time when many performers of a certain age find it ever-harder to 
get roles. 
</P>
<P>
	``The part is wonderful; the challenge is awesome,'' she says.  
``Martin (Sherman) wanted the play done here, and that was fine. 
It's an honor to be here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The honor brought its own headaches, however.  
</P>
<P>
	``I thought, `I can't do this. I don't know how to do this.' I'm  
still not sure I know how, but it's slowly beginning to happen. The 
play's beginning to evolve,'' she says. 
</P>
<P>
	Half an hour into one of the May preview shows, Dukakis left the  
stage rattled by the demands of the text. She returned after 
several minutes and completed the play to a rousing ovation. 
</P>
<P>
	Lest she lose her way, she wears an earpiece for prompts.  
</P>
<P>
	``You want to feel on top of the material,'' she explains,  
giving a shrug one senses that Rose would enjoy, ``and yet you're 
playing someone who's not on top of the material of the moments in 
her life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The play, she says, is ``like milk on a table; it's moving  
around. I'd never done a one-woman show before, and certainly not 
one that requires this degree of emotional commitment and variety 
and range. This is really extraordinary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The London critics agree, at least as regards her performance,  
which received a rare standing ovation on opening night in a city 
famously chary of such displays. 
</P>
<P>
	Although some reviewers faulted the writing, they praised what  
The Independent On Sunday called ``a stunning debut'' achieved 
``through sheer stamina.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Dukakis doesn't steal the show. She makes it,'' said The  
Evening Standard. 
</P>
<P>
	Dukakis is of Greek extraction. But she said a life lived as a  
self-described ``ethnic'' enabled her to identify with a 
Ukrainian-American Jew, just as she did with the feisty mother in 
``Moonstruck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She says she shares with Rose a sense of not belonging. ``It's  
very lively in me. It's not something that is cast away because I'm 
first generation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At school in the Boston suburbs, Dukakis felt marginalized --  
``absolutely because of the name.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The interesting thing is that all the other kids were from  
some other country, but in my mind they were all Americans,'' she 
says. ``Irish, French, Armenians, Germans -- these are the people we 
fought on the streets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More recently, Dukakis has had to face the separate sidelining  
that comes with not being part of the New York theater mainstream, 
despite running The Whole Theater across the Hudson River in New 
Jersey for almost 20 years. (She relinquished that position in 
1990, at which time the theater closed.) 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had not too friendly a time in New York, I would say,''  
says Dukakis, who later this year is moving back to the city from 
New Jersey to take an apartment with Louis Zorich, her 
actor-husband of 38 years, with whom she has three children. 
</P>
<P>
	``They seem to prefer to import British things,'' she says of  
New York tastes, aware that, with this London debut, she now is 
exactly that. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe,'' she says, her hazel eyes widening in anticipation,  
``they'll import me.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
