<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Villeneuve Looking To British GP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SILVERSTONE, England (AP) -- Jacques Villeneuve won the British  
Grand Prix twice in the past three years. This year, though, he'd 
settle for just finishing the race in his first season driving for 
the new British American Racing team. 
</P>
<P>
	Villeneuve left the successful Williams team for his current  
team and says he's one frustrated driver as the championship 
reaches the halfway mark this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew it was going to be a difficult start for a new team,  
but I did think that we would have achieved some better results by 
now,'' Villeneuve said. 
</P>
<P>
	The British-based team burst onto the F1 scene with a big budget  
and big ambitions, predicting a win in its opening race. But its 
best finish has been a seventh-place achieved by Mika Salo at the 
San Marino Grand Prix. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is easy for people to forget that we are a first-year team  
and that we are quicker than first-year teams have ever been,'' 
Villeneuve said. ``But we are way below our own expectations, and 
that's why it is frustrating. We came in as a big team so we are 
not seen or judged as a new team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadian driver said technical problems had hindered his  
progress but he was expecting the situation to improve. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been OK at Silverstone in the past and I am happy to go  
there,'' he said. ``Our car seems better in high-speed corners than 
slow ones, so we could be good at Silverstone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Team chief Craig Pollock said the team had performed below  
expectations but learned from every race. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've covered a huge amount of ground very quickly and that  
may be one of the reasons we haven't yet achieved the results we 
want,'' he said. ``We are now confident that we have cars that can 
get to the finish. We have progressed competitively, but we are 
fully aware that the other teams have, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, after overhauling Ferrari driver Michael Schumacher's  
early lead in the drivers' championship, McLaren's defending world 
champion Mika Hakkinen says he has the momentum. 
</P>
<P>
	Schumacher took an early lead in the standings after  
back-to-back wins at San Marino and Monaco, but since then Hakkinen 
won in Spain and Canada to reclaim the No. 1 spot. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-year-old Finn also finished second behind Jordan's  
Heinz-Harald Frentzen in the French GP 10 days ago after lining up 
14th on the grid, while Schumacher finished fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you look at our results it looks as though the balance of  
power is shifting our way,'' Hakkinen said. ``We have won a couple 
of races in a row and Magny-Cours (French GP) was also brilliant. I 
was only able to do that because the car the team gave me was 
great. But it is still very close with Ferrari all the time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hakkinen, who edged Schumacher for the championship in the final  
race last season, said anything could happen in the next nine 
races. 
</P>
<P>
	``The championship is tough at the moment and of course Michael  
is just eight points behind,'' he said. ``But I feel confident, 
quite comfortable at the moment.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
