<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unity Conference To Formally Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                         *BY KAREN GAUDETTE   	
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Newspapers and broadcasters risk losing  
credibility if their staffs don't reflect the diversity of the 
communities they cover, panelists at a minority journalists 
conference said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of the people who cover the news and make the decision  
about what gets covered are still overwhelmingly white and male,'' 
Catalina Camia, president of Unity: Journalists of Color Inc., said 
Tuesday. ``It's time for editors to rethink the issue of diversity, 
because the credibility of your news product is at stake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some 6,000 minority journalists from around the country were  
expected to attend the Unity conference, which was to formally open 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we're saying, in effect, is that communities of color,  
communities that are not white, need to be treated in the same way 
as upper middle-class white communities in terms of coverage. 
That's revolutionary,'' said Ellis Cose, a contributing editor at 
Newsweek. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a survey of minority journalists released today found  
grim prospects for retaining minorities in newsrooms. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey of more than 450 minority print journalists at U.S.  
daily newspapers of 25,000-plus circulation found more than half 
expected to leave the newspaper business within the next five 
years. Most cited low pay, poor hours and lack of opportunities for 
professional development. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 50 percent gave their newspapers a ``C'' grade or  
lower in their coverage of minority communities. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey, conducted by the Freedom Forum's Media Studies  
Center in New York, also found that 61 percent liked their current 
jobs ``very much,'' and that 81 percent would choose journalism as 
a career if they had it to do over again. 
</P>
<P>
	Minorities currently account for 26 percent of the U.S.  
population, according to Census Bureau figures. In its 1998 survey 
of newsroom employment, the American Society of Newspaper Editors 
found that black, Asian, Hispanic and American Indian journalists 
accounted for about 11 percent of newspaper editors, reporters and 
photographers -- about the same as the previous year's figure. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
