<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Books and Authors: Germaine Greer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAFFRON WALDON, England (AP) -- When all the lights in Germaine  
Greer's farmhouse went out recently, she checked the fuses, then 
rang the electric company to report a fault. But the male duty 
officer insisted no one else had a problem -- and inquired curtly 
whether she had checked her fuses. 
</P>
<P>
	``So I looked beyond my garden and there were blue sparks  
shooting into the sky and a team of people working on the line and 
it turned out to be a major fault,'' she recalls in her broad 
Australian tones, distractedly scraping long fingers through her 
short, gray hair. 
</P>
<P>
	``I rang back and the duty officer said, 'Oh yes,' there was a  
fault noted on his log. He just hadn't read the log. If I was a 
man, he wouldn't have treated me that way -- but I'm a middle-aged 
woman, so it's OK.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some would argue that any caller could have received the same  
response. But Greer believes it illustrates the way women are still 
trivialized and degraded, 30 years after she wrote her landmark 
treatise, ``The Female Eunuch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of the second millennium, women can be prime  
ministers and company presidents. 
</P>
<P>
	But Greer notes that millions of women are still slaving in  
Asian sweatshops for almost nothing-an-hour, wearily raising 
families alone and mutilating their bodies to conform to male 
ideals of feminine beauty. 
</P>
<P>
	Irked by the ``lifestyle feminists'' who claim today's women can  
``have it all,'' the fiery, feisty Greer has written the book ``I 
swore I would never write,'' a major stock-taking of the state of 
women's liberation called ``The Whole Woman.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Published in Britain in March, it became available on U.S.  
bookshelves in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of being liberated to lead valued, joyous lives, Greer  
argues, women have been sold a dud ideal of equality that dictates 
they become like men in order to succeed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just look at Mrs. Thatcher,'' she says, referring to Britain's  
tough-as-nails former prime minister. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's society, she says, is ``far more masculinist'' than it  
was three decades ago, with films, video games and popular music 
all peddling brutish misogyny. 
</P>
<P>
	``On every side, we see women troubled, exhausted, mutilated,  
lonely, guilty, mocked by the headlined success of the few,'' she 
writes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reality of women's lives is work, most of it unpaid and,  
what is worse, unappreciated. Every day we hear of women abused; 
every day we hear of new kinds of atrocities perpetrated on the 
minds and bodies of women; yet every day we are told there is 
nothing left to fight for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It is time to get angry again,'' the book says.  
</P>
<P>
	And that Greer clearly is, a taut figure in trademark gray (a  
form of semi-mourning adopted during the Gulf War), coiled on the 
edge of a sofa at her home a few miles from Cambridge University, 
where she teaches women's studies. She is also professor of English 
and Comparative Literary Studies at Warwick University. 
</P>
<P>
	She grows vegetables, bakes her own bread and runs a  
rambunctious household that embraces nine geese, a cat, several 
dogs and a variety of lodgers. 
</P>
<P>
	Time -- Greer is now 60 -- has not eroded the intellectual ardor  
of the woman who once demolished Norman Mailer in debate. 
</P>
<P>
	More striking than her photographs depict, she is an intriguing,  
frustrating mixture of contradiction and candor, her speech a 
tumble of expletives illuminated by a sharp, darting wit. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman who once posed naked for a Dutch porn magazine berates  
singer Courtney Love in ``The Whole Woman'' for flaunting her body. 
</P>
<P>
	And she asserts, sweepingly, that ``some men hate all women all  
of the time; all men hate some women some of the time.'' Yet she 
confesses, ``I like men. They have given me the best times of my 
life -- and the worst.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Greer, the whole, liberated woman is comfortable with her  
body -- womb, breasts, menstrual blood and all. 
</P>
<P>
	She ``does not exist to embody male sexual fantasies or rely  
upon a man to endow her with identity and social status.'' And she 
``does not have to be beautiful ... can be clever (and) will grow 
in authority as she ages.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Greer says, we get Barbie, the pouting plastic goddess  
who sells by the million, purveying an ersatz ideal of frilly 
femininity to little girls. The ideal Barbie woman is blond, 
barrel-breasted and brainless. Significantly, Greer notes, she is 
also silent. 
</P>
<P>
	So women have allowed doctors to flood their systems with  
chemical contraceptives, trim and tuck their bodies and perform 
unnecessary caesareans and hysterectomies, she says. 
</P>
<P>
	They ``are driven through the health system like sheep through a  
dip. The disease they are being treated for is womanhood,'' she 
writes. 
</P>
<P>
	In relationships, women still take the blame; in the home, they  
do most of the labor, she says. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Greer confesses that she's changed her mind on some  
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	In ``The Female Eunuch,'' she insisted that motherhood was not a  
substitute career. ``Now,'' she says, ``I would argue that 
motherhood should be regarded as a genuine career option ... as 
paid work and, as such, an alternative to other paid work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She also once condemned female circumcision as barbaric  
mutilation demanded by men. But after traveling in the 
``woman-centered, child-infested cultures'' of countries like 
Sudan, she says she has realized that such practices can have 
ritual and social value in some cultures. 
</P>
<P>
	The critics are divided on ``The Whole Woman.''  
</P>
<P>
	``Will young women come flocking to this call? Unlikely, I  
think,'' wrote Ros Coward in The Guardian newspaper. ``The days for 
feminist fundamentalism have gone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But American feminist Camille Paglia said that while most  
British feminists have ``wasted their lives sitting around in 
discussion groups like atheists looking for a new religion, Greer 
got out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's time for Greer to take the stage again,'' Paglia said,  
``and I'm glad that she is.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 08:38:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Says Kosovo Turmoil Falling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Despite more reports of ethnic  
violence, NATO and U.N. officials said today that turmoil has 
declined sharply since peacekeepers arrived and it soon will be up 
to Kosovo's people to keep the peace themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	``The situation is progressively improving,'' said NATO  
spokesman Louis Garneau. ``The people of Kosovo must now turn to 
peaceful means to resolve their differences. The conflict is 
over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, NATO troops remain essential for maintaining the  
peace, as evidenced today when a large, well-armed escort by French 
soldiers and police prevented violence from erupting during a march 
by ethnic Albanians through the Serb-held section of the divided 
city of Kosovska Mitrovica. 
</P>
<P>
	About 5,000 ethnic Albanians, closely guarded by the French  
peacekeepers, marched across a bridge dividing the northern Kosovo 
town and through the Serb sector. The crowd chanted ``Albania, 
Albania'' and ``U-C-K, U-C-K,'' the Albanian-language initials for 
the Kosovo Liberation Army. 
</P>
<P>
	Serbs retorted with shouts of ``Serbia! Serbia!'' Despite some  
stone throwing and flag burning by both sides at the disputed 
bridge, the hourlong march came off without serious violence, no 
small feat in a city that has come to symbolize Kosovo's ethnic 
divide. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO and the United Nations have been brokering talks aimed at  
defusing tension in the town since Serbs blocked the bridge several 
weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Garneau condemned scattered acts of violence elsewhere in  
Kosovo, including an incident in the town of Lipljan, south of 
Pristina, in which 10 Serb doctors and nurses allegedly were 
assaulted by the Albanian staff at a clinic. 
</P>
<P>
	He said a Serb also reported she and her husband had been beaten  
in the southern Kosovo town of Urosevac, and a Canadian helicopter 
was fired on, but not hit, during a routine patrol over Pristina. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO has struggled to restrain returning ethnic Albanian  
refugees from taking revenge on minority Serbs who subjected them 
to brutal abuse during the Kosovo conflict. At least 60,000 Serbs 
have fled the province for fear of reprisals. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. spokesman Kevin Kennedy said the deployment of civilian  
police from other countries should help curb the violence. ``But 
the bottom line is that unless there is concerted effort on the 
part of political leaders and individuals ... to restrain 
themselves .. there's really very little we can do to stop random 
acts of violence,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO's mission has been complicated by the unexpectedly rapid  
return of refugees to Kosovo since the alliance's 78-day bombing 
campaign forced Yugoslavia's government to accept a peace plan and 
pull out its troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Of an estimated 860,000 Albanians who fled or were expelled from  
Kosovo during the conflict, more than 600,000 have returned since 
NATO peacekeepers began arriving June 12. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO is hoping the deployment of Russian peacekeepers will help  
calm Serb fears. Russia, a traditional Slavic ally of Serbia, is 
sending 3,600 troops to supplement the 55,000 planned by NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	Planeloads of Russian troops and equipment arrived Tuesday,  
formally ending a stalemate with NATO over their deployment, and 
more are expected to arrive daily to work alongside NATO troops. 
For now, they are remaining close to the airport outside Pristina 
while final details about their deployment are settled, Garneau 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new agreement with NATO, the Russians will be deployed  
in Orahovac and Malisevo in the German sector, at Kosovsko Kamenica 
in the American sector, and at Lausa in the French sector. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, opposition leaders in Yugoslavia said they would step  
up protests to demand the resignation of President Slobodan 
Milosevic, who is widely blamed for the Kosovo conflict and has 
been indicted for crimes against humanity by a U.N. tribunal in The 
Hague. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the opposition remains sharply divided, its leaders have  
been bolstered by growing protests, including two Tuesday in the 
cities of Leskovac and Uzice. Some leaders speak of calling a 
general strike to force Milosevic to resign. 
</P>
<P>
	Many accuse Milosevic of virtually losing Kosovo, a southern  
province of Serbia, the dominant republic in what remains of 
Yugoslavia. Though many Serbs regard Kosovo as the cradle of their 
culture and Serbian Orthodox religion, its prewar population of 2 
million was 90 percent ethnic Albanian. 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic cast his crackdown in the province as a battle against  
terrorist-led secessionists. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
