<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Coca-Cola Settles Claim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- The company producing Coca-Cola in  
Portugal reached an out-of-court settlement Wednesday with a man 
who alleged he was blinded when one of the soft drink bottles 
exploded in his face, according to news reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Joao Redondo had demanded compensation from Refrige, which  
produces Coca-Cola in Portugal under license, for injuries he 
allegedly sustained in 1991 while working in a cafe. 
</P>
<P>
	A court in Figueira da Foz, 90 miles north of Lisbon, was to  
start hearing the case Wednesday but the two sides told the judge 
they had reached an agreement, the Portuguese news agency Lusa 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither side would give details of the settlement.  
</P>
<P>
	Redondo had demanded $324,000 from Refrige but the company  
refused, and he had rejected their earlier counteroffer of $16,000, 
Lusa reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Redondo alleged the bottle exploded as he put down a crate of  
Coca-Cola bottles on a counter of the cafe where he was working 
during his summer vacation, according to Lusa. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he suffered injuries to his face and chest and lost his  
eyesight. He was 14 at the time. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
