<DOCNO> APW19990707.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 11:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Auto Plant Makes 28,000 Trucks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Ford and Mazda's joint assembly plant  
in Thailand has produced 28,000 vehicles in its first year of 
operations and is aiming for 65,000 this year, executives said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant produces Ford Ranger and Mazda Fighter pickups and is  
operated under the AutoAllance joint venture by the U.S. and 
Japanese automakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Since production began July 1, 1998, AutoAlliance has exported  
18,694 pickups, about evenly split between the two brands, making 
the venture the second-largest auto exporter after Mitsubishi. 
</P>
<P>
	Export earnings were about $40 million.  
</P>
<P>
	David Snyder, president of Ford Operations (Thailand), told a  
news conference marking the anniversary of the plant that the 
export targets for the second year are 40,000 to 45,000 pickups. 
</P>
<P>
	The group's domestic strategy faces a major hurdle since the  
government has still not ruled whether the four-door Ranger model 
is a pickup, which is taxed at 5 percent, or a sedan, taxed at 43 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-door model currently is only exported.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 18:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Toyota To Shed Seniority Pay System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Breaking with Japanese corporate tradition, Toyota  
Motor Corp. said Wednesday it plans to adopt a new pay system based 
on performance rather than seniority. 
</P>
<P>
	The new arrangement, which the automaker hopes to launch in  
October, is intended to encourage employees to work harder by 
rewarding them for their achievements, Toyota spokesman Tomomi Imai 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think this will improve our company's performance,'' Imai  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota, like most large Japanese companies, has traditionally  
given management-track workers automatic pay raises as they got 
older. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers will still receive these regular pay raises under the  
new system. The amount they get, however, will be based on 
performance instead of age, Imai said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company will ask its labor union to agree to the new payment  
plan in August, and once in place, about 20,000 of Toyota's 70,000 
employees in Japan will be affected, Imai said. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that the new system will only affect lower-level  
managers. Top Toyota executives are already paid on a merit-based 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	The automaker's announcement comes as Japanese companies across  
the board are scrambling for ways to increase productivity and 
innovation through new management styles and drastic labor cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent months, corporate giants like Mitsubishi Electric  
Corp. and Sony Corp. have announced plans to slim operations and 
cut thousands of workers -- straying from Japan's long tradition of 
lifetime employment. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, many electronics and computer companies have  
adopted performance-based pay scales to spur creative thinking 
among engineers. 
</P>
<P>
	Even major appliance-maker Hitachi, long criticized as  
inflexible, has slashed its work force and adopted a casual dress 
policy -- something company officials say is to emphasize ``respect 
for the individual.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota is the first of Japan's automakers to completely abolish  
its seniority-based wage system. Many, however, say it may not be 
the last. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've seen all kinds of companies adopting this kind of  
policy,'' said Satoko Hiwatari, who studies labor trends for 
Nikkeiren, an influential business group. ``Everything is pointing 
in this direction.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 01:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> $1M Lien Levied on Frankel Estates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) -- A judge has levied a $1 million lien on  
two estates owned by fugitive financier Martin Frankel. 
</P>
<P>
	The lien was attached at the request of David Rosse, Frankel's  
former bodyguard, who is suing the missing money manager for 
allegedly connecting him to a fraudulent charity, The Greenwich 
Time reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The 44-year-old financier, accused of embezzling at least $215  
million from insurance companies in five states, is wanted on 
federal wire fraud and money laundering charges. Also missing is as 
much as $1.98 billion from the St. Francis of Assisi Foundation, a 
purported charity established in the British Virgin Islands. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities say Frankel used the alias ``David Rosse'' to set up  
the charity. Rosse last week sued Frankel for more than $1 million, 
charging misappropriation of his name. 
</P>
<P>
	Superior Court Judge Frank D'Andrea Jr. signed the lien Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	Frankel has been missing since May 5, when firefighters called  
to his mansion found a blazing file cabinet and two fireplaces 
stuffed with burning documents. Left behind was a to-do list -- item 
No. 1: ``Launder money'' -- and astrological charts designed to 
answer such questions as ``Will I go to prison?'' 
</P>
<P>
	He is believed to have fled to Europe.  
</P>
<P>
	The Hartford Courant reported today that Frankel may be  
financing his life on the run with $10 million in diamonds he 
bought shortly before disappearing. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper said Frankel transferred $10 million to the  
Beverly Hills branch of an Israeli bank, where it was deposited 
into the account of World Wide Diamond, an international wholesaler 
based in Los Angeles. The FBI is attempting to seize the $10 
million from the diamond company. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Wiener, who operates World Wide Diamond, declined to  
comment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
