<DOCNO> APW19990707.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 17:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Orders Election at Shipyard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Union organizers at the Avondale shipyard  
must hold a new union election because the one held more than six 
years ago was ``fatally flawed,'' the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of 
Appeal ruled Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 3,850 workers who voted should have had to do more than give  
their names -- especially since the National Labor Relations Board 
knew that hundreds of votes would be challenged, Judge Edith H. 
Jones wrote for a unanimous three-judge panel. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one knows exactly who voted in the Avondale election,''  
Jones wrote. The company also raised serious questions about 
possible vote fraud, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	A union attorney called the ruling bizarre, saying the NLRB has  
used the same identification procedure for 60 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's ruling came as Avondale prepared for a July 27  
merger with Litton Industries Inc., which owns Ingalls Shipyard in 
nearby Pascagoula, Miss. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither union attorney Bill Lurye or company attorney Keith  
Pyburn would talk about how the merger will affect the chances of 
union representation at Avondale. 
</P>
<P>
	There's no way to hold another election before the merger, said  
Lurye, adding that it's too soon to say whether the union will 
appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Litton spokesman Randy Belote refused to comment on the ruling,  
since shareholders must still vote on the merger July 27. But he 
wouldn't rule out a union at Avondale. 
</P>
<P>
	``Litton enjoys a very good relationship with its union and has  
a close working relationship with the leaders of its union in its 
yard in Pascagoula,'' Belote said. ``We would expect that type of 
relationship to continue in Avondale once we conclude the 
acquisition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The New Orleans Metal Trades Council had claimed a 600-vote  
victory immediately after the 1993 election, which Judge Jones 
characterized as ``contentious and bitter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The union challenged 850 votes, but after a recount the NLRB  
gave the union a 250-vote majority. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
