<DOCNO> APW19990707.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 11:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Consumers Buying More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- In what may be a sign of optimism for Japan's  
economy, consumers are buying more computers and compact cars and 
plan to travel more this summer -- though many are targeting 
discount models and low-fares. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan Travel Bureau estimated that the number of people planning  
trips in July and August rose 2.5 percent from last year, a 
spokesman for the travel agency said today. The increase follows a 
3 percent decline in overseas travel last summer as recession-weary 
consumers cut back. 
</P>
<P>
	Behind the increase this summer is a ``recovery in consumer  
sentiment,'' said JTB spokesman Tsuyoshi Kurata. 
</P>
<P>
	But the survey also showed that Japanese are choosing less  
exotic, and cheaper, destinations so that even though there will be 
more travelers, they will only spend about the same amount as last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase in discount-travel is part of a broader shift away  
from high-priced, name-brand products, as Japan's once famously 
haughty consumers look for value in tough economic times. 
</P>
<P>
	Some economists said the trend is encouraging because it shows  
that more people are willing to open their purse strings. 
</P>
<P>
	An increase in consumer spending is seen as crucial for recovery  
because it accounts for about two-thirds of Japan's economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's gross domestic product -- the measure of all goods and  
services produced within its borders -- rose 1.9 percent in the 
first quarter but much of the growth came from government, not 
private, spending. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase in travel wasn't the only recent bright sign.  
</P>
<P>
	Sales of personal computers are soaring this summer, said  
Yoshiharu Satake, a spokesman for Yodobashi Camera, one of Tokyo's 
largest computer and electronics retailers. 
</P>
<P>
	The company wouldn't disclose exact figures, but Satake said  
computer sales in the last month were about three times higher than 
a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	And while sales of most cars have been falling in recent months,  
there's been a surge in demand for low-priced compact models. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of the so-called mini-vehicles -- a special category of  
low-power cars that are cheaper to license and insure -- rose 29 
percent in June compared to year ago to 165,466 cars, a trade 
association said. Sales of the cars have risen by double-digits 
every month since October. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, spending by Japanese households in May rose 2.4 percent  
from a year earlier, marking the first pickup in four months, the 
Management and Coordination Agency said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Increases were registered for housing, transportation and  
communications, the agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The consumption trend is clearly up,'' said Richard Werner,  
chief economist for Profit Research Center in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Werner said he believes consumer spending is even stronger than  
the recent numbers indicate. 
</P>
<P>
	That's in part because those figures focus too much on sales at  
high-priced department stores and not enough on the discount stores 
and supermarkets where a growing number of people are shopping, he 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
