<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 08:37:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serb Politician Accused </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- A former Bosnian Serb Cabinet  
minister planned a campaign of terror and murder to drive non-Serbs 
from parts of Bosnia in 1992, according to a U.N. indictment 
unsealed today, a day after his arrest by NATO troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Radislav Brdjanin, 51, is the most senior Bosnian Serb civilian  
official yet to be brought to the U.N. war crimes tribunal for 
trial. He arrived at the tribunal's detention unit late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment revealed details of a campaign of persecution  
that Brdjanin, now a lawmaker in the Bosnian Serb parliament, 
allegedly instituted to drive Muslims and Croats from the regions 
of Prijedor and Sanski Most in northwest Bosnia. 
</P>
<P>
	The former civil engineer, who served briefly as Bosnian Serb  
prime minister in the early part of the 1992-95 Bosnian war, 
allegedly helped design and execute a three-point plan aimed at 
ethnic purges. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan involved first pressuring non-Serbs to flee by creating  
``impossible conditions involving pressure and terror tactics,'' 
the indictment claims. Those who refused to leave allegedly were 
physically forced from their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	The chilling final stage was ``to liquidate those non-Serbs who  
remained,'' according to the indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say Brdjanin was president of a so-called crisis  
staff in the region responsible for putting the plan into action in 
1992. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment alleges he ``planned, instigated, ordered,  
committed or otherwise aided and abetted'' attacks on villages, 
killings and the imprisonment of non-Serbs in camps. Hundreds of 
prisoners were killed in the camps. 
</P>
<P>
	Brdjanin was arrested Tuesday in the northern Bosnian city of  
Banja Luka by British troops serving in the NATO-led Stabilization 
Force. His March 12 indictment was kept secret by the tribunal 
until his arrest to prevent him from going into hiding. 
</P>
<P>
	During the Bosnian war, Brdjanin served as minister of  
urbanization in the government of Radovan Karadzic and also has 
been blamed for ordering the destruction of mosques in mainly 
Muslim areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Karadzic, who no longer holds power, twice has been indicted by  
the U.N. war crimes tribunal on genocide charges but remains at 
large. 
</P>
<P>
	Brdjanin was formally charged with persecution, a crime against  
humanity. He faces a maximum sentence of life imprisonment if 
convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	No date was immediately set for his arraignment, at which he  
will be asked to confirm his identity and enter a plea to the 
charge. 
</P>
<P>
	In a related case, the tribunal announced today that judges will  
deliver their verdicts July 15 in prosecution and defense appeals 
of Bosnian Serb Dusan Tadic's 1997 war crimes conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	Tadic, the first defendant to be tried at the U.N. tribunal, was  
sentenced to 20 years imprisonment after being convicted of 
murdering and torturing non-Serbs in the Prijedor region in 1992 -- 
the same period in which Brdjanin allegedly planned atrocities 
there. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
