<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Cop Finds No Pressure in Golf  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Playing in a golf tournament, even  
one as prestigious as the U.S. Senior Open, is no pressure for Ron 
Ferguson. 
</P>
<P>
	Pressure is looking into the barrel of a gun held by an angry  
man who wants to kill you. Pressure is leveling a shotgun at a 
suspect, pulling the trigger and killing him. 
</P>
<P>
	That's the kind of pressure Ferguson faced before retiring from  
the Orlando, Fla., police force to become a professional golfer. 
After that, facing a 10-foot birdie putt to win a tournament hardly 
rates any perspiration. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before I came here, three of my good cop buddies, they were as  
excited as I am,'' said Ferguson, one of the 156 golfers starting 
play in the Senior Open Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of them wrote me a little note and said that he was proud  
of me for being here and that no matter how tough the stress and 
the pressure got, that I have already been through more stress and 
pressure than everybody else put together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His 25-year career as a police officer brought enough stress to  
fill a lifetime. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1974, three years after joining the force, Ferguson was  
pistol whipped and shot twice with his own gun -- in the side and in 
the chest -- by a man he was trying to arrest for murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferguson said bullet wounds in the side didn't hurt. Not so with  
a slug he took in the chest. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am down and he is up over me and he has got the gun pointed  
and I rolled out of the way and the bullet hit me in the chest and 
that one did hurt,'' he said. ``It was very loud and I could feel 
the percussion from the gun shot. 
</P>
<P>
	``And he kept clicking. The gun was out of bullets. He kept  
clicking. I got up and he hit me in the head with the gun a few 
more times. And then I ran to an apartment complex and he ran the 
other way. He got in my car and took off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The man later was apprehended, convicted of murder and executed.  
Ferguson, coughing up blood and his head battered, was hospitalized 
for a week-and-a-half and spent another week-and-a-half 
recuperating at home before returning to work. 
</P>
<P>
	Three years later, Ferguson was on the other end of a shooting.  
He and a partner were staking out a gas station that an informant 
had told them would be robbed. After the stickup, the bandit was 
fleeing the scene and pulling up the mask he had been wearing when 
Ferguson's partner yelled, ``Halt, police.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the man turned and pointed his gun at the other officer,  
Ferguson fired. 
</P>
<P>
	``I shot him with a shotgun, hit him with nine pellets in the  
chest,'' he said. ``I could see the look on his face with the mask 
pulled like that. I could hear the air coming out of his lungs. 
</P>
<P>
	``So he dropped and he was dead right there.''  
</P>
<P>
	After being applauded by his back-slapping fellow officers,  
Ferguson soon found that shooting someone was much harder than 
being shot. He got sick to his stomach and couldn't eat. If he 
tried to eat, he'd throw up. A 6-foot-1, 190-pounder now, his 
weight dropped to between 135 and 140 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I ended up going to the hospital, contemplated suicide and  
finally survived. I pulled out of it,'' Ferguson said. ``I could 
still picture that in my mind, me shooting him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ferguson, 51, who had been a successful amateur golfer in  
Florida, turned pro in October 1996 after retiring from the police 
force that summer. He has made $30,000 so far, which is about what 
he has paid in traveling expenses and entry fees. 
</P>
<P>
	No matter. He's living out a dream, and no one is shooting at  
him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have never been treated so well in all my life,'' Ferguson  
said. ``I have a Cadillac waiting for me at the airport. I've got a 
locker right next to Raymond Floyd and Bruce Fleisher and four 
dozen Titleists. Guys are asking for my autograph, kids, women. It 
is a thrill.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
