<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Western Union Returns To Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- The yellow sign still hangs outside Havana's old  
Western Union office, closed after the United States imposed trade 
sanctions against communist Cuba at the height of the Cold War. 
</P>
<P>
	But under President Clinton's moves to increase contacts between  
people in the United States and Cuba, Western Union is authorized 
to begin sending wire transfers to the island on Thursday, making 
it easier, safer and cheaper for people to send money to their 
loved ones. 
</P>
<P>
	The wire transfer company previously had been permitted to  
handle cash transfers only for emergency expenses or emigration 
costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cuban government holding company Cimex, which will run the  
Western Union operation on the island, in recent months has been 
busy building new Western Union outlets in gas stations and 
supermarkets. One will be located in the year-old Carlos III 
shopping mall, the largest modern commercial center in Havana. 
</P>
<P>
	Cimex officials approached about the new service declined to  
comment, nor would they provide media access to the new Western 
Union offices. 
</P>
<P>
	But one passer-by, who declined to give his name, said Cubans  
were excited about the move. ``If this method is direct, I believe 
it will be much easier for us Cubans who receive money from our 
families in the United States,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	For years Cuban immigrants in the United States have relied on a  
network of agencies with links to businesses in Cuba to get money 
to friends and relatives on the island. Since the collapse of the 
Soviet Union in 1991 sent Cuba into a severe economic crisis, 
Cubans have increasingly depended on cash remittances from 
relatives in the United States just to get by. 
</P>
<P>
	Even the Cuban American National Foundation, a prominent exile  
lobby group that opposes U.S. government moves toward detente with 
President Fidel Castro's government, has come out in favor of the 
resumption of Western Union service. 
</P>
<P>
	Until recently, rules under the U.S. embargo against Cuba  
allowed only family members of Cubans on the island to send up to 
$300 in cash remittances every three months. But under new rules, 
anyone in the United States now can send that amount, as long as 
the money does not go to senior Cuban government or communist party 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Western Union will charge $29 for sending between $200 and $300  
in cash. Agencies now offering the service to Cuba set their own 
prices. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
