<DOCNO> APW19990707.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 20:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Forbes, Keyes Address GOP Activists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Republican presidential candidates Steve  
Forbes and Alan Keyes told party activists Wednesday night the GOP 
must present a substantive message to voters to have any hope of 
winning the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	They made their remarks at a private dinner kicking off the  
Republican National Committee's summer meeting here. It was a tough 
crowd: Many of the delegates have already come out in support of 
Texas Gov. George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Party activist Charles P. Sexton's response was typical:  
``Excellent Republican message. Nobody's swayed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The dinner was closed to reporters, but in an interview Forbes  
said he reminded RNC members that the last Republican convention in 
Philadelphia, in 1948, featured Thomas Dewey as the nominee. 
</P>
<P>
	``They nominated somebody who didn't have a substantive message  
and lost in an upset to a man named Harry Truman,'' Forbes said. 
``I told them that when we have a substantive message, we win, and 
when we don't, we lose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And how was his message received?  
</P>
<P>
	``Very politely and cordially,'' Forbes said. ``I'm not sure  
everyone would agree, but that's what a campaign is for -- to have a 
vigorous and honest debate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes talked of a moral crisis in America, made worse by eight  
years of the Clinton administration. But he reserved his harshest 
words for Bush, who raised a record $36 million in the first six 
months of the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview, Keyes called the Texas governor ``the virtual  
reality candidate'' and a ``fabrication of the money bosses and the 
media.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's millions ``can't buy a single heart, can't change a  
single mind, won't move a single conscience,'' Keyes said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that each of the dollars he gets is a shackle tying  
him to the interests of the monied establishment of this country 
that has shown a willingness to sell out our conscience and even to 
betray our national security. I think it's very suspect,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes, whose personal wealth makes him the only candidate able  
to match Bush dollar for dollar, said ``nine out of 10'' Americans 
aren't yet paying attention to the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``When they do, we're going to be there,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Republicans from across the country will meet here through  
Saturday to plot strategy for next year's elections. It's their 
first trip to Philadelphia since they chose the city to host their 
2000 national convention. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
