<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gay Reporter on Trial in Sex Sting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *BY NOAH ISACKSON   	
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO (AP) -- A gay journalist says he was simply doing  
research for a story on homosexual teens when he showed up at a 
park to see a 13-year-old boy he met on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruce Mirken, 42, went on trial Tuesday, accused of arranging  
for sex with a teen-ager. 
</P>
<P>
	He was arrested a year ago in a Sacramento park where he went to  
meet a gay boy he had conversed with online. Instead he was met by 
an undercover police officer in a sting operation that tracked 
Mirken's e-mail and phone conversations with ``Anthony,'' a 
fictitious boy used to dupe Mirken. 
</P>
<P>
	Mirken could get up to four years in prison if convicted of  
attempting to commit a lewd and lascivious act on a child. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities started investigating Mirken after he answered an  
electronic message posted in a chat room by ``Anthony,'' who said 
he was looking for an adult friend because his last one moved away. 
</P>
<P>
	Mirken, whose stories about gay and lesbian culture have  
appeared in newspapers and magazines including the San Francisco 
Examiner, Miami Herald, Detroit Free Press, Men's Health and Out, 
contends he corresponded with the boy in hopes of writing an 
investigative story about troubled gay youth, not to have sex. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't wait to testify,'' said Mirken, who took notes in a  
spiral notebook throughout Tuesday's opening arguments. ``The 
prosecution's evidence is made up of out-of-context statements and 
half-truths.'' 
</P>
<P>
	First Amendment advocates fear the case may hurt reporters'  
efforts to gather information. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not all that uncommon for a journalist who is dealing  
with the fringes of society to ignore or play along with the 
source,'' said Terry Francke, general counsel for the California 
First Amendment Coalition. ``The whole point is to get the 
information that the journalist is looking for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors told the jury that recorded conversations and e-mail  
records between Mirken -- who used the screen name ``Luvboys343'' -- 
and the boy were sexually charged and filled with flirtatious 
questions such as, ``Do you skinny-dip?'' and ``Does your mother 
come home during lunch?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The defense argued that the boy introduced himself to Mirken as  
lonely and that the questions were not sexual in their proper 
context. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we have are innocent statements by Mr. Mirken and a  
series of sexual responses by the police officer,'' said his 
attorney, Bruce Nickerson. ``What interested Mr. Mirken were 
statements by the boy that sounded like he may be in trouble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Perry Sims said Mirken clearly indicated his sexual  
intentions by arranging to meet the boy in a park nearly 90 miles 
from his home and leaving his notebook and expired press pass in 
his car when he got there. 
</P>
<P>
	Sims said Mirken was arrested carrying $96, the amount the  
undercover officer had said it would cost for them to get a hotel 
room. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 21:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> El Guerrouj Sets Mile Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Hicham El Guerrouj smashed the world record in the  
mile with a time of 3 minutes, 43.13 seconds at the Golden Gala 
meet Wednesday, fighting off Kenya's Noah Ngeny, who also beat the 
old mark. 
</P>
<P>
	In becoming the first Moroccan to hold one of track and field's  
most hallowed records, El Guerrouj shaved 1.26 seconds off the mark 
of 3:44.39 set by Noureddine Morceli of Algeria on Sept. 5, 1993, 
at Rieti, Italy. Ngeny was timed in 3:43.40. 
</P>
<P>
	This was only the third time in 18 years the record was broken.  
</P>
<P>
	It was the second straight year that El Guerrouj set a world  
record at the Golden Gala meet, and each time he erased a mark held 
by Morceli. Last year, he cracked the 1,500-meter record with 
3:26.00. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rome is a magic track for me,'' El Guerrouj said. ``I can't  
compare this year with last year. It's another El Guerrouj. I was 
more concentrated, but the public was the same.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fans supported El Guerrouj, shouting and applauding noisily  
as he rushed to the record. 
</P>
<P>
	El Guerrouj ran a victory lap, waving a Moroccan flag to the  
cheering fans. He dedicated the race to his family and to King 
Hassan of Morocco. 
</P>
<P>
	``I needed to bring some happiness to my family, as my uncle  
died recently,'' he said. ``I hope God continues to give me 
strength because I want to be the strongest in the world at all 
distances between 1,500 and 5,000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After Britain's Sebastian Coe reduced the record to 3:47.33 in  
1981, the mark stood until 1985, when another Briton, Steve Cram, 
lowered it to 3:46.32. Cram's time held for eight years until 
Morceli clipped nearly two seconds off it. 
</P>
<P>
	El Guerrouj, 24, has been almost unbeatable the past four years.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, he won 12 of 13 races at a mile or 1,500 meters, losing  
only in the Olympic 1,500 final when he fell just before the bell 
lap and Morceli went on to win the gold medal. Later that season, 
he ended Morceli's four-year winning streak at 1,500 meters, 
winning the IAAF Grand Prix final. 
</P>
<P>
	El Guerrouj won 14 of 15 races in 1997, losing only at one mile  
in the Grand Prix final. Last year, he won all 12 races, including 
one at 2,000 meters, and just missed world records at the mile with 
3:44.60 and 2,000 meters with 4:48.36. He is undefeated this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
