<HEADLINE> Tenn. Court Monitors TV Judge Brown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- The Tennessee Supreme Court is  
scrutinizing the amount of time that TV's Judge Joe B. Brown spends 
on his real-life bench. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Justice E. Riley Anderson is trying to determine whether  
Brown received permission from the state's high court for all the 
days he has taken off to tape ``Judge Joe Brown'' in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson allowed a retired judge to sit in for Brown on six days  
this winter. But records show the retired judge sat in 14 
additional days. Brown said he thought Anderson's approval also 
applied to those absences. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown also said the show isn't causing him to fall behind  
because he has streamlined his court in Memphis and convened on 
weekends and evenings. Besides, he said, it's good for business. 
</P>
<P>
	``The show helps me be a better judge on the state level,'' he  
said. ``People can get stagnant in their work. I'm hooked up with a 
lot of judges in Los Angeles. We talk about what kinds of problems 
we have and how we can address these problems.'' 
  	   	
</P>
