<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up in Quiet Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar edged higher against major currencies  
Wednesday, but trading was subdued as dealers were wary of market 
intervention by the Bank of Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's central bank stepped into currency markets earlier this  
week to push down the value of the yen, which had risen on a report 
showing increasing confidence among business leaders. The Bank of 
Japan fears that an overly strong yen could jeopardize Japan's 
economic recovery by making exports more expensive abroad and 
threatening the earnings of major exporting companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading against the euro was quieter, with the dollar holding  
steady against the currency a day after the euro touched another 
low against the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 122.23  
Japanese yen, up slightly from 122.02. The euro was quoted at 
$1.0226, unchanged from late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.5693 Swiss francs, up from  
1.5668, and 1.4700 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4703. The British 
pound fell to $1.5603 from $1.5618. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Since Wednesday's dollar-euro rate was unchanged from Tuesday, so 
were the dollar equivalents against the European currencies under 
the euro. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on Wednesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.9128  
German marks, 6.4144 French francs, and 1,893.94 Italian lire, all 
unchanged from Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
