<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 09:10:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Price of Racing Popularity High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	These days, when fans talk about ``trading paint,'' they might  
not be discussing the bumping and banging that for so long defined 
stock car racing. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, it's the business side that keeps those paint shops  
busy -- and fans in need of more than just a program. A copy of 
Consumer Reports might help, too. 
</P>
<P>
	One year, Sterling Marlin is driving the Kodak car; the next, it  
belongs to Bobby Hamilton. 
</P>
<P>
	Need to sell a new die-cast model? Change the paint scheme.  
</P>
<P>
	Now, one of the senior sponsors in the sport, Skoal, is dropping  
out. 
</P>
<P>
	And Ricky Rudd has lost his nine-year ride with Tide to a team  
yet to run a NASCAR race. 
</P>
<P>
	For at least the last decade, hardly a driver can finish a  
sentence without mentioning the sponsors of these rolling 
billboards masquerading as Chevrolets, Fords and Pontiacs. Some in 
the sport believe the slick, 1990s version of NASCAR has been 
created at a price. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're an old-style racing fan, today's racing is boring,''  
said Kyle Petty, son of Richard Petty, the man who more than three 
decades ago put the first real face on the sport. 
</P>
<P>
	But things have changed dramatically since he was in the prime  
of a career that produced a record 200 victories. Drivers who once 
did nothing but race are now also pitchmen seemingly more 
interested in protecting lucrative Winston Cup points positions 
than in taking chances on winning. 
</P>
<P>
	Kyle Petty decries what he perceives to be a lost adventure.  
</P>
<P>
	He pines for the purity of a true one-on-one showdown -- not the  
kind that now frequently span only the final few laps of a race. He 
remembers his father running door-to-door for lap upon lap with 
Bobby Allison, Cale Yarborough, Buddy Baker and others who 
dominated the sport in a simpler time. 
</P>
<P>
	Back then, nobody could have imagined their races filling a  
prime-time slot on network TV. But last Saturday night, the Pepsi 
400 -- remember when they called it the Firecracker 400? -- was 
televised on CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	And none other than Baker was part of this show, providing  
analysis for a sport he still loves, even though it barely seems 
the same. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as changing things, I don't see any problem with the  
sport,'' Baker said. ``It's growing every day. The sport is 
healthy, and I think NASCAR does a great job of making sure the 
competition is all on a level playing field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rudd might disagree.  
</P>
<P>
	A single-car owner in an era of multicar teams, he has slogged  
along over the last five years, unable to generate the money to 
field a second car. One-car teams are a dinosaur of the high banks, 
where every race this year has been won by a driver from a multicar 
operation. 
</P>
<P>
	With a second car, Rudd would have more manpower, more time and  
ways to test, and a better chance to be competitive. He lost his 
sponsor at a time when he seeks to extend one of Winston Cup's 
hallowed records. He has at least one victory in each of the last 
16 seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll surely find a sponsor for next year, but the loss of Tide  
definitely set back his plans to find a partner. It also offered 
him a jolting reminder that the old days are certainly gone. 
</P>
<P>
	Rudd longs for the era when pioneer owners like Bud Moore and  
Junie Donlavey would have cars in the field every week. There was 
then an unmistakable flavor to a sport many feel is slowly being 
homogenized. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore, who hit the beach in the first wave on D-Day, is gone,  
unable to attract a sponsor despite 63 wins. The familiar No. 90 
car of Donlavey, also a victim of poor sponsorship, is all but 
invisible in his 50th year in the sport. 
</P>
<P>
	``As this becomes the trendy thing to be a part of, some of the  
negative fallout is nobody really pays attention'' to the 
old-timers and their brand of racing, Rudd said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like, `Hey, the 90 car isn't here this week.' But he's  
been here for every race for the last how many thousands of races 
when they needed cars in the field,'' said Rudd, who drove for 
Donlavey 20 years ago, and later for Moore. 
</P>
<P>
	Kyle Petty fears the day will come when there will be no fans  
who remember what stock car racing once was. 
</P>
<P>
	``People talk about how much the sport has changed in the last  
seven, eight years,'' he said. ``There are more sponsors, more TV, 
more fans. At the same time, racing on the racetrack is changing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Is it for the better?  
</P>
<P>
	``In some ways it might be,'' he said. ``But I don't think  
boring is for the better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	 *End Adv for Thursday, July 8    	
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
