<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Special Olympian Claims Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHAPEL HILL, N.C. (AP) -- A Special Olympics athlete from  
Reunion, an the island off southern Africa, has accused a 
13-year-old teammate of sexually assaulting her. 
</P>
<P>
	The assault was said to have occurred Thursday at Morrison  
Dormitory at North Carolina-Chapel Hill, according to the Orange 
County district attorney's office and UNC police. 
</P>
<P>
	The athletes' coach took them to the UNC Hospitals emergency  
room, then notified police, according to a police report. 
</P>
<P>
	The case will be decided in Reunion, according to authorities.  
</P>
<P>
	Police and the DA's office declined to investigate further  
because, among other things, evidence from a hospital ``rape kit'' 
examination could take months to process, long past the time 
athletes were due to return home. The Special Olympics World Summer 
Games ended Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The long wait for rape kit results would have meant keeping the  
alleged assailant in jail for a long period of time, said UNC 
Police Chief Derek Poarch. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't even know if he had the mental capacity to understand  
that he was committing anything wrong,'' Poarch said. 
</P>
<P>
	DA Carl Fox said he would forward the physical evidence to  
Reunion officials if they requested it. 
</P>
<P>
	Special Olympics officials conducted an investigation and found  
discrepancies in the woman's story, said Joe Freddoso, the Games' 
chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were some questions whether a sexual assault actually  
occurred,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
