<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 15:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fan Cast 40,000 Votes for Shortstop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Red Sox wanted fans to vote early and often  
for Nomar Garciaparra. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Nandor, of Carver, Mass., took the promotional campaign to  
heart and voted for the shortstop almost 40,000 times via the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, when I first heard he won, I wasn't sure, but I thought  
it could've been me,'' Nandor said Tuesday night. ``But I also 
thought it could've been other people in addition to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only major league baseball and its computer people detected the  
ballot box-stuffing and threw out Nandor's votes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've outlined certain procedures that catch 99 percent of the  
potential problems out there,'' Alex Kam, major league baseball's 
director of new media, said Wednesday. ``It does happen quite 
frequently, (but) they filter it out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra overtook New York Yankees' rival Derek Jeter in the  
final week of counting, winning 1,089,974 to 1,069,528. But 
baseball says hackers didn't influence the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Individuals voting on the Internet were limited to 22 votes --  
matching the average number of home games for teams during the 
voting period. 
</P>
<P>
	Kam says Nandor used a computer programming language to evade  
limits on how many times a person could vote on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	On May 19, Nandor tried to vote 14,000 times, Kam said. And The  
Boston Globe reported Tuesday that Nandor cast 25,259 more votes 
for Garciaparra from June 25-27. The ballots also voted for Red Sox 
players Scott Hatteberg, John Valentin and Jose Offerman. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a matter of process, we look for certain type of activity  
that would be repetitive in nature,'' Kam said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nandor says when he heard Garciaparra had garnered enough votes  
to start, he suspected perhaps he had had something to do with it. 
</P>
<P>
	What apparently did in Nandor was a certain amount of laziness.  
In his first attempt in May, Nandor used the same e-mail address. 
His last attempt, in June, he used the same phone number 
(111-222-3333) and ZIP code (11111). Nandor wrote that he set his 
computer to run repeatedly, then went to a barbecue. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think in large part I did it just because the All-Star game  
was going to be in Fenway, so I felt Nomar deserved a start on his 
home turf, with the incredible season he's had,'' he said in an 
e-mail to the Globe. ``I still might have done it if the game had 
been in New York, but it makes me feel good to have this 
justification for my actions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because Nandor didn't vary his basic bits of information, the  
systems administrators at CBS SportsLine, the Internet site which 
conducted the voting, caught on quickly, Kam said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jon Orwant, a doctoral candidate at MIT's Media Lab who  
inadvertently tipped off the Globe about his friend Nandor's 
program, remains unconvinced that the system can withstand a clever 
hacker. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they claim their system is foolproof, they're wrong,'' he  
said. ``I'll prove it to them next year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kam says baseball will be ready.  
</P>
<P>
	``It makes us redouble our efforts,'' he said. ``There are a lot  
of enterprising people out there who might try to do this.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 02:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fernandez Recalls Senior Open Loss  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Vicente Fernandez recalls his  
narrow loss at last year's U.S. Senior Open not with a scowl but a 
smile. 
</P>
<P>
	And that's exactly how the television camera caught him at the  
Riviera Country Club near Los Angeles when Hale Irwin sank the 
12-foot birdie putt that gave him a one-stroke victory over 
Fernandez -- smiling. 
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez was reminded of that moment Tuesday before starting a  
practice round for the 1999 Open beginning Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oh, yes, I remember, because it was a very good day for me,''  
Fernandez said. ``I thought I did the best I could do and then it 
wasn't on me to win the tournament. It was on him to win or not to 
win. He did it in a magic way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both golfers enter this year's tournament with confidence, Irwin  
ranking fourth in winnings and Fernandez fifth. And Irwin is coming 
in on a tear. 
</P>
<P>
	He has won three of his last five senior tournaments and has  
shot par or better in 16 of 17 rounds in that stretch. In 12 of 
those rounds, he has scored in the 60s. 
</P>
<P>
	``It feels like my game is back where I want it to be,'' said  
Irwin, who struggled early this year after winning seven events in 
1998 and leading all of golf with nearly $2.9 million in prize 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now, whether or not I continue playing as I have, it's  
anybody's guess,'' he said. ``But I feel good about my game right 
now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He should. Since the first week of May, Irwin has won the  
Nationwide Championship, Boone Valley Classic and Senior Players 
Championship. He finished sixth at the Las Vegas Senior Classic, 
which Fernandez won. 
</P>
<P>
	Irwin's only downer was a tie for 26th at the BellSouth Classic.  
But the next time out, he won the Senior Players Championship by 
seven strokes, closing with rounds of 64 and 65. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have played extremely well, there's no doubt about that,''  
Irwin said. ``I think it's in large part due to sort of a 
recommitment, of focus if you wish, to get myself more back in the 
frame of mind and the playing mode which I found myself in at this 
time last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Something else might be just as important, though. Just before  
he started winning again, Irwin changed the ball he used. He 
discarded the new style Titleist he had been using for the first 
part of the year in favor of the old style ball he had played last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Irwin admitted there isn't much difference between the old  
Professional and new Professional. He just feels more comfortable 
with the old one. 
</P>
<P>
	``The old Professional was a ball which I knew how far I was  
going to hit it each time under what conditions,'' Irwin said. ``It 
was a very predictable ball that fit my game nicely. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new Professional is a very good ball, too, but it goes a  
little bit farther. It has different flight characteristics and 
affected my game more than it might affect some other player's 
game. I was hitting it a little too far with some clubs and I 
couldn't find the right pattern. When I went back to this other 
one, it was just like it fell into place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There's just one problem. Titleist no longer makes the old  
Professional, so supplies are limited. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm squeaking through,'' Irwin said. ``I've got enough at home  
probably to last me another several months, and if Titleist can 
come up with a few others, that would be great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez said he figured Irwin would come around eventually. He  
said those who thought Irwin would be in no position to repeat his 
Open title have been proven wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every time they ask me about Hale being a little bit slow  
starting this year, I always said ... he was taking a rest,'' 
Fernandez said. ``I think he is ready again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez said he's ready, too, though his scores have slipped  
the last couple of weeks. Someone suggested he might be saving 
himself for the Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope so,'' Fernandez said. ``I have been striking the ball  
the best ever the last four weeks, but I couldn't take full 
advantage of that. I never try to save anything, but maybe it was 
somebody up there in heaven that is saying, `Well, you have 
something waiting for you.''' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
