<DOCNO> APW19990707.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 18:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Anderson, Williams Miss Mini-camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SUWANEE, Ga. (AP) -- Pro Bowl running back Jamal Anderson did the  
expected Wednesday and failed to show for first day of the Atlanta 
Falcons' three-day mini-camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Due to be paid $2.6 million this season in the final year of his  
contract, Anderson has made clear his desire for a restructured 
deal that would place him among the NFL's highest-paid players. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, offensive lineman Gene Williams and kicker Morten  
Andersen were the only players not present for the first official 
summer workout for the defending NFC champions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew Morten wasn't going to be here because I had given him  
an excuse, but those two guys have a contract, and I fully expect 
them to honor it and be here,'' coach Dan Reeves said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like we haven't had a conversation. They understand  
what the situation is. I didn't write the rules the way the 
National Football League is now. I'm disappointed they aren't out 
here, you bet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reeves indicated Anderson and Williams will receive the maximum  
fine, $1,000 per day, that is allowed under the NFL collective 
bargaining agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've got a contract and they should live up to it,'' said  
Reeves, who allegedly spoke with New England during the April NFL 
draft about a possible trade involving Anderson. ``I'm disappointed 
they aren't here, and they will be fined.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson and his Oakland, Calif.-based agent, Jim Sims, already  
have turned down an offer from the Falcons, but dispute the team's 
description of a five-year deal worth $26 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Sims told the Columbus Ledger-Enquirer on Tuesday night that the  
Falcons have offered a signing bonus of just over $6 million, while 
he and Anderson are seeking $10 million. At least, Sims said, 
Anderson wants to be the highest-paid Falcon. 
</P>
<P>
	Quarterback Chris Chandler signed a five-year, $25 million  
extension last season as he and Anderson were earning spots on the 
NFC Pro Bowl team. Anderson rushed 410 times for 1,846 yards -- tops 
in the NFC and second only to Denver's Terrell Davis in the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, who also ran for an NFC-high 14 touchdowns, crossed  
the 1,000-yard mark for the third straight season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel that with his impending and imminent free-agent  
status, you take a lot of risk by putting a player on the field 
(who's earning) below what his market value is,'' Sims said. ``He 
would certainly take that risk if he steps on the field for the 
mini-camp.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Falcons general manager Harold Richardson said he had responded  
to one of the two proposals he received from Sims on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're both trying to get the same thing done,'' Richardson  
said. ``Is it possible in these situations that you can both want 
to get something done and you can just flat disagree on the numbers 
(so much) that it doesn't get done? 
</P>
<P>
	``Sure. But we both want to get it done and we're pushing it  
that way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson said last month that he wants to remain a Falcon and  
prefers not to test the free agent market after the 1999 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Cornerback Ray Buchanan said he hopes the issue will be settled  
as soon as possible. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jamal knows he's one of the thumping heartbeats on this  
football team, and we need him here,'' Buchanan said. ``But at the 
same time, he's got to think about himself and his situation with 
his contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's deserving of a lot of money. He's played well for this  
football team. That's the way contract negotiations go. We can't 
really think about his situation as much as trying to get ourselves 
prepared.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fullback Bob Christian, however, was less diplomatic.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'll keep that to myself,'' Christian said. ``It means I get  
more (practice time). I got to do the nickel stuff, which I like.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 08:19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lott Holds Up Holbrooke Nomination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott himself is  
among three senators now blocking the long-delayed nomination of 
Richard Holbrooke to be U.N. ambassador, congressional and 
administration officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott and Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., are doing it secretly,  
said the officials, speaking on the condition of anonymity. Sen. 
Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, is the third, but he announced his 
``hold'' on the veteran diplomat's nomination late last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott, R-Miss., and McConnell are using the delaying technique to  
apply pressure on the White House to nominate an Ohio law professor 
for a position on the Federal Election Commission, said the 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The professor, Bradley A. Smith of Capital University in  
Columbus, had been recommended by Republican Senate leaders for a 
Republican vacancy on the commission, which is evenly divided 
between Democrats and Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Traditionally, their recommendation likely would be accepted.  
But Common Cause and other public-interest groups have waged a 
campaign to persuade President Clinton not to make the nomination, 
saying Smith's writings demonstrate hostility to campaign-finance 
laws he would be sworn to uphold. 
</P>
<P>
	McConnell is chairman of the Senate GOP committee that helps  
elect Republicans to the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesmen for neither Lott nor McConnell could be reached today  
for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott said last week said that Holbrooke's nomination ``has some  
problems right now,'' and his spokesman, John Czwartacki, cited 
``irreconcilable holds'' on the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	However, until now, only the identity of Grassley had been known  
among those blocking the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	By Senate tradition, any senator can block a nomination, at  
least temporarily, by putting a ``hold'' on it, which can be 
anonymous. 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley, who has sought to overhaul that practice by requiring  
senators to announce such holds publicly, is blocking the 
nomination for a different reason. He contends that a government 
official who worked at the U.N. mission in New York was demoted and 
transferred to a lesser job in Washington in retaliation for her 
telling members of Congress about waste and inefficiency at the 
United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department has said that the official, Linda Shenwick,  
was reassigned because of unsatisfactory job performance, not 
because she was a whistle-blower. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for Grassley, Jill Kozeny, said today that  
``nothing has changed'' and that the Grassley hold remains. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``holds'' are just the latest obstacles in the course of  
Holbrooke's more than yearlong effort to win confirmation. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of that delay was caused by the administration's own ethics  
background investigations into Holbrooke. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke was approved last week by the Senate Foreign Relations  
Committee. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
