<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Met's John Franco Out 3-10 Weeks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- New York Mets reliever John Franco will miss  
3-10 weeks with a partially torn tendon on the middle finger of his 
left hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Franco, 38, injured the finger in the ninth inning of a 16-0  
loss to the Braves last Friday night at Shea Stadium. He underwent 
an MRI on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had no illusions of losing him for more than two weeks,''  
Mets manager Bobby Valentine said. ``I think of our bullpen as a 
group and obviously, there's a big hole in our group right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 34 games this season, Franco was 0-2 with a 3.45 ERA and had  
converted on 19 of 20 save chances. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully it will be about four weeks,'' Franco said. ``The  
doctors have learned from having dealt with other pitchers. Right 
now, they're just trying to keep it (the finger) immobilized.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Franco, who has 416 career saves, was one of many Mets denied  
the chance to join catcher Mike Piazza at the All-Star game in 
Boston next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ironically, here we are talking about his injury and the  
All-Star selections,'' Valentine said. ``I feel he was as deserving 
as anyone on our team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Armando Benitez is expected to handle the full-time closer  
duties in Franco's absence. He has saved five games so far this 
season while striking out 49 in his last 27 innings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
