<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 09:00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Parsons' Find Has Racing Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Benny Parsons never figured to discover a great talent when he  
went to Winter Heat, an off-season watering hole for thirsty NASCAR 
wannabes. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, one December afternoon in the Arizona desert, he found  
Greg Biffle. Three years later, the driver from suburban Portland, 
Ore. -- a place hardly synonymous with big-time stock car racing -- 
is a big star in the Craftsman Truck series. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Saturday, in West Allis, Wis., Biffle won for the third  
time in his last eight races. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anyone who was at Tucson could easily have seen the talent he  
has,'' Parsons said. ``My only advantage in telling people about it 
was that I had validity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parsons, now a NASCAR racing analyst for ABC and ESPN, won the  
Winston Cup championship in 1973 and posted 21 victories in 19 
seasons on stock car racing's most demanding circuit. So, when he 
mentioned Biffle to Jack Roush, the car owner gave him a listen. 
</P>
<P>
	``Benny Parsons, with his stock car wisdom, told me Greg Biffle  
was one of the best talents and showed the greatest potential in 
his 40 years of racing,'' said Roush, who also owns five cars -- 
including those of superstars Mark Martin and Jeff Burton -- on the 
Winston Cup circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Parsons, who gave up driving a taxi cab in Detroit to race full  
time more than three decades ago, laughs now about the exchange 
with Roush. But, for Biffle's sake, he's happy his credentials gave 
him credibility. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I had been some fan, Jack would have dismissed it and gone  
down the road,'' Parsons said. 
</P>
<P>
	Biffle is glad that didn't happen. The Parsons-Roush connection  
has allowed him to spend more time driving race trucks rather than 
fabricating race cars. 
</P>
<P>
	It also took him away from his pub in Vancouver, Wash. Carrying  
trays around the corner has given way to carrying speed in the 
corners. 
</P>
<P>
	``I owe everything I have to Benny Parsons and Jack Roush,''  
said Biffle, the truck series Rookie of the Year in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Roush never second-guessed himself for hiring the former  
short-track terror of the Northwest, who in 1996 won 27 of his 47 
races. But he certainly spent a lot of money fixing trucks Biffle 
kept breaking. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wrecked all together too much last year, which was a  
disappointment to me,'' Roush said. 
</P>
<P>
	He wasn't alone. Biffle was concerned about more than the bills  
Roush was paying to remove all the dents. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt like I was in grave jeopardy of losing my job,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	He didn't, and by the end of the season Biffle was a force. He  
ran consistently among the top 10, leading in five of the final 
seven races. 
</P>
<P>
	But early on, he had no way of knowing there would be impressive  
final numbers of eight top-five finishes in 27 races, four poles 
and earnings of $359,782 that would stamp him as a star of the 
future. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was trying my hardest to get good finishes, but I was being  
too aggressive at the wrong times,'' he said. ``I was making rookie 
mistakes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, the 29-year-old driver has learned to be more judicious on  
the track. 
</P>
<P>
	His aggressive style has not changed. But he realizes there are  
times when a pedal-to-the-metal approach just won't work. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still take chances now, but only when I have a safety net,''  
he explained. 
</P>
<P>
	The boss has noticed.  
</P>
<P>
	Martin and Burton, with a combined 38 Winston Cup victories,  
have conditioned Roush to expect nothing less than solid contention 
from his top drivers. It's no different with Biffle. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Roush adds ``maturity'' to words such as potential and  
ability in discussing Biffle. 
</P>
<P>
	``He stays out of trouble, but still maintains great enthusiasm  
and skill,'' Roush said. ``He's developing judgment that has got 
him to the point that he's in position to win every week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To Randy Goss, crew chief for the Roush truck effort, Biffle is  
doing more than just driving well. Goss gets more feedback, the 
kind he says will help Biffle steadily improve. 
</P>
<P>
	The most important factor is the driver's input on chassis  
setups for their Fords, and adjustments needed to improve the 
vehicles during the races. The payoff has been a second-place 
standing in points after 13 of 25 races. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's more assertive with telling us what he wants, and I let  
him make more of his own decisions out there,'' Goss explained. 
``Last year, we were trying to guide and sometimes even think for 
him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	 *End Adv for Thursday, July 8    	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0206 </DOCNO>
