<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 12:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mich. St. Players Likely Face Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Michigan State basketball stars  
Mateen Cleaves and Antonio Smith are likely to go to trial after 
prosecutors refused to dismiss theft charges against them today. 
</P>
<P>
	The pair is charged with the theft of a 40-ounce bottle of beer  
from an East Lansing 7-Eleven. The car they were in was pulled over 
early on the morning of April 14 because the vehicle was said to 
match the description of the one involved in the theft. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith is charged with two misdemeanors: larceny of property  
worth less than $200 and malicious destruction of property. He is 
accused of breaking the door lock on 7-Eleven's cooler. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleaves is charged with larceny of property worth less than  
$200. Both men pleaded innocent to the charges last month. If they 
are convicted, the charges carry penalties of up to three months in 
jail. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the players' attorney, Brian Jeffries, met  
privately with Ingham County Prosecutor Stuart Dunnings III to 
discuss whether a plea bargain could be reached and a trial could 
be avoided. 
</P>
<P>
	Dunnings refused to reduce the charge against Cleaves. Smith was  
given the option of pleading guilty to one of the charges in 
exchange for the dismissal of the second charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeffries said he wouldn't agree to those terms.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's a deal on the table and we'll consider that,'' he  
said. ``But at this point we're going to move toward a trial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dunnings said prosecutors have a videotape from the 7-Eleven as  
well as accounts from at least six witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeffries called the evidence ``primarily circumstantial'' and  
said the video from the store ``doesn't show a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The alleged theft occurred a little more than two weeks after  
team captains Cleaves and Smith led the Spartans to their first 
Final Four in 20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith completed his eligibility in March.  
</P>
<P>
	Cleaves, a two-time All-American, has chosen to stay for his  
senior year next fall, passing up an opportunity to declare for the 
NBA Draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleaves also faces two citations filed against him last week  
after a noisy party at his campus apartment. Those citations carry 
penalties of up to 90 days in jail. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
