<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Calls for Internet Tax Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate John  
McCain said Wednesday he favors a permanent ban on Internet sales 
taxes, a position that may distinguish him from front-runner George 
W. Bush and incur anger from governors and mayors. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech to about 100 conservatives, McCain said ``the ban  
must be permanent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked later about the specifics of his proposal, he took a  
softer stance, saying he liked the idea of exempting Internet sales 
from state and local taxes but would await the findings of a 
congressional panel created last year to study the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said the Texas governor  
is still considering whether commerce on the Internet should be 
taxed. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, a Republican senator from Arizona, bemoaned a shortage  
of skilled foreign workers allowed into the country, and he 
denounced ``the nation's out-of-control'' civil justice system. 
Both are hot-button issues for high-tech industry executives here. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Bush, he attacked the Clinton administration for dragging  
its feet on a bill Congress passed last week that would make it 
harder to sue high-tech companies for Y2K-related problems. 
President Clinton has said he will sign the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Touching on another issue dear to Silicon Valley, McCain called  
for removing more trade barriers, proclaiming himself ``the most 
free-trading, anti-protectionist you will ever see in the United 
States Senate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain delivered his speech at the Hoover Institution, a  
conservative think tank based at Stanford University that is home 
to at least 10 Bush policy advisers. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology companies have pleaded with the federal government to  
raise the cap on visas that allow highly skilled foreign workers 
into the country. Congress did so last year, but not as much as 
U.S. manufacturers of high technology products wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain blamed union donations to political parties for that  
outcome. 
</P>
<P>
	``Labor unions, having spent millions in soft money quid,  
received their pro quo,'' he said. ``The visas have already run 
out; the high-tech experts and the jobs they create will now roll 
overseas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, like Bush, McCain didn't say to what extent he would  
raise the cap. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain praised President Clinton for agreeing to sign the Y2K  
bill last week, ``over the vehement objections of the trial lawyers 
and the vice president.'' But he called it ``less than comforting'' 
that ``it was still in the end a close call for him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Congress last year imposed a three-year moratorium on new  
federal, state and local electronic commerce taxes, which expires 
in October 2001. It also created the Advisory Commission on 
Electronic Commerce to recommend future Internet tax policy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
