<HEADLINE> Alexander Launches Straw Poll Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander  
opened a grassroots drive Wednesday to build support for a straw 
poll next month that could be a key to his hopes for the GOP 
presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander said he plans to campaign in 60 of the state's 99  
counties in the 23 days he has planned in the state before the Aug. 
14 straw poll in Ames. 
</P>
<P>
	``My goal is to get the presidential campaign discussion back  
where it ought to be and away from polls and money and media and 
back to character, to schools and farm prices,'' Alexander said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander said he will undertake an intense organizational  
effort to get backers to show up at the straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	After focusing such heavy attention on the straw poll, a weak  
showing would be a big blow to the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot is at stake for a lot of us,'' Alexander said. ``I plan  
on making a stellar showing. My reason for going to 60 counties is 
to improve my chances of making a good showing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The drive started Wednesday with an ice cream social at the home  
of one of Alexander's most prominent and visible Iowa supporters, 
former Gov. Terry Branstad. 
</P>
<P>
	The straw poll is being closely watched because it is one  
measure of a campaign's ability to deliver supporters to a 
political event, the same skills needed to score well on caucus 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Gov. George W. Bush has dominated the race in recent  
weeks, riding high atop the opinion polls and raising far more 
money than his GOP rivals. He has only campaigned in the state 
once, but has said he will compete in the straw poll and his 
campaign is putting together a big effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Should Bush win the straw poll after only campaigning in the  
state once, it would provide a big burst of momentum. It also would 
be a big blow to Alexander, who has campaigned for months. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
