<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Questions With Camryn Manheim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It is a hot, muggy summer day. Manhattan is  
sizzling. And so is Camryn Manheim. 
</P>
<P>
	Last September, Manheim became a champion of large-size women  
when she triumphantly hoisted her Emmy into the air and exulted: 
``This is for all the fat girls!'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The Emmy was really spectacular,'' she said during an  
interview in her dressing room at the Hammerstein Ballroom. ``My 
parents were there, and my best friend was there, and it was the 
first time I had ever been to an event like that and walked down a 
red carpet. The whole day was really spectacular. And like a 
fantasy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manheim, who divides her time between New York and Los Angeles,  
is on Ladies' Home Journal's list of the 10 Most Fascinating Women 
and People magazine's 25 Most Intriguing People of 1998. Her face 
has graced the covers of TV Guide, Mode, Radiance and Parade 
magazines. 
</P>
<P>
	Her portrayal of feisty lawyer Ellenor Frutt on ABC's ``The  
Practice'' also won her a Golden Globe. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, she is a recipient of the Golden Hanger, bestowed  
by E! Entertainment's Joan Rivers, who is known for her cutting 
comments as fashion-challenged stars walk down the red carpet on 
Oscar night. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Golden Hanger award was thrilling for me because ... I'm  
representing a group of women who've been overlooked for so many 
decades,'' said Manheim, who is a size 22. ``I actually took it 
very seriously that a plus-size woman was getting an award for 
setting trends in fashion. I actually am very proud of that award 
and it sits right next to my Emmy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her memoir, ``Wake Up, I'm Fat!'' (Broadway Books), hit the The  
New York Times and Publishers Weekly best-seller lists. Her 
one-woman off-Broadway show of the same name ran from 1993 to 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Manheim, who earned her master's degree from New York  
University, is only hours away from her runway debut, where she 
will model outfits for Lane Bryant's Venezia Jeans Collection. Lane 
Bryant services the large-size market. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know what's going to freak me out the most? It's the  
decline on the runway in heels,'' the 5-foot-10-inch actress 
laughed. ``THAT is the most frightening part.'' (P.S. Manheim later 
strutted down the catwalk like a pro, planting a sassy air kiss on 
the audience.) 
</P>
<P>
	Her outfits: red silk-crepe bustier and matching long red skirt;  
long, neon-white silk coat and matching trousers; and black V-neck 
silk top and trousers paired with a hot-pink taffeta duster. 
</P>
<P>
	Pretty fancy for a woman who rides a motorcycle!  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a jeans and a T-shirt gal,'' said Manheim, 38, who is  
fashionably attired in black pants and sheer long-sleeve white 
shirt layered over a white top. 
</P>
<P>
	When David E. Kelley picked her to play Ellenor Frutt on ``The  
Practice,'' she recalled: ``I said to the wardrobe designer, `I'd 
like to wear pants, and then she said, `Well, you know, it's 
conservative Boston court system, the commonwealth of Massachusetts 
and all,' and I said, `Listen, it's a federal law that women can 
wear pants in court and you tell Mr. Kelley that.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Manheim got her way.  
</P>
<P>
	``But that's before I knew how powerful he was,'' she laughed.  
``Had I known, I wouldn't have been so bold. As far as I was 
concerned, he was Michelle Pfeiffer's husband. He wasn't his own 
entity at the time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She recently completed work on an ABC television movie, ``The  
Loretta Claiborne Story,'' the true story of a woman who became a 
Special Olympics champion. Manheim also has a part in a new Mike 
Nichols comedy and will play Snow White in a new NBC miniseries, 
``The 10th Kingdom.'' 
</P>
<P>
	1. Did you ever dream that you would be backstage in your  
dressing room getting ready for a fashion show at the Hammerstein 
Ballroom in New York? 
</P>
<P>
	Manheim: Well, I fantasized about it as a young girl. I think  
all little girls fantasize about taking the trip down the runway 
with the photographers clicking their cameras and blinded by the 
lights. (Laughs.) The funny thing about my life is that I had 
unbelievable fantasies which I never thought would become realities 
and they all have. So nothing surprises me anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	2. Not everyone can boast of having both an Emmy and a Golden  
Hanger. How does it feel? 
</P>
<P>
	Manheim: I joke about it and say, `You know, this award was  
harder to win than the Emmy,' and in some ways it was. But thanks 
to Joan Rivers, she is acknowledging that plus-size women can be 
beautiful. And I know that she has in the past given a lot of flak 
to some women who have had weight issues, but I think she's opening 
up her eyes and widening her interpretation of what beauty is. 
</P>
<P>
	3. Where is your favorite place to shop?  
</P>
<P>
	Manheim: In L.A., my favorite big girls' store is called Culver  
Large. Nothing costs more than $50, and things cost as little as 
$4.99. It's in the Culver City Mall. It's FAN-TASTIC! This shirt's 
from there. It literally was like $8.99. I love everything that 
comes from Culver Large. I'm telling you, it's the best. That's for 
my everyday wear. I shop at Lane Bryant all the time, especially 
for intimate apparel. 
</P>
<P>
	4: Would you reveal the names of any stars who have signed your  
autograph book? 
</P>
<P>
	Manheim: I'll just tell you my favorite. My very favorite  
autograph is Roberto Benigni. He wrote something in Italian, and I 
worship the ground he walks on. And I have some very special 
autographs, I have a whole list, and one day it will be auctioned 
off at Sotheby's. It's pretty cool. 
</P>
<P>
	I'm looking for another autograph book. So please put in your  
article that if anyone can find the ones that say `Autographs' on 
it, I'd really appreciate it. And they can tell me at my Web site, 
www.camryn.com. 
</P>
<P>
	5. How did David E. Kelley come up with the name Ellenor Frutt?  
</P>
<P>
	Manheim (laughing): You know, Ellenor I like. Ellie I like.  
Frutt? I don't know what he was thinking. And had I been as cocky 
then as I am now, I would have said to David, `What is up with 
Frutt?' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
