<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Terry Nichols Seeks New Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Terry Nichols' lawyers asked for a new trial in  
the Oklahoma bombing Wednesday, arguing that the government 
withheld FBI documents that could have helped his defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Michael Tigar said there are 43,000 documents  
still hidden in FBI files. Prosecutors countered that they turned 
over 12,000 pertinent FBI files and that the others wouldn't have 
changed the verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Richard Matsch, who presided over the trial,  
said he will have to study the documents and will issue a ruling 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	Nichols, 44, was convicted in 1997 of conspiracy and involuntary  
manslaughter in the April 19, 1995, bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah 
Federal Building that killed 168 people. He is serving a life 
sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Timothy McVeigh, his former Army buddy, was separately convicted  
of murder and weapons convictions and sentenced to die. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors claimed Nichols helped McVeigh finance the plan,  
gather the ingredients and mix the bomb. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Sean Connelly argued ``there is no legal or factual  
basis'' for turning over the documents or giving Nichols a new 
trial because the documents would not have changed the outcome. 
</P>
<P>
	He said prosecutors and the FBI closely screened the documents  
and determined that most of them were internal reports not subject 
to disclosure, or so vague they were of no value. 
</P>
<P>
	But Tigar said an FBI document that wasn't released until late  
in the trial contradicted the prosecution claim that racing fuel 
used in the bomb was purchased in Texas. Tigar claimed he has other 
documents showing that McVeigh plotted the attack with a group of 
associates operating around Kingman, Ariz., rather than with 
Nichols. 
</P>
<P>
	Tigar said other FBI documents show that a gun dealer who was  
supposedly robbed by Nichols and McVeigh to finance the bombing 
changed his testimony. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
