<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 09:40:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Cavaliers To Hire Wittman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Minnesota Timberwolves assistant Randy Wittman  
reportedly will be the new coach of the Cleveland Cavaliers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cavs, who have been looking for a head coach since Mike  
Fratello was fired June 1, scheduled a 4 p.m. EDT news conference 
to introduce their coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Wittman and his family arrived at Cleveland Hopkins  
International Airport about noon. As television camera crews and 
reporters waited at the flight gate, Wittman exited from a side 
door and was whisked by van to a waiting limousine. 
</P>
<P>
	The Akron Beacon Journal reported in today's editions that  
Wittman told Orlando head coach Doc Rivers, a former NBA teammate 
and longtime friend, that he had accepted the job. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's really excited,'' Rivers said. ``He thinks it's a perfect  
situation for him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Plain Dealer and several Twin Cities and Cleveland  
television stations, citing unnamed sources, also reported Wittman 
would be the new Cavs coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Wittman does not have a listed phone number in the Twin Cities  
area. The Cavaliers would not confirm Wittman's hiring officially 
and Timberwolves spokesman Kent Wipf also declined comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Wittman, 39, is well regarded in NBA coaching circles, and in  
his five years with the Timberwolves gained a reputation as one of 
the league's brightest assistants. He also has been an assistant 
with the Indiana Pacers and Dallas Mavericks. 
</P>
<P>
	A nine-year NBA veteran, Wittman was a first-round draft pick of  
the Washington Bullets in 1983 but was traded to the Atlanta Hawks 
before the 1983-84 season. He finished his career averaging 7.4 
points per game following playing stints in Atlanta, Sacramento and 
Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to playing for Indiana's 1981 NCAA title team,  
Wittman was a two-time academic All-American with the Hoosiers. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland hasn't made it past the first round of the playoffs  
since 1993 and has seen average attendance sag from 18,011 in 
1994-95 to 14,120 last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Wittman first met with Cavs general manager Jim Paxson on June  
16 and was back in Cleveland 10 days later to have dinner with 
Paxson. He emerged as the frontrunner over the holiday weekend 
after meeting with Gordon Gund at the owner's offices in Princeton, 
N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cavs were secretive about their coaching search after  
Fratello was fired. Four coaches were known to have been 
interviewed: Wittman, Dave Cowens, Del Harris and John MacLeod. 
</P>
<P>
	Wittman is the only one of the group who has no NBA head  
coaching experience. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 16:20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gasoline, Heating Oil Prices Rise Oil Prices  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Futures prices for refined oil products rose  
Wednesday on the New York Mercantile Exchange amid expectations 
that a weekly report would show a drop in U.S. inventories. 
</P>
<P>
	However, crude prices edged lower a day after spiking above $20  
a gallon for the first time in 19 months. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract for August delivery of light sweet crude oil  
settled at $19.77 per barrel, down 1 cent. 
</P>
<P>
	But unleaded gasoline for delivery in August settled at 59.17  
cents a gallon, gaining 0.69 cent, while home heating oil for 
delivery in August settled at 50.08 cents a gallon, up 0.70 cent. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude prices briefly pushed above $20 a barrel on Tuesday as  
investors bet that world oil producers are making good on promises 
to slash output. Recent inventory data has continued to show 
tightening supplies, and analysts say shortages could begin to 
appear by September if the output cuts hold. 
</P>
<P>
	After the close of Wednesday's trading, the American Petroleum  
Institute reported that the nation's crude supply slipped to 327.94 
million barrels in the week ended July 2, down from 329.87 million 
a week earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Gasoline inventories fell from 220.79 million barrels to 216.38  
million by the end of last week, while heating oil supplies rose to 
132.44 million barrels from 131.17 million a week earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Friday, natural gas prices were lower, with  
contracts for delivery in August settling at $2.141 per 1,000 cubic 
feet, down 5.0 cents. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, North Sea Brent Blend crude oil for delivery in  
August settled at $18.15 per barrel, up 5 cents at the 
International Petroleum Exchange. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 17:56:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  World Cup Fuels Girls' Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Lisa White jumps in the air and heads the soccer ball, making  
her brown braid slap wildly. Around her, teammates practice their 
dribbling and long kicks. 
</P>
<P>
	Lisa, an 11-year-old from Gardena, Calif., already has her  
soccer future mapped out: She wants to be on her high school team, 
win an athletic scholarship to UCLA and then play professionally. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would like that a lot,'' she said, grinning.  
</P>
<P>
	So would many in a new generation of young, female soccer fans  
whose passion for the game has been heightened by the Women's World 
Cup competition. 
</P>
<P>
	TV ratings for World Cup soccer have exceeded those for NHL  
playoff games, and the successful U.S. team is regularly drawing 
sellout crowds. 
</P>
<P>
	Even when the Americans aren't playing, more than 22,000 people,  
mostly girls and women, have turned out for matches. Hair dyed red, 
white and blue and faces painted with American flags are de rigueur 
in the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	``This team has become so popular with mainstream America, not  
just the soccer fans,'' U.S. coach Tony DiCicco said. ``They're 
such a wonderful group of women that once people got to know them, 
it's just steamrolled. It's awesome to see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And a drastic change from 1991, when the American women won the  
World Cup in China. That victory barely registered a blip in U.S. 
newspapers or on television. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight years later, the United States is in a position to win the  
World Cup again. This time, millions will be watching. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States plays China for the championship Saturday at  
the Rose Bowl in Pasadena, Calif. A sellout crowd of more than 
88,000 is expected, which would top the record of 78,972 for a 
women's sporting event, set June 19 at the World Cup opener in 
Giants Stadium in New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to be a soccer player after watching the tournament. It  
has inspired me,'' said 11-year-old Ye Pei of Devon, Pa. ``My 
favorite player is the Chinese goalie, because she is so 
athletic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More girls are playing soccer since the 1996 Olympics, when the  
U.S. women won a gold medal, said Mike Nelson, a regional 
coordinator and coach of American Youth Soccer Organization teams 
in Torrance, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``The girls are seeing there's an opportunity,'' said Nelson, a  
father of four girls. ``My youngest knows the girl players by name 
now. Where she was big on Ken Griffey Jr., it's Mia Hamm now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 8.6 million soccer players in the United States, 2.5  
million are girls, according to AYSO. About 635,000 boys and girls, 
ages 5 to 18, play in AYSO's 1,000 leagues nationwide. Forty 
percent are female. 
</P>
<P>
	Nelson is projecting an enrollment of 44 percent girls in his  
region's leagues this fall, up from 38 percent five years ago. The 
first female players allowed in AYSO in 1971 now are mothers, and 
he credits them with enrolling their daughters. 
</P>
<P>
	Brittany Stevens, 12, of Torrance was introduced to soccer by  
her mother. 
</P>
<P>
	``She said it would be good for me because I like to kick  
things,'' Brittany said. ``You're in the game to have fun and not 
just for competition. It's fun to be aggressive, roll in the mud 
and slide.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nelson said the numbers of female players in the under-6,  
under-8 and under-10 divisions are on the rise. He expects six of 
seven divisions in his region to set records this fall for 
participation by girls. 
</P>
<P>
	Alyssa Baydar, 10, comes from a soccer-crazy family. Her father  
introduced her to the sport when she was 5, and her 13-year-old 
sister plays, too. The Torrance family watches World Cup matches 
together. 
</P>
<P>
	``They teach me if I make a mistake how to correct it and what I  
can do better in the next game,'' she said, referring to Hamm and 
Brazilian sensation Sissi. 
</P>
<P>
	Girls tend to stick with soccer for years, while boys often skip  
from football to basketball to baseball, Nelson said. He said the 
girls play better, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``The girls play a more teamwork-based game. The girls don't get  
on each other when a mistake is made. They kind of band together,'' 
Nelson said. ``The boys' game is sometimes a little faster, but 
it's also a little more out of control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. midfielder Julie Foudy believes kids accustomed to  
following individual sports such as figure skating and gymnastics 
enjoy seeing a team of Americans succeeding together. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our team is a special group because we've been playing  
together for so long and there's a bond there that people notice. 
That's an attraction to the kids,'' she said. ``We have fun when we 
play, we have fun when we're together, so I think they're attracted 
to that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During a World Cup quarterfinal between Norway and Sweden,  
11-year-old girls Jamie Loney and Laura Adams of Pleasanton, 
Calif., wore painted American flags on their faces and chanted: 
``Girls rule! Boys drool! Soccer's cool!'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe it's unusual for girls our age to be so into sports,''  
Jamie said, ``but when I look at the players, I just know it's 
something I want to do when I get older.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 17:56:01 </DATE_TIME>
