<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 19:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians Use Signs To Air Grievances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PINE RIDGE, S.D. (AP) -- Edgar Bear Runner held up a sign and  
yelled to urge President Clinton to grant clemency to an Indian 
serving a life term for killing two FBI agents. 
</P>
<P>
	But he and other activists decided against holding formal  
demonstrations during the president's visit Wednesday to the Pine 
Ridge Indian Reservation. 
</P>
<P>
	Even those worried about human rights and other issues agreed  
the president's visit should remain focused on his plans for 
bringing jobs and better housing to the reservation, said Bear 
Runner, who lives at Porcupine village. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to Clinton's speech, some activists had said they planned  
to stage demonstrations during his visit to the reservation, but 
none occurred during the time he was in Pine Ridge. 
</P>
<P>
	Some held up signs during Clinton's speech calling for the  
return of land taken from the Sioux more than a century ago. 
Another sign referred to unsolved murders on the reservation. 
</P>
<P>
	People who have marched to protest the sale of beer at  
Whiteclay, Neb., only two miles from the village of Pine Ridge, 
also had threatened to demonstrate. Indian activists Dennis Banks 
and Russell Means have been involved in the recent marches, but 
they did not appear to be in Pine Ridge on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Alcohol is banned on the Pine Ridge Indian Reservation, but  
alcohol bought elsewhere creates severe problems for residents. 
</P>
<P>
	Bear Runner, who was involved in some American Indian Movement  
activities when he was younger, wanted the president to know about 
Leonard Peltier, who has been in prison since 1977. Peltier was 
convicted of the 1975 murders of two FBI agents during a shootout 
on the Pine Ridge Reservation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're here as Peltier's supporters to continue to echo the  
sounds of freedom for Peltier,'' Bear Runner said. 
</P>
<P>
	Babe Poor Bear held up a sign urging Clinton to follow the terms  
of treaties that had given the Sioux most of western South Dakota. 
Those treaties were broken more than a century ago and the tribes 
were restricted to smaller reservations. 
</P>
<P>
	One line on her sign urged the president to ``give back the Paha  
Sapa,'' the Sioux name for the Black Hills. 
</P>
<P>
	Wendell Yellow Bull, executive director of the Oglala Sioux  
Tribe, said most people wanted to avoid any demonstrations that 
might have disrupted discussions on improving the reservation's 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of the people just wanted this to go well,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 15:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Titleist Suing Nike Over Woods' Ads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- You're not likely to see Tiger Woods wearing  
Reebok golf shoes or an Adidas T-shirt. That's because Nike pays 
him about $40 million to wear theirs. 
</P>
<P>
	Nike says it has no problem with two of its television ads that  
show the golfer swinging a club at a golf ball, even though the 
club and ball are made by one of Nike's competitors, Titleist, 
which is paying Woods about $20 million to promote its clubs and 
golf balls. 
</P>
<P>
	But now the Fairhaven, Mass.-based Titleist is swinging back,  
with a lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit, filed on June 25, claims that the Nike ads violate  
Woods' exclusive contract to endorse Titleist balls and clubs. 
</P>
<P>
	In one ad, Woods bounces a ball off the face of a wedge several  
times before swatting it baseball-style. In the other, regular 
golfers join Woods at the driving range, and begin hitting the ball 
300 yards, just as he does. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials for Acushnet Co., the parent company for Titleist,  
FootJoy footwear and Cobra Golf Inc., say the Nike ads have caused 
``irreparable harm'' because a Nike slogan appears at the end of 
both commercials. As a result, ``many tens of millions'' of people 
may think Woods has switched to Nike equipment, according to court 
papers filed by Acushnet's lawyer, James King. 
</P>
<P>
	But Nike says it's doing nothing wrong. Tiger is using a  
Titleist club and hitting Titleist balls in the ads, said Mike 
Kelly, Nike's director of golf communications. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has already changed the slogan at the end of the ad  
from ``Nike Golf'' to ``Nike -- Just Do It'' in an effort to 
accommodate Titleist, Kelly said. And the company is considering 
other slogans before the ad's next run on network television, 
scheduled to coincide with the PGA Championship in August. The ads 
are currently running primarily on the Golf Channel. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't advertise Tiger without him playing golf,'' Kelly  
said. ``We're within our rights to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Titleist seeks unspecified monetary damages in the suit and  
hopes that talks with Nike, which began manufacturing golf balls 
this year, will pull the ads. 
</P>
<P>
	That's unlikely, Kelly said.  
</P>
<P>
	``We plan to continue airing these two ads on national  
television, and we have communicated that to the Acushnet 
Company,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods' agent, Mark Steinberg, said he was working closely with  
both companies to settle the dispute, but he declined to say how a 
compromise could be reached. 
</P>
<P>
	``We certainly don't want two of Tiger's biggest sponsors to  
just slug it out,'' Steinberg said. ``We're taking an active role 
in trying to get this settled.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Woods, 23, turned pro in 1996 after winning his third straight  
U.S. Amateur tournament. He immediately signed endorsements with 
Nike and Titleist worth a total of $60 million over five years. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 15:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Broker Sentenced to Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A broker at a now-defunct investment firm that  
stole $75 million from clients was sentenced Wednesday to nine 
years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	State Supreme Court Justice Edward McLaughlin imposed the  
sentence on Roman Okin, 31, of Manhattan, who had worked for A.R. 
Baron &AMP; Co. The firm was created solely to steal its customers' 
money, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Okin, jailed for the past 13 months, pleaded guilty in May 1998  
to enterprise corruption and began helping in the prosecution of 
co-defendants and the recovery of some of the stolen money. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant District Attorney John Moscow told the judge that  
Okin's help was valuable. ``A substantial number of the crooks he 
was dealing with will soon be in prison,'' the prosecutor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Okin was among 14 Baron brokers charged in 1997 in a 174-count  
indictment that accused them of lying to investors, making 
unauthorized trades, forging documents, and manipulating stocks and 
markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Moscow said 13 of the defendants have pleaded guilty and one,  
John McAndris, was convicted after trial. McLaughlin sentenced 
McAndris, 57, of Montvale, N.J., to five to 15 years in prison, the 
longest sentence imposed in the Baron case. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine-year maximum sentence McLaughlin imposed means that  
Okin must serve at least three years in prison and that he will be 
eligible for parole in 23 months. The judge could have sentenced 
him to 25 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Baron opened in July 1991 and closed in July 1996 after years of  
complaints. When the indictments were handed up, District Attorney 
Robert Morgenthau estimated that Baron had stolen $75 million from 
8,000 clients. 
</P>
<P>
	The district attorney said then that Baron was a place where  
``every conceivable form of dishonesty was used,'' and which ``was 
created and existed for no other reason than to line the pockets of 
its executives and employees at the expense of unsuspecting members 
of the public.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 03:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Slips, Tokyo Stocks Fall / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar slipped against the yen late today in  
Tokyo and stocks fell for a second straight day. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.96 yen in late trading in Tokyo, down 0.12  
yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and also below its late New York 
level of 122.02 yen. The dollar traded between 121.94 yen and 
122.21 during the day. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average dropped 91.83  
points, or 0.51 percent, to close at 17,958.90. On Tuesday, the 
average closed down 84.33 points, or 0.47 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, investors took profits for a second  
day after the average closed above 18,000 on Monday for the first 
time in almost two years. Prices soared after the Bank of Japan's 
``tankan'' survey showed a rise in business confidence. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section fell 1.70 points, or 0.11 percent, to 1,477.02 
points. The TOPIX closed down 7.86 points, or 0.53 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading on the main section of the Tokyo exchange was estimated  
at 645 million shares, down from 675 million Tuesday. Declining 
issues barely outnumbered rising stocks 595 to 580, while 152 
shares were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The recent gains by the Nikkei gave the Japanese currency a  
boost by encouraging foreign investors to sell dollars to buy yen 
and invest more money in Japanese markets, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the currency market, foreigners, encouraged by recent rises  
in the Nikkei, sold dollars to buy yen, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of dollar selling pressure, especially because  
foreigners want to buy yen to invest in Japanese stocks,'' said 
Ryohei Muramatsu, a foreign exchange manager at Commerzbank in 
Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar earlier in the day edged higher against the yen on  
expectation the central bank would again intervene to stem a rise 
in Japan's currency, but the bank was never seen in the market. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan last bought dollars on Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	Japan is still struggling to recover from its longest postwar  
recession despite some improved economic indicators recently. 
Officials are concerned a rise in the yen could send the economy 
back into the doldrums because a stronger Japanese currency makes 
exports more expensive abroad and reduces dollar denominated 
earnings at domestic companies. 
</P>
<P>
	A day before his promotion to vice finance minister for  
international affairs, Haruhiko Kuroda played down government 
efforts to prop up the dollar against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In a talk regarding how closely the government is monitoring the  
dollar-yen exchange rate, Kuroda suggested reporters translate a 
Japanese phrase generally rendered as ``carefully watching'' as 
just ``watching.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 125.06 yen, up from  
124.80 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell to 1.6500  
percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.6800 percent, driving its price 
up to 101.30 yen from 101.04 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
