<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Artists: El Nuevo Mundo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The photographer, who has amassed countless  
stories from behind his Nikon, likes to tell of the Salvadorans who 
moved into the Los Angeles bungalow. Behind their front-yard fence, 
encircled by concrete and metal and urbanity, they kept all manner 
of fowl -- until the health department stopped by with a warning. 
</P>
<P>
	The geese were relocated to the park and the duck to the dinner  
table. ``But,'' offers Camilo Jose Vergara, ``they still keep some 
chickens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vergara, a documentary photographer who uses his camera to  
explore the starkness and vibrancy of everyday life, has been 
exploring such corners of Los Angeles' Latino culture for years. 
While he originally went to chronicle poverty, he found instead a 
thriving culture within a culture, a second city with an identity 
all its own. 
</P>
<P>
	His latest photo exhibit, ``El Nuevo Mundo'' (``The New  
World''), on exhibit at the National Design Museum, investigates 
this phenomenon: What happens when an established urban landscape 
meets -- collides with, some might say -- an immigrant population 
insistent on maintaining many traditional folkways. 
</P>
<P>
	``Los Angeles talks about mosaics. There's no mosaic here. This  
is just a big chunk of Mexico and Central America that is there -- 
and is functioning,'' says Vergara, a 55-year-old Chilean immigrant 
who specializes in poking into urban corners and enclaves. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every time you look at something here, you come up with a  
sense of identity,'' he says. ``You can drive for 10 miles in this 
environment; it's so big, you could dump Philadelphia here. And it 
happened in 15 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles he's talking about is one where older buildings  
are retooled, redesigned, even just repainted to fit their new 
Latino owners. Space -- ``transnational space,'' Vergara calls it -- 
is used differently. Distances and proximities between things are, 
to the Anglo eye, a little distorted. Exuberance -- mercantile and 
otherwise -- is everywhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Two ways of life are blending, and the results -- ``material  
objects that bear witness to Latino culture'' -- are always 
fascinating and occasionally even artistic. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the poetry of the streets,'' Vergara says. ``Everywhere  
you go, you see the hand of people. You have a sense that it was a 
person doing the job, not a machine. You see the place being made. 
And this is a very malleable area.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pastiches revealed in his photographs point this up  
dramatically. In one, mattresses are for sale, stacked in the front 
yard of a light-blue bungalow with blue skies beyond. Another 
features an old red van, now used as a food cart, painted with 
house paint. The windshield is used for sign display; the motor has 
been removed so the van can't be stolen. 
</P>
<P>
	One photographed junk heap includes an old airplane; on it, in  
English, someone has written: ``Will it ever fly?'' A junkyard 
truck becomes an ice-cream shop -- another L.A. castaway converted 
into an entrepreneurial accouterment. A man paves over his backyard 
because it's more convenient -- and a step away from the mud of his 
home village in Mexico; another, a gardener, pours water into yard 
dirt and smells it to remind him of home. 
</P>
<P>
	Vergara documents the business of the neighborhoods, too: The  
guy who paints elaborate portraits from snapshots. The barber who 
makes house calls. The woman who operates the clothing store whose 
outside wall is festooned with hanging clothes, both painted and 
real; when a car crashed through the outside wall, she made it into 
a window. The stores, many with elaborately designed, hand-painted 
signs designed to catch the eye and stop the passer-by. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a can-do attitude -- people who are willing to do just  
about anything to make a sale,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	And the patchwork fences in Latino neighborhoods -- ``the  
archaeology of LA,'' Vergara calls them. They are cobbled together 
from scraps of metal, wood and wiring, much of it still bearing the 
sign of its original incarnation (``DiSalvo Trading Company,'' one 
segment says). Everything is game for use and reuse. 
</P>
<P>
	It's about survival in a world that's new to the immigrants but  
also similar; after all, many of them come from only a couple 
hundred miles south, albeit from more rural areas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Much of this is imposing rural ways on what is a very advanced  
city,'' Vergara says. ``Their ideal is to reconstruct `el 
ranchito,' because that's the way they grew up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vergaro is fascinated with what humans infuse into -- and what  
they draw from -- the places they inhabit. 
</P>
<P>
	His best-known project explored how places change over time; for  
it, he photographed buildings and storefronts in New York City over 
two decades. Some improved over time, but many decayed. Both the 
changed and the unchanged told compelling stories. 
</P>
<P>
	Vergara ends ``El Nuevo Mundo'' with more fences -- not in  
neighborhoods but miles south, at the U.S.-Mexico border. One juts 
340 feet into the Pacific Ocean to keep people out, which he finds 
unimaginable. 
</P>
<P>
	His notion: Such approaches won't work forever in a culture  
where people are continually going back and forth, building new 
lives while maintaining strong ties to the culture that produced 
them -- which, after all, isn't really that far away. 
</P>
<P>
	``People come to a place with tradition, a certain rhythm of  
living life. They come to California thinking this used to be OUR 
land, so there's no sense of going to a foreign country,'' Vergara 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	``And they ask: What is the way life should be lived? You should  
be close to animals, close to nature. That's what's here. People 
see these pictures and they understand -- it's something that 
they're part of. It's the place that allows you to have these 
experiences, and tells you who you are.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``El Nuevo Mundo'' is on exhibit at the Smithsonian  
Institution's Cooper Hewitt, National Design Museum, until Sept. 5. 
Information is available at 212-849-8400. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
