<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Cos. Search for Brazilian Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- U.S. oil giant Texaco Inc. and  
Brazil's Petrobras will jointly search and drill for oil on the 
continental shelf near Rio, the Brazilian company announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies are expected tomrrow to sign two contracts worth a  
reported $1.5 billion for exploration and production in the Campos 
Basin, which now produces more than half of Brazil's petroleum, a 
Petrobras spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Each company will own 42.5 percent of the venture, but Texaco  
will be the operator, the spokeswoman said. Japanese group Nissho 
Iwai Corp. holds a 12.75 percent stake and Brazil's Odebrecht has 
the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	Texaco was among the big winners in Brazil's auction of 27 oil  
and gas blocks last month, acquiring a share of three areas. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
