<DOCNO> APW19990707.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 15:17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NYC Residents Cope With Power Outage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The stench of spoiling meat rose from small  
groceries left without refrigeration by a heat wave blackout 
Wednesday, as hundreds of police guarded against looting and 
directed traffic down avenues where signal lights were dark. 
</P>
<P>
	Some shops sold durable goods by what light came through doors  
and windows, but other stores remained shuttered in the midst of 
the blackout affecting upper Manhattan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We lost about $500 worth of meat products,'' said Dimitrios  
Tabares, owner of the Tabares grocery store on West 187th Street. 
Employees had to use flashlights to find their way through darkened 
aisles, and the store was selling out of batteries, flashlights and 
ice. 
</P>
<P>
	At La Mundial grocery, thawed chickens spilled out of boxes in  
the basement freezer, where the temperature topped 70 degrees. The 
stench of bad meat wafted from the open freezer door up the rickety 
wooden stairs to the sidewalk. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to lose all the meat,'' manager Reso Infante said.  
</P>
<P>
	The blackout affected 68,000 businesses and households in a  
250-square-block area above Manhattan's 155th Street. 
</P>
<P>
	After two days of record heat and record demand for electricity,  
six of the 14 feeder cables into the area failed, forcing the 
utility company, Consolidated Edison, to shut the rest down Tuesday 
night, spokesman Michael Spall said. 
</P>
<P>
	The utility hoped to have power completely restored to the area  
by Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	About 500 police were sent to patrol the area. Officers reported  
a handful of break-ins and nine arrests, a sharp difference from 
the 1977 blackout that affected the whole city and led to 
widespread looting. 
</P>
<P>
	This power outage left 200,000 people in the dark without air  
conditioners or fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the lights turned off, everyone got scared,'' said  
13-year-old Victor Pena. ``I felt like I was in a maze. I could see 
nothing. But I had to feel my way around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His mother, Thelma Goris, said other people also had reason to  
be afraid. 
</P>
<P>
	``I heard ambulances all night. They were taking old people and  
newborns to the hospital because it was as hot as an oven and they 
couldn't resist the heat,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Marielina Bonilla, 18, spent the night sleeping on her  
second-floor fire escape. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was scared I might fall asleep and roll off,'' she said.  
``But the alternative was to stay inside, where I was burning.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
