<DOCNO> APW19990707.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 15:17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NYC Residents Cope With Power Outage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The stench of spoiling meat rose from small  
groceries left without refrigeration by a heat wave blackout 
Wednesday, as hundreds of police guarded against looting and 
directed traffic down avenues where signal lights were dark. 
</P>
<P>
	Some shops sold durable goods by what light came through doors  
and windows, but other stores remained shuttered in the midst of 
the blackout affecting upper Manhattan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We lost about $500 worth of meat products,'' said Dimitrios  
Tabares, owner of the Tabares grocery store on West 187th Street. 
Employees had to use flashlights to find their way through darkened 
aisles, and the store was selling out of batteries, flashlights and 
ice. 
</P>
<P>
	At La Mundial grocery, thawed chickens spilled out of boxes in  
the basement freezer, where the temperature topped 70 degrees. The 
stench of bad meat wafted from the open freezer door up the rickety 
wooden stairs to the sidewalk. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to lose all the meat,'' manager Reso Infante said.  
</P>
<P>
	The blackout affected 68,000 businesses and households in a  
250-square-block area above Manhattan's 155th Street. 
</P>
<P>
	After two days of record heat and record demand for electricity,  
six of the 14 feeder cables into the area failed, forcing the 
utility company, Consolidated Edison, to shut the rest down Tuesday 
night, spokesman Michael Spall said. 
</P>
<P>
	The utility hoped to have power completely restored to the area  
by Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	About 500 police were sent to patrol the area. Officers reported  
a handful of break-ins and nine arrests, a sharp difference from 
the 1977 blackout that affected the whole city and led to 
widespread looting. 
</P>
<P>
	This power outage left 200,000 people in the dark without air  
conditioners or fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the lights turned off, everyone got scared,'' said  
13-year-old Victor Pena. ``I felt like I was in a maze. I could see 
nothing. But I had to feel my way around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His mother, Thelma Goris, said other people also had reason to  
be afraid. 
</P>
<P>
	``I heard ambulances all night. They were taking old people and  
newborns to the hospital because it was as hot as an oven and they 
couldn't resist the heat,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Marielina Bonilla, 18, spent the night sleeping on her  
second-floor fire escape. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was scared I might fall asleep and roll off,'' she said.  
``But the alternative was to stay inside, where I was burning.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 18:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jesse Jackson Tours With Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PINE RIDGE, S.D. (AP) -- President Clinton had just finished an  
impassioned call for a sea change in how the government treats 
American Indians when some in the audience began chanting for a man 
who hadn't uttered a word: Jesse Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	``Speak, Jesse Speak!'' a few people called. ``Run, Jesse Run!''  
others said. 
</P>
<P>
	One women just yelled ``Reverend Jackson!'' over and over again.  
</P>
<P>
	This is how it's been since Clinton began his national poverty  
tour in Appalachia three days ago with Jackson at his side. 
</P>
<P>
	It started with ringing applause in Hazard, Ky., to Jackson's  
call to ``keep hope alive,'' and continued through Pine Ridge on 
Wednesday when even Clinton gave a nod to Jackson for helping shape 
his message of economic empowerment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to thank my good friend Jesse Jackson for never letting  
us forget our common obligations,'' Clinton said. Jackson did not 
address the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	At times, their pairing made for interesting political theater.  
Clinton and Jackson may not have literally been competing with each 
other, but their reputations as men of the people certainly were. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not more popular than he is,'' Jackson said as he awaited  
Clinton on the tarmac at South Dakota's Ellsworth Air Force Base. 
``Both of us are well known, but he is the president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Monday night in Memphis, Clinton and Jackson went together to  
the civil rights museum in the Lorraine Motel where Martin Luther 
King Jr. was assassinated. After their tour, Jackson grabbed a cell 
phone and called the widow of Ricky Byrdsong, the former 
Northwestern University basketball coach shot to death last week by 
a white supremacist. 
</P>
<P>
	When Jackson finished the conversation, he handed the phone to  
Clinton so he could chat with the slain man's widow. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson tagged along and worked the masses alongside Clinton at  
Ellsworth. On the far edge of the crowd, a woman held up a sign 
that read, ``Jesse Rules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She wanted to thank Jackson for bringing the three American  
soldiers back from Yugoslavia unharmed. Jackson kissed her, 
autographed the sign and posed for a picture with her and Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson and Clinton also were side by side with Oglala Lakota  
Sioux on a courtyard at the reservation's high school. 
</P>
<P>
	As Clinton finished shaking hands, Jackson lingered to play with  
2-year-old Aaron Black Bull. He took Aaron in his arms and carried 
him over to Clinton, who kissed the boy on the cheek. 
</P>
<P>
	Both men turned to leave - until a woman called, ``Jesse, we  
want to shake your hand.'' Jackson went back to the crowd and so 
did Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	A blue baseball cap labeled, ``Water is Life'' -- which Clinton  
took off and replaced with a black one that read ``Native 
American'' -- somehow found its way onto Jackson's head. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson attributed the attention he has gotten to the fact that  
he has visited the same places during the past year, advocating the 
same sort of economic investment that Clinton now is touting. 
</P>
<P>
	Plus, he said, he drummed up votes for Clinton in places like  
Pine Ridge in 1992 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a team,'' Jackson said. He likened his alliance with  
Clinton to the interaction between Michael Jordan and Scottie 
Pippen in taking the Chicago Bulls to six NBA championships. 
</P>
<P>
	``He does have a chemistry, an undeniable chemistry, with the  
people,'' Jackson said of Clinton. ``He's touching a live nerve 
when he's touching the needs of working poor people and the middle 
class at the same time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton left Pine Ridge in his usual limousine. Jackson climbed  
into a van a few vehicles back in the motorcade. The van was called 
``Special 1.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
