<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 12:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study Raises Alzheimer's Hopes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Raising hopes of someday preventing Alzheimer's, scientists have  
developed a vaccine that in mice appears to ward off and even 
reduce the brain-clogging deposits that are characteristic of the 
disease. 
</P>
<P>
	It is uncertain whether the treatment will work in humans, but  
the San Francisco pharmaceutical company behind the research wants 
to test it on people soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Deposits in the brain of a sticky protein called amyloid are one  
of the characteristics of Alzheimer's. The vaccine appears to 
prevent the formation of these so-called plaques in mice that were 
genetically engineered to overproduce amyloid. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Zaven Khachaturian, senior medical adviser to the  
Alzheimer's Association, called the study a landmark. 
</P>
<P>
	``If one can repeat the same phenomenon in humans, it will have  
a very important impact,'' he said. Even if it fails to produce a 
treatment, it introduces the idea of using a vaccination against 
protein deposits, which are associated with a variety of diseases, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	There is no known cure for Alzheimer's, which is believed to  
affect more than 4 million Americans. The patients, most of them 
older than 60, progress from forgetfulness to dementia and usually 
die five to 10 years after diagnosis. 
</P>
<P>
	In the study, published in Thursday's issue of the journal  
Nature, a team of researchers led by Dale Schenk at Elan Corp. 
tried to trick the immune system of the mice to recognize amyloid 
as a foreign substance that should be attacked. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers injected nine 6-week-old mice with amyloid  
combined with substances that excite the immune system. Seventeen 
other mice of the same age did not get the vaccine. 
</P>
<P>
	When the mouse brains were dissected after a year, the  
researchers were surprised to find no or very small plaques in the 
injected mice, while the unvaccinated mice had extensive deposits. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers then tried a more ambitious experiment:  
injecting the vaccine into 24 1-year-old mice that already had 
plaques. Twenty-four similar mice did not get the vaccine. 
</P>
<P>
	``We saw that it completely stopped the further progression of  
the disease,'' Schenk said. ``It looks like it might have actually 
diminished the plaques.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elan wants to start trials with people later this year. Schenk  
said that the researchers hope to submit a vaccine to the Food and 
Drug Administration for approval in five years. 
</P>
<P>
	But there are a number of reasons the method may not prevent or  
halt Alzheimer's in humans. 
</P>
<P>
	Most important, the amyloid plaques may be a symptom of the  
disease, rather than the cause. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Alzheimer's patients have other changes in the brain that  
the mice do not fully exhibit, such as tangles of protein inside 
nerve cells, according to Dr. Blas Frangione, head of the 
Alzheimer's research unit at the New York University School of 
Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	If the vaccine does work, scientists will face another  
challenge: determining who needs it. While detectable genetic flaws 
cause some Alzheimer's cases, most patients have no such telltale 
markers. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we are going to have the maximal effect of this, we need to  
find out who has the disease, who is at risk, much earlier,'' 
Khachaturian said. 
</P>
<P>
	Neurobiologist Peter St. George-Hyslop at the University of  
Toronto said the study raises the prospect of using immunization to 
treat or prevent other diseases associated with protein deposits. 
Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, the fatal human brain disorder thought 
to be related to mad cow disease, would be a candidate. So would 
Parkinson's disease and myeloma, a form of cancer that overproduces 
protein in bone marrow. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 10:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aussies Choose Hewitt for Davis Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Lleyton Hewitt will make his Davis Cup debut when Australia  
faces the United States in this month's quarterfinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Hewitt was placed on the team Wednesday, replacing injured Mark  
Philippoussis for the July 16-18 matches in Brookline, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	The 18-year-old player reached the third round at Wimbledon  
before losing to Boris Becker. He joins an Aussie team that also 
features U.S. Open champion Patrick Rafter, Todd Woodbridge and 
Mark Woodforde. 
</P>
<P>
	Hewitt and Rafter are expected to play singles. Woodbridge and  
Woodforde, the ``Woodies,'' will play doubles. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. team is composed of Pete Sampras, Jim Courier, Todd  
Martin and doubles specialist Alex O'Brien. 
</P>
<P>
	Philippoussis hurt his knee during his Wimbledon quarterfinal,  
quitting early in the second set against Sampras, the eventual 
champion. 
</P>
<P>
	Philippoussis later withdrew from the Davis Cup, prompting  
Rafter to recommend Hewitt. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not even an issue right now,'' said Rafter, a  
Wimbledon semifinalist. ``He's definitely put the runs on the board 
and I still think he has a chance of playing regardless. I put him 
high on the list.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hewitt, a swift, hard-hitting baseliner, began his ascent in  
January 1998. He won a tournament in his hometown of Adelaide to 
become the lowest-ranked player (No. 550) to capture an ATP event. 
He is now ranked No. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Captain Tom Gullikson has not said if Sampras will play singles.  
Courier and Martin led the United States to a 3-2 win over Britain 
in April, inspiring Sampras to play in the next round. 
</P>
<P>
	Sampras has said he doesn't want to take a singles spot from  
Courier or Martin, but Martin has offered to step aside. 
</P>
<P>
	In other Davis Cup quarterfinals, 1997 French Open champion  
Gustavo Kuerten, a surprise quarterfinalist at Wimbledon, will lead 
Brazil against France. 
</P>
<P>
	Yevgeny Kafelnikov will lead Russia against a Slovak Republic  
team featuring Karol Kucera in Moscow. Belgium and Switzerland meet 
in Brussels. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 15:20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Kashmir Fighting Escalates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DRAS, India (AP) -- India captured key mountain peaks Wednesday  
from Pakistan-based Islamic fighters in the battle for Kashmir, 
while Pakistan held off on its promise to withdraw forces from 
Indian territory. 
</P>
<P>
	India blew up an ammunition bunker and captured a third key  
lookout in craggy Himalayan ridges over Kashmir's main highway, 
which is also India's primary military supply route. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Pakistan's pledge to call back the insurgents, an Indian  
commander in the Batalik sector battle zone said there was no sign 
of a rebel retreat. Instead, the rebels attacked positions they had 
lost earlier this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``The enemy is giving us stiff resistance,'' said Col. Bikram  
Singh, the Indian military spokesman. Five Pakistani artillery 
shells landed in Kargil town. One shell hit the office of state-run 
All India Radio, killing one policeman, a local commander said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Pakistan, defiant government and militant groups waited for  
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif to return Thursday from 
London, where Prime Minister Tony Blair encouraged him to fulfill 
the agreement he made with President Clinton in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	White House officials said Sharif agreed on Sunday that the  
intruding forces would be returned to the Pakistani side of the 
Line of Control, which divides Kashmir between the two 
nuclear-power neighbors. 
</P>
<P>
	India says Pakistani troops are leading the rebel forces. The  
Islamabad government, however, denies the Indian claim, but in the 
past has acknowledged its influence over the separatists. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan's army chief, Gen. Pervez Musharraf, said Tuesday that  
a request for retreat would have to wait until Sharif returned. But 
he said Pakistan ultimately had no control over the insurgents. 
</P>
<P>
	The militant groups in Pakistan said they would rather die than  
withdraw from their fight to separate Muslim-majority Kashmir from 
Hindu-dominated India. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our mujahedeen will fight until the last drop of blood,''  
United Jehad Council chairman Syed Salauddin said in Islamabad. He 
called Sharif's meeting with Clinton a ``stab in the back of the 
Kashmiri freedom struggle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fiercest fighting so far was under way on icy, knife-edged  
ridges in Batalik, east of Kargil, where Indian soldiers captured 
three heights, two of them Tuesday night and the third on 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In New Delhi, India's Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee said  
military operations will continue until all Pakistan-based forces 
that two months ago crossed the 1972 cease-fire line dividing the 
disputed Kashmir region have left. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said India would not accept mediation by a third party.  
</P>
<P>
	India has ruled out a safe passage for nearly 700 Islamic  
fighters who crossed four miles into the cease-fire line. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have to find their own way out,'' said Raminder Singh  
Jassal, Indian foreign ministry spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian soldiers said they recovered the bodies of 77 Pakistani  
soldiers this week from the battlefields in the Dras and Batalik 
sectors. 
</P>
<P>
	India says 542 Pakistani soldiers and more than 150 Islamic  
guerrillas have been killed, while 283 Indian soldiers have died, 
451 were wounded and 10 are missing. The figures cannot be 
independently confirmed. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 15:20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
