<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 07:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Questions Cisneros Over Tapes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal judge on Tuesday questioned the  
effort by lawyers for former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros to 
prevent tapes secretly recorded by his former lover from being used 
as evidence in his upcoming conspiracy trial. 
</P>
<P>
	In the eighth day of a pre-trial hearing on the admissibility of  
the tapes, U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin again demanded that 
Cisneros' legal team show that the recordings made by Linda Jones 
don't represent what Cisneros actually said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sporkin has indicated growing skepticism in recent days over the  
defense's argument that the tapes should be rejected wholesale 
because they bear the signs of some editing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's get down to the brass tacks here,'' Sporkin said  
Tuesday, expressing irritation at the lengthy pre-trial 
maneuverings. ``The relevant issue here is: The statements the 
government wants to put in, are they reliable or aren't they 
reliable?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under federal law, tapes of intercepted phone communications may  
not be admitted into evidence if the person doing the taping has an 
unlawful intent in making them. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros' attorneys are challenging use of the recordings on two  
grounds: They allege Mrs. Jones was extorting Cisneros for ``hush 
money'' during the period she was taping her phone conversations 
with him; and the tapes are copies, in some cases altered, of 
since-destroyed originals. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros' lawyers have not accused Ms. Jones of manufacturing  
conversations by pasting together different sections, and the 
government's tape expert testified he found no evidence of 
splicing. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense, however, asserts that she deleted some passages  
that would show Cisneros in a positive light and eliminated 
sections unfavorable to herself. 
</P>
<P>
	``The courts have said if it is not original, if an item has  
been tampered with, it does not come into evidence,'' said Barry 
Simon, one of Cisneros' lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Tuesday, Simon forged ahead with his argument that the  
tapes should be thrown out. 
</P>
<P>
	Exhibit A was a tape recording of a Dec. 3, 1992 phone  
conversation between the two former lovers. While phone company 
records indicate the call lasted 42 minutes, only 20 minutes of the 
conversation were captured on the tape that Ms. Jones provided 
federal investigators, Simon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros' lawyers contend all 88 tapes handed over by Ms. Jones  
-- 26 of which the government is seeking to use at Cisneros' 
September trial -- are inadmissible. Prosecutors say only four of 
the 26 tapes were edited by Ms. Jones, largely to erase her threats 
to Cisneros. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense contends that the pauses reflect instances where she  
was deleting information. Mrs. Jones acknowledged on the witness 
stand that she edited out passages where she threatened to publicly 
reveal Cisneros' payments to her if the money flow stopped. 
</P>
<P>
	The tapes are crucial to Independent Counsel David Barrett's  
case that Cisneros, while being considered for a post in the 
Clinton Cabinet, conspired with Ms. Jones to understate his 
payments to her. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros acknowledged during his Cabinet background check that  
he gave her financial support, but prosecutors contend he falsely 
told the FBI he never paid her more than $10,000 annually. 
</P>
<P>
	The 18-count indictment against Cisneros alleges he paid her  
more than $264,000 between 1990 and 1993. He has pleaded innocent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 11:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Berlin Power Co. To Cut Jobs, Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- The Berlin electrical utility, Bewag,  
said today it will eliminate up to 4,000 jobs, or about half of its 
work force, over the next three years as part of an effort to cut 
costs by $555 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The utility said pressure to reduce prices required that it cut  
costs to maintain its market share of 80 percent in Berlin and 5 
percent in Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Bewag is facing pressure in its home market, with Germany's  
largest utility RWE AG having made Berlin a key expansion target. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Germany's cartel office is considering cases  
against Bewag's refusal to allow third-party access to Berlin's 
power grid. If Bewag loses, it could face heavy competition from 
other producers who stand ready to encroach into the company's home 
market. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
