<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Noon EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	First Lady Vows Action for N.Y.  
</P>
<P>
	WEST DAVENPORT, N.Y. (AP) -- First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton  
launched her campaign for the Senate today with a pledge to be a 
``strong and effective advocate on behalf of the people of New 
York.'' Addressing criticism that she is a ``carpetbagger'' for 
choosing to seek election from a state where she has never lived or 
worked, she said ``What I am for is maybe as important, if not more 
important than where I am from.'' She is the only first lady ever 
to seek public office. Mrs. Clinton plans a four-day swing through 
eastern and central New York, a traditional GOP stronghold. For her 
first official campaign appearance, Mrs. Clinton chose the 
homestead of the man she hopes to succeed, Sen. Daniel Patrick 
Moynihan. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Says Kosovo Turmoil Falling  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO and U.N. officials said today  
that violence in Kosovo has declined sharply since peacekeepers 
arrived and it soon will be up to Kosovars to keep the peace 
themselves. But NATO troops remain essential for maintaining the 
peace, as evidenced today when a large, well-armed escort by French 
soldiers and police prevented violence from erupting during a march 
by ethnic Albanians through the Serb-held section of the divided 
city of Kosovska Mitrovica. Of an estimated 860,000 Albanians who 
fled or were expelled from Kosovo during the conflict, more than 
600,000 have returned since NATO peacekeepers began arriving June 
12. 

</P>
<P>
	Disney, Katzenberg Settle Lawsuit  
</P>
<P>
	BURBANK, Calif. (AP) -- Walt Disney and Jeffrey Katzenberg have  
settled a bitter lawsuit filed by the former studio chief claiming 
he was owed at least $250 million by the entertainment giant. Terms 
of the settlement weren't disclosed. Katzenberg, who left his post 
of studio chief at Disney in 1994 after he was denied a promotion, 
sued claiming the company owed him a 2 percent bonus from profits 
for shows produced during his tenure and future profits of all 
films. Disney had argued that Katzenberg forfeited that bonus 
because he left two years before the end of his six-year contract. 

</P>
<P>
	Eastern Heat Wave Eases Somewhat  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The heat wave that brought sweaty misery and  
even death eased today as a cool front moved through the East, but 
power outages including a big blackout in New York City left 
hundreds of thousands of people sweating in the dark through the 
night. Record highs and power demands were set again yesterday in 
the mid-Atlantic and Northeast as utilities scrambled to keep 
electricity flowing around flaming transformers and melting power 
lines. For today, highs only in the 70s and 80s were forecast in 
much of New England and in the 90s farther south. 

</P>
<P>
	Panel To Oppose DNA Testing  
</P>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- A federal panel has decided to oppose  
mandatory DNA testing for anyone charged with a crime, a 
recommendation that could be adopted by the Justice Department and 
used as guidance by states, USA Today reported. The newspaper 
reported yesterday that the National Commission on the Future of 
DNA Evidence is expected this month to recommend that Attorney 
General Janet Reno reject mass DNA testing because such a process 
could overwhelm the justice system. DNA has already been used as 
evidence to convict -- and exonerate -- crime suspects. 

</P>
<P>
	Barnesandnoble.com Selling Music  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Barnesandnoble.com, trying to keep pace with  
rival Amazon.com, today launched a music superstore that will be 
part of the newly redesigned bookselling Web site. 
Barnesandnoble.com's move into music comes more than a year after 
Amazon.com added a vast music selection to its site and quickly 
became the leading music retailer on the Internet, toppling CDNow. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 12  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before noon EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 12.98 to 11,122.14. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,401-1,204. The Nasdaq was up 2.04 to 
2,738.82. 

</P>
<P>
	Mark Wohlers Undergoes Elbow Surgery  
</P>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Cincinnati Reds reliever Mark Wohlers, trying  
to save his career from control problems and a torn elbow ligament, 
underwent elbow surgery today and is expected to miss about a year. 
Wohlers, who set a Braves record for saves in 1996, lost his 
ability to throw strikes last season. Since his trade to Cincinnati 
in April, he had been pitching in the minor leagues in hopes of 
regaining his control and working his way back to the majors. But 
the elbow injury has thrown his playing future into doubt. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  

  	   	
</P>
