<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Waste Management Shares Plunge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Shares in Waste Management Inc. plunged 37  
percent Wednesday after the largest U.S. trash hauler warned both 
quarterly and year-end earnings will fall at least 10 percent short 
of expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Waste Management said Tuesday night that a $250 million  
shortfall in its core solid waste business would result in 
second-quarter earnings per share in the range of 67 to 70 cents, 
compared to the 78 cents per share projected by analysts. 
</P>
<P>
	For the year, the company projected earnings of $2.65 per share,  
well short of the $3.02 predicted by analysts polled by First Call 
Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The Houston company's stock price closed down $19.62 1/2 to $33.93 3/4  
on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Both revised figures would be increases from last year, when  
Waste Management earned 41 cents per share in the second quarter 
and $1.82 for the year. But the new estimates fall well short of 
the company's own expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although we are disappointed with the revised projections, we  
remain proud of our accomplishments over the past 12 months,'' 
Waste Management chief executive officer Rodney Proto said. ``And 
the fact that the new full-year 1999 earnings expectation still 
represents a minimum of 46 percent improvement over comparable 1998 
results.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Melville Cody, an analyst with Sanders Morris Mundy, said  
Wednesday that the loss stems from an unexpected downturn in June, 
normally a busy month when business is supposed to increase. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they lost some business from price increases, but  
there could be a service component involved,'' she said. ``They've 
cut $800 million in costs out of the company and let some people 
go, and it's possible customers were not getting the service they 
were accustomed to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Proto said the company is investigating the causes of the  
shortfall and will provide more details when it formally releases 
its earnings report on Aug. 3. 
</P>
<P>
	Cody also said the company might have been too optimistic about  
quickly integrating its new components after Houston-based USA 
Waste Services and Oak Brook, Ill.-based Waste Management closed a 
$13.5 billion merger last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The company retained the Waste Management name, though USA Waste  
effectively gained control of its larger but struggling former 
rival. The combined company then bought Mt. Laurel, N.J.-based 
Eastern Environmental Services Inc. in late 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a tremendous undertaking to do it all (both mergers) in  
one year,'' Cody said. ``They probably set their sights too high 
and set expectations on Wall Street too high.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
