<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Palmer To Play at Senior Open  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Fans, golfers and organizers all  
felt the disappointment when Jack Nicklaus withdrew from the U.S. 
Senior Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Arnold Palmer did his best to ease it.  
</P>
<P>
	Palmer, who at 69 still retains the aura that made him one of  
the nation's most popular sports figures, drew a huge throng of 
fans as he played a practice round at the Des Moines Golf and 
Country Club on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials had not been sure if Palmer would make it because he  
has been bothered by a pulled muscle in his rib cage. But Palmer 
said he never wavered in his commitment to play the 72-hole 
tournament, which begins Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no doubt in my mind,'' he said. ``I had some problem  
I had treated. I feel fine. I was going to play with or without 
that problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nicklaus, one of Palmer's few rivals in worldwide golf acclaim,  
decided not to play because of an aching left hip. 
</P>
<P>
	He had the hip replaced on Jan. 27 and returned to tournament  
play in May. But Nicklaus hasn't played competitively since 
withdrawing after 45 holes of the Senior Players Championship two 
weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The hip hurt so much in that tournament that Nicklaus had to  
ride in a cart before withdrawing because he was in so much pain. 
</P>
<P>
	``My hip is starting to feel good,'' he said. ``But I think it  
would be wise on my part to wait a week or so to test it again. I'm 
very eager to play golf, but I just don't think I should right 
now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nicklaus, 59, won the U.S. Senior Open in 1991 and 1993. His  
last victory on the Senior Tour came at The Tradition in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think to a man we're disappointed that Jack is not playing  
and to a man we hope that he recovers quickly,'' defending champion 
Hale Irwin said. ``Certainly the U.S. Open is not complete without 
Jack being in there. 
</P>
<P>
	``But at the same time, I think we're going to have a wonderful  
tournament without Jack.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer certainly brought plenty of luster with his appearance at  
the biggest golf event ever to hit Iowa. Fans lined two and three 
deep behind the ropes begged Palmer for an autograph as he walked 
from the driving range to the chipping green, with several 
reporters and TV cameras following along. 
</P>
<P>
	``Does this mean I'm in Arnie's Army?'' one reporter asked.  
</P>
<P>
	By mid-afternoon on a perfect summer day, an estimated 5,000  
fans were walking the course with Palmer, who said he wasn't there 
just for practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't come all the way from Latrobe, Pa., to Des Moines,  
Iowa, not to play,'' Palmer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer also said he was impressed with the crowds. The  
tournament was sold out in advance for the first time in the 
20-year history of the Senior Open and the attendance for Tuesday's 
practice round was estimated at 27,000. About 25,000 showed up for 
Monday's practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's great the USGA has seen fit to bring the Open  
here,'' Palmer said. ``I think they should do more things like this 
to spread the championships around. It's good for golf.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
