<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pregnant Woman Awakens From Coma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Maria Lydia Hernandez Lopez had been in a  
coma for a month. Doctors didn't expect her or the twins in her 
womb to survive. Her family prepared to remove life support and 
called in a priest. 
</P>
<P>
	As he prayed, Mrs. Lopez suddenly coughed and moved.  
</P>
<P>
	Reflexes, doctors said. A sign from God, relatives insisted, and  
decided to continue her care. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the 25-year-old woman is awake and can communicate by  
wiggling her fingers. She gave birth to two girls last month. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you were there from the beginning to now, it's just very  
awesome,'' her sister Adela Hernandez said Wednesday. ``It is a 
miracle. We just thank God.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Mrs. Lopez began complaining of headaches. Doctors  
blamed them on her pregnancy. 
</P>
<P>
	On April 24, she had trouble breathing and slipped into the coma  
in an ambulance on the way to the hospital. It turned out that a 
blood vessel had popped inside her brain. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Lopez has a condition called arteriovenous malformation, in  
which people are born with malformed or tangled blood vessels in 
the brain. Over time, the vessels can pressure neural tissue or 
rupture. 
</P>
<P>
	At the University of California Medical Center in Los Angeles,  
she underwent embolization, in which doctors inject a glue-like 
substance to cut the blood flow to the tangled vessels. 
</P>
<P>
	``For three weeks she didn't get any better,'' said her  
neurosurgeon, John Frazee. ``I was having discussions with her 
family about the chances of her recovering. ... I didn't think she 
would wake up to take care of herself, let alone take care of her 
children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In mid-May, the family was about to remove life support. Then  
she moved. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I saw that, I knew she was not gone. That was a sign for  
me,'' Hernandez said. ``That's where my faith came in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Intensive care continued, including a procedure to drain fluid  
from her brain in early June, just before she slowly began to 
regain consciousness and respond to simple commands. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, on June 9, she awoke. Six days later, she delivered  
twins. Arizandy Leann was released from the hospital Saturday and 
Brianna Angel was expected to be released today. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Lopez, who underwent further brain surgery last week, is  
slowly recovering, Frazee said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've given up making predictions,'' Frazee said. ``The fact  
that she is continuing to rapidly improve after this surgery leads 
me to be hopeful that she can do normal things. It will take 
several months for that to occur. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one knows for sure,'' he added, ``but that's certainly  
possible.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
