<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Are Mostly Lower / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices were mostly lower Wednesday in quiet  
trading as demand slipped due to a slew of upcoming corporate bond 
sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 1/8 point,  
or $1.25 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the 
opposite direction, rose to 6.04 percent from Tuesday's 6.03 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Treasurys ended lower for the second straight day, as  
investors prepared for a number of upcoming offerings by corporate 
and agency issuers. Among those companies selling debt are Ford 
Motor Co. and its Ford Motor Credit Co. financing unit, which are 
expected to price up to $7.5 billion in debt later this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Demand for corporate bonds lowers demand for government bonds  
because corporate offerings generally have higher yields. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were unchanged, and intermediate maturities were unchanged to down 
3/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Tuesday, yields on three-month Treasury bills  
rose to 4.64 percent while the discount fell 0.05 percentage point 
to 4.52 percent compared with their auction price late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-month yields were 4.70 percent, as the discount fell 0.03  
percentage point to 4.53 percent from their auction rate Tuesday. 
One-year yields slipped to 5.00 percent as the discount fell 0.03 
percentage point to 4.76 percent from Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, was unchanged at 4.94 percent from late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 1/16 point to 118 17/32. The average 
yield to maturity was unchanged at 5.55 percent from late Tuesday. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
