<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Charge Boeing With Interfering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government is accusing Boeing Co. of  
interfering with enforcement of affirmative action and 
nondiscrimination requirements for federal contractors. 
</P>
<P>
	Complaints filed by the Labor Department against the  
Seattle-based aircraft maker and defense contractor claim that 
Boeing refused federal inspectors access to records and facilities 
in Seattle, Wichita, Kan., and Mesa, Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
	Labor Secretary Alexis Herman said her agency ``must -- and is  
entitled to -- have reasonable access to the premises and records of 
companies which benefit from doing business with the federal 
government. Denying us that access cannot -- and will not -- be 
tolerated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing officials said the company is trying to be cooperative  
but called some of the government's requests ``unreasonable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The company has been and is cooperating with the agency in a  
number of ongoing audits and investigations and will continue to do 
so,'' said Boeing spokesman Peter Conte. 
</P>
<P>
	``To the extent that Boeing has withheld data from the agency,  
it has done so based upon its good-faith belief that the request is 
either unreasonable or exceeds the scope of the Office of Federal 
Contracting Compliance Programs' authority.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department charges were filed on Tuesday with federal  
administrative law judges, who offer a first avenue of recourse for 
government agencies outside the normal court system. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency contends that Boeing has disrupted its investigation  
of a class-action complaint alleging race discrimination filed by 
an employee of a commercial aircraft facility in Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	The employee is among black Boeing workers who filed a lawsuit  
contending they were treated with hostility and were passed over 
for promotions that went to less-qualified white workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The other two government complaints charge Boeing with failure  
to cooperate in routine compliance reviews at commercial aircraft 
and military space and defense facilities in Wichita and at a 
training facility in Mesa. 
</P>
<P>
	With $11 billion in government business last year and 230,000  
workers nationwide, Boeing is the second-largest defense contractor 
after Lockheed Martin Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal contractors that interfere with nondiscrimination or  
affirmative action rules enforced by Labor's Office of Federal 
Contract Compliance Programs can have contracts canceled or be 
barred from doing future business with the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Conte said Boeing officials hope the dispute can be resolved  
informally. ``If necessary, however, Boeing is prepared to defend 
its positions vigorously and believes it will ultimately prevail,'' 
he said. 






  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 11:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Toll Hits Poor, Elderly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- For most people heat waves merely mean  
discomfort or inconvenience, but they can also kill by the 
thousands -- mostly poor and elderly victims with bodies unable to 
cope with the temperature or wallets unable to afford the costs of 
cooling. 
</P>
<P>
	Only winter's cold kills more people, year after year, than  
heat. Tornadoes, hurricanes, floods and earthquakes are less 
deadly, according to the National Weather Service. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1979 through 1996, a yearly average of 381 people died of  
heat in the United States, the federal Centers for Disease Control 
and Prevention in Atlanta said. It calculated 6,864 heat deaths in 
that time span. 
</P>
<P>
	And the heat wave now baking much of the nation promises to add  
to the toll. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 40-year period from 1936 through 1975, almost 20,000  
people were killed in the United States by the effects of heat and 
solar radiation. 
</P>
<P>
	A sizzling July in 1901 baked the Midwest, claiming more than  
9,500 lives, according to a report in NOAA, the former magazine of 
the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration. That easily 
exceeds the death toll of 6,000 from a hurricane a year earlier 
that struck Galveston, Texas, often cited as the deadliest weather 
event of the 1900s. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1906 an earthquake and fire in San Francisco claimed 452  
lives - fewer than Los Angeles-area heat waves that caused 546 
deaths in 1939, 946 in 1955, and 580 in 1963, a study in the 
journal Environmental Research found. 
</P>
<P>
	Many believe the tolls are understated, listing only those who  
succumb directly to temperature-related conditions such as 
heatstroke. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one can know how many more deaths are advanced by heat wave  
weather, how many diseased or aging hearts surrender that under 
better conditions would have continued functioning,'' the National 
Weather Service reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Indirect casualties can be staggering, with the stress leading  
to a jump in deaths from heart attacks and other causes. During a 
1966 heat wave, the mortality rate more than doubled in New York 
City and leaped fivefold in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	The Centers for Disease Control noted that age is a major factor  
in succumbing to the heat; half the victims are 65 or over. 
</P>
<P>
	Some deaths can be attributed to lack of air conditioning in a  
city where the weather is usually cooler. Others can be traced to 
power outages. Many occur simply because people don't consider the 
danger of heat. 
</P>
<P>
	Many who died in the 1995 Chicago heat wave were frail,  
frightened or alone. Some died behind boarded windows, their fear 
of intruders contributing to their demise. Others lost their lives 
when no one came to check on them. 
</P>
<P>
	Cities are particularly dangerous in heat waves. Paving and  
buildings absorb heat and warm the temperature, and air movement is 
restricted by buildings. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 14:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
