<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oneida Rejects Libbey's Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ONEIDA, N.Y. (AP) -- Oneida Ltd.'s board has rejected the latest  
buyout offer from rival glass tableware maker Libbey Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The board, which called Libbey's offer an attempt to gain inside  
information at Oneida, also announced Tuesday that it had 
authorized the repurchase of another 500,000 of its 17 million 
shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Libbey raised its offer for Oneida to $37.50 a share, or about  
$637 million, in late June. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Libbey's third attempt since 1995 to gain control the  
world's largest silverware maker, a strong rival in making 
glassware and other table-top products. 
</P>
<P>
	Oneida board members said they rejected the proposal because it  
included ``substantial contingencies and uncertainties'' including 
concerns over financing and anti-trust laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Oneida rejected the two previous offers. At the company's annual  
meeting May 26, Chief Executive Officer Peter Kallet said the 
118-year-old company wants to remain independent. 
</P>
<P>
	Libbey believes the merged companies would have been more  
profitable. Libbey first approached Oneida about merging in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Libbey, a leading glassware maker based in Toledo, Ohio, had  
revenues of $439.5 million last year with profits of $25.4 million, 
down 30 percent from the previous year. 
</P>
<P>
	Oneida Ltd. last year had sales of $465.9 million, but after  
years of growth, profits fell 32 percent. That prompted the company 
to restructure and lay off 300 workers since January while closing 
two foreign plants. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
