<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ore. Authorities Taped Kinkel Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- A sheriff's office taped jailhouse  
conversations between a school-shooting suspect and his pastor, 
despite having been found in violation of the U.S. Constitution in 
a similar case several years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lane County Sheriff's office in Eugene said Tuesday it taped  
three conversations between pastor Albert Gaines and Kip Kinkel, 
16, who is charged with shooting to death his parents and then 
opening fire at his high school. 
</P>
<P>
	Two students were killed at Thurston High School in Springfield  
on May 21, 1998, and two dozen others were wounded. 
</P>
<P>
	Lane County District Attorney F. Douglass Harcleroad said he had  
not signed off on the recordings, which were done with family 
members or friends of Kinkel's present. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have never authorized, approved or sanctioned the taping of  
a clergy person talking to Mr. Kinkel nor has any of my staff,'' 
Harcleroad wrote in a July 2 letter to a circuit judge. ``The 
sheriff's office employees acted on their own ... I am deeply 
disturbed and frustrated that this incident has occurred.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the tapes will not be used in the case against Kinkel.  
</P>
<P>
	The taping comes three years after law-enforcement authorities  
were criticized for illegally recording a jailhouse confession 
between triple-murder suspect Conan Wayne Hale and his priest. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Hale was later convicted and the tapes were never used  
in his trial, the surreptitious taping brought widespread 
condemnation from religious leaders and free-speech advocates. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Lane County agreed to pay $25,000 to settle a claim  
brought by the Rev. Timothy Mockaitis, who argued that his civil 
rights had been violated by the recordings. 
</P>
<P>
	Harcleroad was found to have violated the U.S. Constitution when  
he authorized the recordings. Hale was sentenced to death in the 
killing of three teen-agers. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal appeals court ruled that the recordings violated the  
Fourth Amendment, the Religious Freedom Restoration Act and the 
Civil Rights Act. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court ruling bars taping of conversations with  
clergy only ``when such members are serving their professional 
capacity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sheriff's office sometimes records conversations between  
inmates and visitors that take place in a secure booth. Sheriff's 
officials said they assumed the rules allowed them to record 
conversations that are social in nature, including when a clergyman 
is involved. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Capt. Paul Sachet, Gaines had said his visit was a  
social one. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Castagna, executive director and legal counselor of the  
Oregon Catholic Conference, said the nature of a conversation could 
quickly turn to legally protected subject matter. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the sheriff starts up the tape recorder, you can't tell  
what direction their visit will take,'' Castagna said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
