<DOCNO> APW19990707.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 17:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Case Against Gay Journalist Dropped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- A judge Wednesday dismissed the case  
against a gay journalist accused of using the Internet to solicit 
sex from a teen-ager. The journalist had argued that he was merely 
doing research for a story. 
</P>
<P>
	On the second day of Bruce Mirken's trial, Judge Rudolph R.  
Loncke dismissed the charge that Mirken attempted to perform a lewd 
and lascivious act on a child. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge agreed with the defense that there was insufficient  
evidence against Mirken, 42, who would have faced up to four years 
in prison if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	``This prosecutor's case was a fraud from day one,'' Mirken  
said. ``They knew they didn't have a case and yet they put it on 
anyway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mirken later cursed at the prosecutor, who did not respond.  
</P>
<P>
	Police started investigating Mirken after he answered an  
electronic message they posted in a chat room, posing as a boy 
named Anthony. Anthony's message said he was looking for an adult 
friend. 
</P>
<P>
	Mirken was arrested last July in a Sacramento park where he went  
to meet who he thought would be the 13-year-old Anthony. 
</P>
<P>
	He was instead met by an undercover police officer taking part  
in a sting operation that had tracked Mirken's e-mail and telephone 
conversations with investigators masquerading as the boy. 
</P>
<P>
	Mirken, whose stories about gay and lesbian culture have  
appeared in publications across the country, contends he 
corresponded with the boy hoping to write an investigative story 
about troubled gay youth. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said, however, that recorded conversations and  
e-mail records between Mirken -- who used the screen name 
``Luvboys343'' -- and the boy were sexually charged and filled with 
flirtatious questions such as, ``Do you skinny-dip?'' and ``Does 
your mother come home during lunch?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm extremely disappointed and saddened that this court would  
take this matter out of the sound judgment of the jury,'' 
prosecutor Perry Sims said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
