<DOCNO> APW19990707.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 14:40:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sugar Sinks on Little Demand  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Sugar futures sank more than 6 percent Wednesday on the Board of  
Trade of the City of New York as new supplies from Brazil and 
Europe saw few takers. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, palladium futures rose sharply, as did copper.  
</P>
<P>
	Sugar futures continued their quick retreat from a rally staged  
last month as heavy Russian buying tapped available supplies of 
refined white sugars in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Importers had worked to beat the Aug. 1 imposition of tariffs  
meant to protect the national sugar beet industry. Prices had 
rallied nearly 40 percent since May on the buying from Russia, the 
world's largest importer. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors now are turning to fundamental supply and demand  
concerns. Brazil, the world's largest producer, is harvesting 
another bumper crop and supplies are beginning to come to market. 
Other key producers also brought in plentiful production this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sugar for October delivery fell .37 cent, or 6.4 percent, to  
5.37 cents a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Copper futures rose sharply on the New York Mercantile Exchange  
as news of a potential mine strike in Canada reinforced ideas 
supplies may be shrinking more quickly than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Falconbridge was trying to avert a strike Thursday at its Kidd  
Creek copper and zinc plant in northern Ontario. 
</P>
<P>
	While a union strike at the mine normally would have little  
effect on production, market participants have been aggressive 
buyers in recent weeks as major producers reduce operations in a 
bid to lift prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The output cutbacks are expected to help balance the  
supply-demand equation that had been continually worsening against 
the backdrop of weaker construction demand in Asia and Europe and 
oversupply. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts noted that Asian demand also is on the rise amid a mild  
recovery underway there. Copper is used in wiring and plumbing. 
</P>
<P>
	September copper rose 2.4 cents to 78.60 cents a pound. Prices  
earlier in the session rose as high as 78.70, the loftiest level in 
10 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Palladium futures bounced higher on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange amid speculation Russia, the world's largest exporter, 
will not make large-scale shipments of the industrial metal until 
next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia for a brief period earlier this year shipped supplies to  
Western manufacturers of automobiles and jewelry, but shipments 
ground to a halt after the government in May imposed a 5 percent 
duty on exports. 
</P>
<P>
	The government now says those duties won't be lifted at least  
until January, according to press reports. That might make it 
unprofitable to resume metals shipments, investors bet. Russia 
produces nearly two-thirds the world's supply of palladium, a metal 
that is seeing rising use especially in the production of catalytic 
converters for cleaner-burning autos. 
</P>
<P>
	Palladium for September delivery rose $6 to $321.15 an ounce.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 15:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> All-Star Debut Gets Extra $250,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Vladimir Guerrero is getting a $250,000 raise  
for making the NL All-Star team for the first time. Only he won't 
see the money for another four years. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because the Montreal Expos outfielder has a unique clause  
in his contract that contains an escalator clause for the final 
season of the deal in 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the $28 million, five-year contract he signed last  
Sept. 1, Guerrero gets $1 million this year, $3.5 million next 
year, $6 million in 2001 and $8 million in 2002. The deal called 
for a $9.5 million salary in 2003, but states it could go up in 
$250,000 increments to as much as $11.5 million for various awards 
and honors. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the raise, Guerrero was among 43 players  
receiving bonuses for making the All-Star game, getting an extra 
$25,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr. got the highest bonus, $125,000.  
Griffey $50,000 for making the AL team and another $75,000 bonus 
for finishing first among all major leaguers in fan voting. 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore's Cal Ripken Jr., an All-Star for the 17th consecutive  
season, and Boston's Jose Offerman each earned $100,000. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the $26 million, four-year contract he signed with  
the Red Sox during the offseason, Offerman would get a $250,000 if 
he makes the All-Star team again during the contract and an 
additional $500,000 if he makes it a third time. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty players will get $50,000 each, and another 19 will get  
$25,000 apiece. 
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles outfielder Gary Sheffield receives $20,000 and  
Chicago White Sox outfielder Magglio Ordonez gets $15,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Eighteen players don't get any bonus money: Paul Byrd, Jeromy  
Burnitz, Sean Casey, David Cone, Alex Gonzalez, John Jaha, Derek 
Jeter, Brian Jordan, Barry Larkin, Pedro Martinez, Kevin Millwood, 
Dave Nilsson, Rafael Palmiero, Mariano Rivera, Jose Rosada, Sammy 
Sosa, Bernie Williams and Jeff Zimmerman. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas outfielder Juan Gonzalez missed out on a $50,000 bonus by  
saying he wouldn't go to next Tuesday night's game at Boston's 
Fenway Park unless he was elected to start. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
