<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mourners Remember Former Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) -- Mourners who gathered to pay their  
respects to Ricky Byrdsong on Wednesday evening said the former 
Northwestern coach's reach far exceeded the bounds of the 
basketball floor. 
</P>
<P>
	Family, friends, neighbors and others whose lives were touched  
by Byrdsong filed through the First Presbyterian Church, 
remembering a man who was dedicated to his family, the community 
and the players he coached. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a sadness in Skokie, a sadness in our hearts and a  
sadness in our homes,'' said Marie Lones, a neighbor of Byrdsong in 
the suburb of Skokie where he was gunned down last Friday in front 
of two of his three children. 
</P>
<P>
	Current and former basketball players, coaches and athletic  
directors attended, as well as mourners from as far away as Detroit 
and Arizona, where Byrdsong also coached. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them were Big Ten Commissioner Jim Delany, former Michigan  
coach Steve Fischer and Eastern Kentucky coach Scott Perry, 
godfather of Byrdsong's son, Ricky Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	Arnold Webber, the former Northwestern president who hired  
Byrdsong, recalled the coach enthusiastically discussing his plan 
to work with youths in the community. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of coaches would say that, but Ricky meant it,'' Webber  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Isaiah McKinnon, a professor at the University of Detroit, was  
on the selection committee that hired Byrdsong in 1988. McKinnon 
had the task of informing Byrdsong of his father's death after the 
job interview. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had such dignity and composure at such a terrible time,''  
he said. ``I knew we did the right thing in hiring him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Byrdsong went from Detroit to Northwestern, where he took the  
Wildcats to only their second postseason basketball appearance in 
school history. 
</P>
<P>
	He compiled an 87-165 coaching record, including 34-78 in four  
seasons at Northwestern. He was fired at the end of the 1996-97 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Some mourners were drawn to Wednesday's service by outrage over  
the circumstances of Byrdsong's death. Authorities said the 
ex-coach, who was black, was a victim of a white supremacist who 
went on a shooting rampage last weekend, killing one other person 
and wounding nine. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're here to show our support and to protest the violence in  
our society,'' said Rabbi Ira Youdovin, who identified himself as 
the executive vice president of the Chicago Board of Rabbis. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrdsong, who was 43 at the time of his death and working for an  
insurance company, is survived by his wife, Sherialyn, and three 
children. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 08:20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brief Look At Auto Racing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Jeff Green has a warning for Casey Atwood.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's always next week,'' he said, insisting Atwood took the  
low road in more ways than one to his record-breaking Diehard 250 
victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Atwood, the 18-year-old Tennessee driver, powered under Green  
with a last-lap, hit-and-run move Sunday to become the youngest 
winner in NASCAR Busch Series history. 
</P>
<P>
	``He took a cheap shot,'' Green said. ``That was intentional, to  
do that on the last lap. ... The other top guys don't drive that 
way, but he does. I just hope he can sleep good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Atwood's Chevrolet tapped the left rear of Green's as they  
entered the third turn on The Milwaukee Mile. Green slipped wide 
through the turn, and Atwood went inside to win the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought he was going to try me on the outside and I would've  
given it to him,'' Green said. ``If he could pass me on the 
outside, he deserved it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Put me in the same situation, I probably would've run second.  
I wouldn't turn him around. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can drive just like that toward him next week,'' said Green,  
who will have that chance next in Myrtle Beach, S.C., on July 17. 
``I hope it comes down to us the last lap again. I promise I'll do 
the same thing to him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Atwood downplayed the incident.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's not many last laps when two cars are battling like  
that where contact doesn't happen,'' he said. ``It wasn't anything 
where I was trying to wreck him. I just wanted my first win pretty 
bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FLYING HIGH:* Jimmy Kite is a fast qualifying run away from  
realizing his boyhood dream of racing at Atlanta Motor Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indy Racing League driver, preparing for the Kobalt  
Mechanics Tools 500 on July 17, got his first taste of big-time 
racing 10 years ago, watching a NASCAR race at the track. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ever since that first day, I dreamed about racing there,''  
Kite said. ``We lived just down the road from the track, so it was 
kind of natural that it would become a special place to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He feels like he has the home-field advantage.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'll sleep in my old bed, in my old bedroom, then get up the  
next day and go race at Atlanta Motor Speedway,'' said the 
23-year-old driver. ``How can it get any more cool than that?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kite, in his first season with McCormack Motorsports, missed the  
race last year because Team Scandia skipped the event. 
</P>
<P>
	``My emotions were probably a lot like someone who has missed  
the Indianapolis 500, because to me the Atlanta race was the most 
important event on the schedule,'' Kite said. ``Knowing I was so 
close, but so far away, I just couldn't stand it.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ONCE A RACER:* Ask a Winston Cup driver about the baseball  
All-Star game, and the answer comes right out of the third turn. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm picking the American League . . . unless they invert the  
field after the fifth inning,'' John Andretti said when pressed for 
a prediction on the game Tuesday night in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	The field is inverted -- with heat winners sent toward the rear --  
in The Winston, NASCAR's annual no-holds-barred all-star event. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd say anything that's even close to similar ends right after  
the National Anthem,'' Sterling Marlin said. ``Now, if those boys 
were beating each other with baseball bats, then they'd be closer 
to what our bodies feel like after running The Winston.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *OIL CHANGE:* Valvoline is ending its sponsorship deal with  
Derrick Walker Racing, which fields the CART entry of Gil de 
Ferran. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had a winning partnership with Valvoline since 1992,''  
Walker said. ``Unfortunately, Valvoline's business plans don't 
include primary team sponsorship in CART in 2000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	De Ferran, a winner June 20 in Portland, Ore., is second in the  
FedEx Championship points race. 
</P>
<P>
	Valvoline also sponsors Roush Racing's Mark Martin-driven NASCAR  
Winston Cup entry. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CURIOUS GEORGE:* Tony George, the Indianapolis Motor Speedway  
president and Indy Racing League founder, is taking the wheel this 
weekend in the Summer Sizzle '99 USAC midget competition. 
</P>
<P>
	George will join his son, USAC regular Eddie Carpenter, in the  
$140,000 event at 16th Street Speedway in Indianapolis. And he 
won't be out there just to collect dirt. George won a 1997 Legends 
feature on the quarter-mile oval. 
</P>
<P>
	 *End Adv Thursday, July 8    	
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
