<DOCNO> APW19990707.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 13:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Italian Wins Tour de France Stage 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLOIS, France (AP) -- In the town where Joan of Arc plotted her  
attack on the English at Orleans, Mario Cipollini of Italy won the 
fastest stage in the history of the Tour de France today. 
</P>
<P>
	Coming off a stone bridge spanning the Loire River, the Italian  
surged past Germany's Erik Zabel in a photo finish to win the 
fourth stage of cycling's showcase race. 
</P>
<P>
	A favorable tailwind, cool weather, a relatively straight course  
and wide, flat roads all contributed to the record average speed of 
31.290 mph, breaking the 1993 mark of 30.707 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia's Stuart O'Grady finished third, followed by Tom  
Steels, the Belgian who won the two previous stages. Estonia's Jaan 
Kirsipuu was fifth but kept the leader's yellow jersey he captured 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 121-mile route took the riders through flat roads from the  
town of Laval on the Mayenne River to Blois in the Loire Valley, 
home to a castle of French kings. The castle is also where Joan of 
Arc prepared for her siege of Orleans in 1429. 
</P>
<P>
	As in Tuesday's third stage, two riders broke from the pack  
early and held a long lead. Gianpaolo Mondini of Italy and Anthony 
Morin of France survived an early breakaway by 10 riders. They 
built a lead of more than six minutes over 62 miles before the pack 
started gaining late in the race. 
</P>
<P>
	The final sprint went down to a photo finish, and Zabel was  
deprived of a stage win on his 29th birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the overall standings, O'Grady moved up to second place, 16  
seconds behind. Steels, who wants to be wearing the yellow jersey 
when the race nears his home country later in the week, was third 
at 21 seconds behind. 
</P>
<P>
	In fourth place was Lance Armstrong, the American making a  
gallant comeback from testicular cancer, 24 seconds behind. Zabel 
was in fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong plans to wait for Sunday's time trial and then the  
mountain stages before making his real challenge. But this week, in 
the early, flat stages, it is the sprinters like Cipollini who are 
in command. 
</P>
<P>
	In winning in 3 hours, 51 minutes, 45 seconds, the 32-year-old  
Italian captured his ninth career Tour de France stage victory, and 
his first this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was the perfect sprint,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	He paid tribute to his teammates on the Saeco team, such as Gian  
Matteo Fagnini and Mario Scirea, who worked mightily to get him 
into proper position for the final sprint. 
</P>
<P>
	Cipollini is ninth in the overall standings, 44 seconds behind  
Kirsipuu. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, this year's Tour has had little of the controversy that  
enveloped last year's race when a drug scandal almost scuttled the 
entire event. 
</P>
<P>
	Manolo Saiz, sports director of the ONCE team, who was initially  
banned from this year's Tour for involvement in the drug scandal 
but then was reinstated, said in Le Monde on Wednesday that he 
thought that ``90, if not 99, percent of the riders in this year's 
Tour de France are clean.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 14:40:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Excess Military Property Probed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nearly $2.7 billion in excess military  
property, including sensitive weapons parts, cannot be accounted 
for after being marked for disposal or sale, according to records 
examined by congressional investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon says the problem is more clerical than criminal,  
though it acknowledges having no record of final disposal for about 
13 percent of military surplus property in fiscal 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The General Accounting Office report cites only one incident  
where military personnel determined a likely theft -- the 
disappearance of a $424 camera lens. Most of the disappearances 
apparently were due to faulty record-keeping, problems with data 
entry into computers or other clerical failures, the GAO concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	About half the property listed as not received by disposal  
offices was items which should have received special military 
handling - such as communications equipment, aircraft components 
and gun parts, the GAO report said in reporting on its examination 
of in-transit records. 
</P>
<P>
	The report was the third in a series of congressional inquiries  
into problems with disposal of surplus military equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	A report last year found that some of the $22 billion worth of  
equipment sold in fiscal 1997 may have caused the leaking of 
sensitive military technology to U.S. and foreign buyers. A year 
earlier, a GAO report found billions of dollars worth of property 
being destroyed that might have been sold for civilian use without 
compromising security or flight safety concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Pentagon efforts to reform its complex system for  
disposing of surplus property, problems persist, the new report 
concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	``Management controls over excess property being shipped to  
disposal are not working effectively, leaving the property 
vulnerable to loss or undetected theft,'' said the report sent to 
Rep. Floyd Spence, chairman of the House Armed Services Committee. 
Copies also went to Defense Secretary William Cohen and to heads of 
the armed service branches. 
</P>
<P>
	The report included a response from Deputy Under Secretary of  
Defense Roger W. Kallock, who said the department concurs with its 
conclusions and is addressing its recommendations for closer 
control of excess military equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon ``believes the property is not being lost and that  
most record discrepancies are due to administrative errors,'' the 
report notes, but it adds that the administrative problems are 
``systemic and widespread.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In one instance, GAO investigators examined 191 sample shipments  
of sensitive military property which were sent for disposal but 
recorded as not received by disposal offices. They were able to 
determine final status of only 114 of the shipments, which were 
received but not recorded because of a backlog. 
</P>
<P>
	They found no trace of the remaining 77 shipments which included  
a wiring assembly used in encrypted electronic communications, 
optical magnifying devices for 25-millimeter guns and components 
for the Bradley fighting vehicle and other weapons systems, the GAO 
report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Each military service is responsible for determining its own  
excess property, which may include unusable parts of weapons 
systems or machinery and such saleable items as photographic 
supplies, hand tools, shop equipment, and clothing. The Defense 
Logistics Agency carries out disposal, which may include transfer 
to other federal agencies, donation to state or local governments 
or sale to the general public. 
</P>
<P>
	Disposal of whole weapons, small firearms, ammunition,  
explosives, classified material and drugs is handled directly by 
the military services and was not covered in the latest report. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 13:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
