<HEADLINE> Firefighters Contain Western Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EUREKA, Utah (AP) -- The largest fire burning in the West, a  
61,400-acre blaze feeding on pinyon pine, juniper and cheat grass 
in central Utah, is contained and expected to be declared 
controlled by late today. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire twice drove residents of Eureka and Mammoth from their  
homes over the weekend, but no one was injured and only three 
abandoned shacks burned. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 420 firefighters had been working on the fire and they  
were expected to be released beginning today, said fire information 
officer Jerry Rohnert. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, a 9,000-acre fire near Genola, 52 miles south of Salt  
Lake City, was 90 percent contained and control was projected for 
late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Near Hesperia, Calif., a blaze in the San Bernardino National  
Forest forced about 70 people to evacuate their homes but they were 
allowed to return late Tuesday. The fire was 80 percent contained 
today after burning through 2,800 acres of brush, said Bill Peters 
of the California Department of Forestry. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire near Interstate 15, southeast of Los Angeles, had  
destroyed sheds, trailers, vehicles and a mobile home, said 
national forest spokeswoman Karen McKinley. 
</P>
<P>
	In Colorado, lighter wind and a little rain helped crews  
complete containment lines around 50 percent of a blaze west of 
Grand Junction. The fire had spread through more than 5,000 acres 
of sage, pinyon pine and juniper. 
</P>
<P>
	No towns or homes were threatened, officials said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
