<HEADLINE> U.S. Women's Soccer League Eyed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A study into the feasibility of starting a  
women's professional soccer league in the United States is being 
developed by U.S. Soccer. 
</P>
<P>
	Federation president S. Robert Contiguglia said Wednesday that a  
business plan is in the works to put together a league. There is no 
top-level professional soccer outlet for American women at home, 
and few leagues around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``U.S. Soccer has been at the forefront of women's athletics for  
many years,'' Contiguglia said. ``We have implemented a number of 
progressive women's programs to ensure the continued success of 
women's soccer, and we are moving into this project with the same 
mindset ... to try and produce the best possible plan to entice 
investors. 
</P>
<P>
	``As the governing body of the sport, U.S. Soccer's role is to  
encourage dialogue and the eventual development of a business plan 
for potential investors, but not to directly fund or operate a 
league.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Funds have been committed by John Hendricks, founder of the  
Discovery Channel, to develop the business plan and present it to 
potential investors by early 2000. Mark Abbott, the chief operating 
officer of Major League Soccer, is drafting the plan. He played a 
similar role for MLS. 
</P>
<P>
	Federation officials have discussed the plan's development with  
members of the U.S. women's team, other participants in the World 
Cup and sponsors in the women's soccer community. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are many elements that need to be in place before you  
can proceed with a start-up project like this,'' Contiguglia said. 
``It's important to remember that this is just the first step in 
the process.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
