<HEADLINE> Disney, Katzenberg Settle Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BURBANK, Calif. (AP) -- Not with a bang but a squeak, the Walt  
Disney Co. and Jeffrey Katzenberg quietly settled their messy, 
high-profile Hollywood divorce for an undisclosed amount, both 
sides revealed Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement of the contract dispute was reached Tuesday  
afternoon, as Katzenberg was calling his final witnesses and Disney 
was about to begin its case in the trial before a retired state 
judge, sitting as a mediator. It returned the dispute to where it 
began: behind closed doors, at the highest level of movie business 
dealmaking, away from the eyes of curious movie fans and nervous 
shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, which still must be approved by a Superior  
Court judge, neither side would comment on the details. At trial, 
Katzenberg had said he was owed a bonus worth as much as $580 
million as a going-away perk when he left as studio boss in 1994; 
Disney put the figure as low as $119 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Katzenberg has reportedly already received $117 million in a  
partial settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Exactly why they settled when they did wasn't known, but the  
trial was headed toward a particularly delicate point for Disney. 
The company, which has been battered on Wall Street, was about to 
put on evidence suggesting the future value of some of its most 
prized properties, from ``The Lion King'' to ``Sister Act,'' wasn't 
as bright as Katzenberg was suggesting. 
</P>
<P>
	What's more, Disney Chairman Michael Eisner was scheduled to  
make a return trip to the witness stand Monday, as a hostile 
witness for Katzenberg. In an embarrassing courtroom performance in 
May, Eisner conceded he may have said of the diminutive Katzenberg: 
``I hate the little midget.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast to the bitterness of the trial, the settlement was  
announced in a joint statement on Disney's Mickey Mouse letterhead, 
in which both sides praised their lawyers and expressed 
satisfaction with the outcome. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am glad that we were able to come to an acceptable  
settlement,'' Eisner said, adding, ``the time has come to put this 
matter behind us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Katzenberg praised his legal team and said, ``I am very pleased  
that we were able to finally resolve this matter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Katzenberg, who left Disney in 1994 after he was denied a  
promotion, filed suit claiming the company owed him a 2 percent 
bonus against future profits of all films and merchandise produced 
during his 10-year tenure as head of the animation and live-action 
studios. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney had argued Katzenberg forfeited that bonus because he  
left two years before the end of his six-year contract. Katzenberg 
went on to become one of the founders of DreamWorks with Steven 
Spielberg and David Geffen and now oversees its animation division, 
a Disney competitor, which last year released ``The Prince of 
Egypt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the partial settlement, Disney acknowledged it did owe  
Katzenberg something, though the exact amount and the particular 
products that fell under the bonus were to be worked out in 
mediation. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney also agreed in the partial settlement, according to  
sources, to give Katzenberg two sums: $77.5 million and $40 
million. The $77.5 million amount was to be deducted from the final 
bonus figure determined in the second phase; the $40 million was to 
be untouched. 
</P>
<P>
	Midway into the second phase of mediation, retired Superior  
Court Judge Paul Breckenridge ruled May 19 that Disney did breach 
its contract, a technical but important legal finding because it 
meant the company owed Katzenberg a potentially huge interest 
payment in addition to the bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit has proven to be not only expensive for Disney, but  
a major embarrassment, as the bad blood between Eisner and 
Katzenberg became painfully public. Observers have long wondered 
why a deal wasn't reached much sooner. 
</P>
<P>
	Eisner's testimony in May turned out to be a public relations  
disaster for Disney. Proving a prickly witness, Eisner was forced 
to acknowledge that he probably once made the now infamous 
``midget'' crack about Katzenberg in discussions with the co-author 
of Eisner's autobiography. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
