<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pa. Torture-Killer Executed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELLEFONTE, Pa. (AP) -- A man condemned for kidnapping and  
torturing six women, including a retarded woman whose body parts he 
fed to his other shackled victims, was executed by injection. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Heidnik, 55, was a disabled Army veteran who made a fortune  
in the stock market and ordained himself bishop of his own church. 
He abducted, imprisoned and raped six women in the basement of his 
Philadelphia home in 1986 and 1987; two of them died. He was put to 
death at Rockview state prison Tuesday as four sisters of victims 
looked on. 
</P>
<P>
	``He should have got the same thing that he dished out to a lot  
of people's families,'' said Carolyn Johnson, whose sister, Deborah 
Johnson Dudley, died when Heidnik touched live electric wires to 
her chains as she stood in a water-filled pit. 
</P>
<P>
	Sandra Lindsay, the retarded victim, died while shackled by her  
arm to a rafter. The women who survived Heidnik's torture said he 
dismembered her body, ground up the flesh with dog food and fed it 
to the others. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt that he was a coward then and he's a coward now,'' said  
Lindsay's sister, Tracey Lomax. 
</P>
<P>
	He was the first prisoner to be put to death in Pennsylvania  
since 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers representing Heidnik's daughter pressed appeals in  
federal court until the end, contending that it was illegal to 
execute him because he was not mentally competent. The courts 
refused to block the execution. 
</P>
<P>
	``The state has executed an extremely mentally ill and psychotic  
man,'' defense attorney Kathy Swedlow said. 
</P>
<P>
	Heidnik himself had declined to pursue any appeals since he was  
sentenced in 1988. He believed he was innocent and that his 
execution would draw protests leading to the end of capital 
punishment. But only a couple of protesters showed up. 
</P>
<P>
	Heidnik was found out when Josefina Rivera, a prostitute,  
escaped. He picked her up in 1986 and after they had sex, choked 
her until she passed out. When she came to, she was in handcuffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the next four months, Rivera watched as the other five  
women arrived and were tortured. Three were prostitutes. Heidnik 
was white; all his victims were black. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Gov. Tom Ridge, who was swept into office in 1995  
partly on a pledge to speed up the signing of death warrants that 
had languished under his Democratic predecessor, Robert Casey, said 
Heidnik's punishment was just. 
</P>
<P>
	``So horrible were his deeds, a jury of 12 Pennsylvanians  
determined unanimously that he must forfeit his life,'' Ridge said 
in a statement. ``Tonight he paid that price. In doing so, he 
suffered far less than the women he tortured and killed.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
