<HEADLINE> Dell To Advise George W. Bush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Republican presidential frontrunner George  
W. Bush today named Michael Dell, chairman of Dell Computer Corp., 
the nation's largest direct seller of computers, to chair his 
advisory council on high technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Other advisers on the nine-member panel include Tom Engibous,  
president of Texas Instruments Inc., and Robert Herbold, executive 
vice president of Microsoft Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas governor has called for freeing Internet sales from  
duties and tariffs, creating a permanent federal research and 
development tax credit, and pledged not to raise federal personal 
or corporate taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has proposed intensifying efforts to combat intellectual  
piracy and called for lifting the cap on the number of high-skilled 
workers allowed into the country under so-called H-1B visas. 
</P>
<P>
	Also named to the advisory council were James Barksdale,  
managing partner at The Barksdale Group; Carol Bartz, chief 
executive officer of Autodesk Inc.; John Chambers, president and 
CEO of Cisco Systems; Richard Egan, founder of EMC Corp.; Ray Lane, 
president of Oracle; and Steve Papermaster, head of Agillon. 

  	   	
