<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fungus Hurting Soybean Plants / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	URBANA, Ill. (AP) -- Glen Hartman opens what looks like a giant  
refrigerator and pulls out a tray of soybean plants sprouting under 
fluorescent lights in white tubes. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the plants look healthy and strong; others are droopy  
with yellow and brown leaves. 
</P>
<P>
	That's just the way Hartman wants it.  
</P>
<P>
	The plant pathologist is combing through soybean collections at  
the University of Illinois, trying to find plants that are 
naturally resistant to two diseases that have hit Illinois farmers 
hard in recent years -- sudden death syndrome and white mold. 
</P>
<P>
	Sudden death syndrome is caused by a fungus that lives in the  
soil and affects the plant's roots. It causes the leaves to yellow 
and pods to fall off prematurely. 
</P>
<P>
	White mold, also known as sclerotinia stem rot, is also caused  
by a fungus, but it affects the plant during flowering and grows 
into the stem. Anything above the affected part of the stem dies. 
</P>
<P>
	Both were virtually unheard of in Illinois 10 years ago. But  
sudden death syndrome was observed in 90 percent of the counties in 
the state in 1998. Both diseases can severely hurt yields. 
</P>
<P>
	Hartman, who is with the U.S. Agriculture Department Research  
Service unit at the UI, is screening three collections. 
</P>
<P>
	The first is of soybean genetic material from around the world  
gathered at the USDA's Soybean Germplasm Collection, housed at the 
university. These soybeans are similar to what was domesticated in 
China thousands of years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	He's also testing wild annual progenitors of today's  
domesticated soybeans and a group of wild perennial relatives of 
the soybean that were collected by UI geneticist Ted Hymowitz on 
trips over the past 25 years to secluded spots in Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Hartman has found some promising results, especially in the wild  
perennials -- although crosses between soybeans and their perennial 
relatives are long and difficult, meaning it could be five years or 
more before farmers can buy resistant varieties. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	TIFTON, Ga. (AP) -- A federal agricultural official says U.S.  
farmers are lagging in making the switch to conservation tillage, a 
type of farming that cuts growers' costs, reduces erosion and 
enhances the environment. 
</P>
<P>
	David Schertz, head agronomist for the National Resources  
Conservation Service, urged about 80 scientists and others 
attending the 22nd Annual Conservation Tillage Conference on 
Wednesday to do a better job of persuading farmers to make the 
switch. 
</P>
<P>
	Schertz noted that conservation tillage was used on 25 percent  
of the nation's planted acres in 1989. That jumped to 35 percent in 
1993, but it grew only slightly from 1993 to 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	With conservation tillage, farmers use winter cover crops such  
as clover to enrich the soil. They minimize plowing to reduce 
erosion and cut labor and fuel costs. And they leave at least 30 
percent of the residue from the previous crop on the ground to 
increase soil moisture, reduce runoff and add organic matter. 
Conservation tillage is sometimes referred to as ``no till'' 
farming. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
