<DOCNO> APW19990707.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 06:10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Longshoremen Shut Oakland Docks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- A work stoppage has halted most activity  
at the port of Oakland and caught management officials off-guard. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's action apparently originated with Local 10 of the  
International Longshore Workers Union in San Francisco. The port 
here includes 12 cargo terminals serving 33 shipping lines. 
</P>
<P>
	Should the stoppage spread to other West Coast ports, it could  
idle thousands of workers who help ship and process cargo at inland 
warehouses and cost the nation billions of dollars in lost 
commerce, association officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``None of our customers are able to conduct business,'' said  
Port of Oakland spokeswoman Roberta Bradley. ``I understand it 
stemmed from local issues but may affect national negotiations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Management officials said they haven't heard from union  
officials since a meeting last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at Pacific Maritime Association, which represents  
management at all West Coast ports in the talks, made their offer 
on Saturday, just before negotiations ended for the Fourth of July 
holiday, with an understanding they would resume this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't heard from the union,'' said Phil Resch, the  
association's senior vice president. ``We have called all day today 
to talk to the international and they have not returned our 
calls.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Union officials, whose members have been working without a  
contract since Thursday, did not return calls seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	A recorded message at the union's office in San Francisco tells  
workers the ``negotiating committee has decided to continue to meet 
with the employers hour-to-hour as long as progress is being made 
on our remaining demands ... The rank-and-file should continue to 
work unless directed otherwise by the negotiating committee.'' The 
message is dated last Friday, prior to the company's latest offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Work stopped in Oakland when employees arriving for the 7 a.m.  
shift Tuesday demanded that an additional person, known as a 
signalman, be added to crews. The signalman's job is to ensure 
safety by helping crane operators keep track of cargo container 
movements on the dock. 
</P>
<P>
	Each crew already had one or two signalmen assigned, and the  
workers were told their request was illegal, but the crews still 
refused to work, Resch said. About 1,000 longshore workers and 
clerks remained off the job. 
</P>
<P>
	The workers had been scheduled to unload five ships, which  
remained at the docks Tuesday evening. 
</P>
<P>
	In Los Angeles and Long Beach, the nation's busiest ports, there  
were minor slowdowns at some terminals, but work was not seriously 
affected. There was no report of slowdowns in San Diego or Seattle, 
Resch said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Port of Los Angeles, a few terminal operators reported  
that work was slow, but union workers still handled a large volume 
of cargo, said spokeswoman Barbara Yamamoto. Long Beach officials 
did not return a call placed after business hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were hearing it was just sporadic. It was pretty much  
business as usual,'' said Yamamoto. ``There weren't any reports of 
ships not being worked.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The association and union leaders have been negotiating behind  
closed doors since May to work out a contract that would affect 
about 14,700 union members on the West Coast. The current contract 
expired on Thursday, but both sides agreed to continue talking. 
</P>
<P>
	The association's offer included a 32 percent boost in pension  
benefits to current future retirees and a 15 percent raise for 
those currently retired. Officials would not describe the 
association's pay offer. Association President Joseph Miniace 
Miniace said it would make West Coast workers ``among the highest 
compensated union workers in America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pay in 1998 averaged $99,000 for workers, $117,617 for clerks  
and $156,251 for foremen, according to the association. 
</P>
<P>
	The use of safety concerns to stop work also has been an issue  
in the talks. The current contract allows union members to stop 
work whenever they perceive a safety problem. The association has 
sought to eliminate that option, arguing that the union 
rank-and-file has used it to stage unauthorized work stoppages and 
slowdowns. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
