<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 12:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Opryland Hotel Lays Off 160 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Opryland Hotel is laying off 160 of its  
4,600 employees, Gaylord Entertainment Co. announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said the layoffs were done to redirect savings into  
new, undisclosed opportunities and expand existing businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Those laid off include both managerial and hourly employees in  
several departments. 
</P>
<P>
	On the news, shares of Gaylord dropped 87 1/2 cents, or 3 percent,  
to $28.87 1/2 in afternoon trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our hotel occupancy, which consistently outstrips the  
hospitality industry, continues ahead of last year's pace, and our 
service level will remain high,'' said Dave Jones, president and 
chief executive officer of the Opryland Hospitality Group, part of 
Nashville-based Gaylord. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2,884-room hotel relies heavily on conventions, which  
represent 80 percent of its business. 
</P>
<P>
	Gaylord also owns the Grand Ole Opry country music show near the  
hotel. It formerly owned the Opryland USA theme park, which closed 
after the 1997 season because of declining attendance. Gaylord is a 
minority owner of the Nashville Predators of the National Hockey 
League. 
</P>
<P>
	Gaylord broke ground last week on a 1,400-room Opryland Hotel in  
Orlando, Fla., which is to open in 2002. The company expects to 
break ground next year on a 1,500-room hotel in Grapevine, Texas, 
which is scheduled to open in 2003. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
