<DOCNO> APW19990707.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 14:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Fla. Jury Finds Tobacco Cos. Liable  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The jury in the nation's first class-action lawsuit  
by smokers ever to go to trial found that cigarette makers produced 
a defective product that causes emphysema, lung cancer and other 
illnesses in a ruling that could expose the industry to billions of 
dollars in damages. The verdict today affects as many as half a 
million Florida smokers and the heirs of those who died. The jury's 
decision could prove to be the industry's most dire courtroom loss 
yet, since the plaintiffs are seeking at least $200 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Closes at New High of 11,187.36  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks bobbed and weaved into record territory  
today as the second-quarter earnings report season injected 
uncertainty into the market. The Dow Jones industrial average 
closed up 52.24 at 11,187.36, a new high. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 
and Nasdaq composite index also set records. Declining issues on 
the New York Stock Exchange led advancers 1,693-1,279. The Nasdaq 
was up 6.31 to 2,743.09. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Focuses on American Indians  
</P>
<P>
	PINE RIDGE, S.D. (AP) -- President Clinton today declared that  
the United States can no longer afford to ignore poverty and 
unemployment among American Indians. Visiting Oglala Sioux on the 
Pine Ridge Reservation, Clinton seemed almost disbelieving as 
Geraldine Blue Bird explained her living situation in a house and a 
nearby trailer. Tribal President Howard Salway said Blue Bird's 
Igloo neighborhood -- a collection of foam-green shacks with 
crumbling porches -- is typical of housing conditions on the 
reservation. 

</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton Plunges Into N.Y. Race  
</P>
<P>
	WEST DAVENPORT, N.Y. (AP) -- Plunging into her race for the  
Senate, Hillary Rodham Clinton brushed aside criticism today that 
she is a carpetbagger in New York. ``What I am for is maybe as 
important, if not more important, than where I am from,'' the first 
lady said. Mrs. Clinton said New Yorkers had some ``very legitimate 
questions'' about what she believes in and the skills and interests 
that she would bring to the job. And she said she would address 
them. 

</P>
<P>
	House Republicans Propose Tax Cuts  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With stock ownership at an all-time high,  
House Republicans proposed today to cut the top tax rate on capital 
gains from 20 percent to 15 percent. The White House immediately 
criticized the idea as a favor for wealthy investors, but GOP 
leaders point to recent research estimating that 84 million people 
now own stock or participate in mutual funds -- an increase of 170 
percent from 1970. For people who pay income taxes in the 15 
percent rate, the capital-gains tax would drop from 10 percent to 
7.5 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Online Bookstore Now Selling Music  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In a race to keep pace with online rival  
Amazon.com, Barnesandnoble.com launched a music superstore today, 
including thousands of titles from artists ranging from pop 
sensation Ricky Martin to jazz legend Duke Ellington. The music 
store will be part of barnesandnoble.com's newly redesigned 
bookselling Web site, which was also launched today. In the new 
music store, shoppers can choose from all types of music, including 
some harder to find categories, such as retro swing or Brazilian 
jazz. 

</P>
<P>
	Peace Accord Signed in Sierra Leone  
</P>
<P>
	LOME, Togo (AP) -- Sierra Leone's president signed a peace accord  
today with rebels to end an eight-year civil war that has killed 
tens of thousands in the West African nation. The agreement, the 
second in three years, granted amnesty for war criminals and a 
power-sharing role for the insurgents in the elected government of 
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah. Kabbah and rebel Revolutionary United 
Front leader Foday Sankoh signed the deal in a public ceremony in 
Togo's capital of Lome following an overnight summit of regional 
leaders. 

</P>
<P>
	All-Star Reserves Selected  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Two days after the fans snubbed the World Series  
champion Yankees in the All-Star balloting, New York manager Joe 
Torre picked four of his own players to bring to Boston next week. 
Derek Jeter, Bernie Williams, David Cone and Mariano Rivera were 
picked today. NL manager Bruce Bochy and president Len Coleman 
selected 16 first-time All-Stars in their pitchers and reserves, 
leaving out usual stars Barry Bonds of San Francisco and Atlanta 
pitchers John Smoltz, Tom Glavine and Greg Maddux. 

</P>
<P>
	Cavaliers Hire Wittman As New Coach  
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- The Cleveland Cavaliers ended their search for  
a coach today by hiring Randy Wittman, a longtime Minnesota 
Timberwolves assistant with no head coaching experience. Wittman, a 
member of Indiana's 1981 NCAA championship team and a journeyman in 
his NBA playing days, replaced Mike Fratello, who was fired on June 
1. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
