<DOCNO> APW19990707.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 21:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Toyota To Shed Seniority Pay System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Looking to boost its bottom line, Toyota Motor  
Corp. is breaking from Japanese corporate tradition by scrapping 
its seniority-based wage system in favor of one base on 
performance. 
</P>
<P>
	The change, expected to be implemented in October, is intended  
to encourage employees to work harder by rewarding them for their 
achievements, Toyota spokesman Tomomi Imai said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think this will improve our company's performance,'' Imai  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota, like most large Japanese companies, has traditionally  
given management-track workers automatic pay raises as they got 
older. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers will still receive these regular pay raises under the  
new system. The amount they get, however, will be based on 
performance instead of age, Imai said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company will ask its labor union to agree to the new payment  
plan in August, and once in place, about 20,000 of Toyota's 70,000 
employees in Japan will be affected, Imai said. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that the new system will only affect lower-level  
managers. Top Toyota executives are already paid on a merit-based 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	The automaker's announcement comes as Japanese companies across  
the board are scrambling for ways to increase productivity and 
innovation through new management styles and drastic labor cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent months, corporate giants like Mitsubishi Electric  
Corp. and Sony Corp. have announced plans to slim operations and 
cut thousands of workers -- straying from Japan's long tradition of 
lifetime employment. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, many electronics and computer companies have  
adopted performance-based pay scales to spur creative thinking 
among engineers. 
</P>
<P>
	Even major appliance-maker Hitachi, long criticized as  
inflexible, has slashed its work force and adopted a casual dress 
policy -- something company officials say is to emphasize ``respect 
for the individual.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota is the first of Japan's automakers to completely abolish  
its seniority-based wage system. Many, however, say it may not be 
the last. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've seen all kinds of companies adopting this kind of  
policy,'' said Satoko Hiwatari, who studies labor trends for 
Nikkeiren, an influential business group. ``Everything is pointing 
in this direction.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 17:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paroled Suspect Arrested in Calif. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A prison parolee accused of stabbing two  
teen-age girls and leaving them for dead was arrested Wednesday 
after passersby spotted him lying on a city plaza bench and 
recognized his tattoo. 
</P>
<P>
	Donald Paul Gatson, 22, was the subject of an intense police  
manhunt after the attack Monday, two days after he was released 
from San Quentin prison. The girls were each stabbed more than 15 
times and left in a ditch to die. 
</P>
<P>
	Both were in critical condition on Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	Passersby at the Nations Plaza spotted Gatson on Wednesday  
afternoon because of his tattoo, a star on the back of his shaved 
head, said San Francisco police spokesman Sherman Ackerson. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it wasn't for the citizens coming forward and calling  
police, he wouldn't be in custody,'' Ackerson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gatson was paroled Saturday after serving time for possession of  
stolen property. He has also been convicted of grand theft, lying 
to a police officer and being under the influence of 
methamphetamine. 
</P>
<P>
	The victims were an 18-year-old girl from Fremont and a  
15-year-old girl from Reno, Nev., who had been visiting relatives. 
Their identities were not released. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said Gatson and an 18-year-old accomplice later arrested  
met the teen-agers near a high school. The girls were threatened 
with knives and a gun and forced to withdraw about $200 from an 
automated teller machine. 
</P>
<P>
	The group then drove to Palomares Canyon, about 30 miles  
southeast of San Francisco, police said. There, each woman was 
stabbed and the younger victim was shot in the face with a large 
caliber handgun. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 15:23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Moroccan Sets New Mile Run Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Hicham El Guerrouj smashed the world record in the  
mile with a time of 3 minutes, 43.13 seconds at the Golden Gala 
meet Wednesday, fighting off Kenya's Noah Ngeny, who also beat the 
old mark. 
</P>
<P>
	In becoming the first Moroccan to hold one of track and field's  
most hallowed records, El Guerrouj shaved 1.26 seconds off the mark 
of 3:44.39 set by Noureddine Morceli of Algeria on Sept. 5, 1993, 
at Rieti, Italy. Ngeny was timed in 3:43.40. 
</P>
<P>
	This was only the third time in 18 years the record was broken.  
</P>
<P>
	It was the second straight year that El Guerrouj set a world  
record at the Golden Gala meet, and each time he erased a mark held 
by Morceli. Last year, he cracked the 1,500-meter record with 
3:26.00. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rome is a magic track for me,'' El Guerrouj said. ``I can't  
compare this year with last year. It's another El Guerrouj. I was 
more concentrated, but the public was the same.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fans supported El Guerrouj, shouting and applauding noisily  
as he rushed to the record. 
</P>
<P>
	El Guerrouj ran a victory lap, waving a Moroccan flag to the  
cheering fans. He dedicated the race to his family and to King 
Hassan of Morocco. 
</P>
<P>
	``I needed to bring some happiness to my family, as my uncle  
died recently,'' he said. ``I hope God continues to give me 
strength because I want to be the strongest in the world at all 
distances between 1,500 and 5,000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After Britain's Sebastian Coe reduced the record to 3:47.33 in  
1981, the mark stood until 1985, when another Briton, Steve Cram, 
lowered it to 3:46.32. Cram's time held for eight years until 
Morceli clipped nearly two seconds off it. 
</P>
<P>
	El Guerrouj, 24, has been almost unbeatable the past four years.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, he won 12 of 13 races at a mile or 1,500 meters, losing  
only in the Olympic 1,500 final when he fell just before the bell 
lap and Morceli went on to win the gold medal. Later that season, 
he ended Morceli's four-year winning streak at 1,500 meters, 
winning the IAAF Grand Prix final. 
</P>
<P>
	El Guerrouj won 14 of 15 races in 1997, losing only at one mile  
in the Grand Prix final. Last year, he won all 12 races, including 
one at 2,000 meters, and just missed world records at the mile with 
3:44.60 and 2,000 meters with 4:48.36. He is undefeated this year. 
</P>
<P>
	El Guerrouj won the 1997 world outdoor 1,500 championship and  
the 1995 and 1997 world indoor 1,500 titles. 
</P>
<P>
	He made his first breakthrough in 1994, running 3:33.61 for  
1,500 meters at Nice, France, with little form in this event, even 
though he had taken the bronze medal for 5,000 meters at the 1992 
World Junior Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Marion Jones extended her four-year unbeaten streak  
in the women's 200 meters, world record-holder Maurice Greene set a 
meet record in the men's 100 and Michael Johnson beat a powerful 
field in the men's 200. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, undefeated in the 100, 200 and 400 this year, easily won  
the 200 in 22.18. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene, the 1997 world champion, won in 9.85, only .06 seconds  
off the world record of 9.79 he set last month. He beat Dennis 
Mitchell and Bruny Surin. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, recently bothered by a quadriceps injury and competing  
in his first 200 in six weeks, beat Obadele Thompson of Barbados 
and Ato Boldon of Trinidad &AMP; Tobago, in 19.93. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a bitter defeat for Boldon, who ran a season best of  
19.86 at Athens last month and had been faster than Johnson this 
season. Boldon was timed in 20.14, behind Thompson's 20.12. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson missed both the USA Championships and the opening Golden  
League meet because of injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Other winners included Allen Johnson in the men's 110-meter  
hurdles, Kenyan-born Wilson Kipketer of Denmark in the men's 800, 
Gabriela Szabo of Romania in the women's 3,000, and Bernard 
Barmasai of Kenya in the men's 3,000-meter steeplechase. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen Johnson, the Olympic and two-time world champion, beat  
American teammates Mark Crear and Larry Wade in 13.01, the season's 
second-fastest time. 
</P>
<P>
	Kipketer, the 1997 world champion, set a season best of 1:42.79.  
He sprinted to victory in the final 200 meters at Olympic Stadium 
on a hot night. 
</P>
<P>
	Kipketer, Johnson and Jones also had won their races in the  
opening meet of the seven-meet Golden League series at Oslo last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	The 100-meter race does not count for the Golden League series.  
</P>
<P>
	Last year, El Guerrouj, Jones and Ethiopian distance runner  
Haile Gebrselassie shared the $1 million Golden League jackpot. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
