<P>
	Greene, the 1997 world champion, won in 9.85, only .06 seconds  
off the world record of 9.79 he set last month. He beat Dennis 
Mitchell and Bruny Surin. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, recently bothered by a quadriceps injury and competing  
in his first 200 in six weeks, beat Obadele Thompson of Barbados 
and Ato Boldon of Trinidad &AMP; Tobago, in 19.93. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a bitter defeat for Boldon, who ran a season best of  
19.86 at Athens last month and had been faster than Johnson this 
season. Boldon was timed in 20.14, behind Thompson's 20.12. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson missed both the USA Championships and the opening Golden  
League meet because of injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Other winners included Allen Johnson in the men's 110-meter  
hurdles, Kenyan-born Wilson Kipketer of Denmark in the men's 800, 
Gabriela Szabo of Romania in the women's 3,000, and Bernard 
Barmasai of Kenya in the men's 3,000-meter steeplechase. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen Johnson, the Olympic and two-time world champion, beat  
American teammates Mark Crear and Larry Wade in 13.01, the season's 
second-fastest time. 
</P>
<P>
	Kipketer, the 1997 world champion, set a season best of 1:42.79.  
He sprinted to victory in the final 200 meters at Olympic Stadium 
on a hot night. 
</P>
<P>
	Kipketer, Johnson and Jones also had won their races in the  
opening meet of the seven-meet Golden League series at Oslo last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	The 100-meter race does not count for the Golden League series.  
</P>
<P>
	Last year, El Guerrouj, Jones and Ethiopian distance runner  
Haile Gebrselassie shared the $1 million Golden League jackpot. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 21:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Some Nuke Plants Still Need Y2K Work  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A third of the nation's atomic power plants  
still have additional work to complete on non-safety computer 
systems to be fully ready handle the Y2K computer bug, the Nuclear 
Regulatory Commission says. Sixty-eight plants indicated that all 
their computer systems that support safe plant operation are ``Y2K 
ready,'' the agency said. The other 35 plants reported that they 
have additional work to complete and provided schedules for 
completing the work, it said. Critics of the utility industry have 
said they fear the bug might cause the nation's power grids to 
crash when clocks strike midnight on Jan. 1, leading to blackouts. 

</P>
<P>
	Tobacco Cos. Liable in Fla. Case  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A landmark lawsuit by smokers yielded a verdict  
Wednesday that could cost the tobacco industry billions in damages. 
Jurors found the companies liable for making a defective product 
that causes emphysema, lung cancer and other illnesses. They will 
return in the next phase to determine damages. Their decision could 
prove to be the industry's most dire courtroom loss yet, since the 
plaintiffs are seeking at least $200 billion. This case was filed 
in 1994 on behalf of as many as 500,000 sick Florida smokers and 
the heirs of those who died. 

</P>
<P>
	Interviews With Racist Aired on TV  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Chilling words videotaped by a racial shooting  
suspect left journalists pondering today whether broadcasting 
Benjamin Smith's message would explain his hatred or spread it. 
NBC's ``Today'' show and ABC's ``Good Morning America'' aired 
interviews by the 21-year-old white supremacist, blamed by 
authorities for a two-state shooting spree that killed two and 
wounded nine. It ended Sunday with Smith's suicide. In the ABC 
interview, conducted by a student documentary filmmaker, Smith said 
a racial holy war was inevitable. 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady Dismisses Outsider Status  
</P>
<P>
	WEST DAVENPORT, N.Y. (AP) -- Perceived by some as a latecomer to  
the New York political scene, Hillary Rodham Clinton pledged that 
she would be a ``strong and effective advocate'' for New Yorkers. 
The first lady plunged into her race for the Senate by brushing 
aside criticism of her outsider status. ``What I am for is maybe as 
important, if not more important, than where I am from,'' she said. 
Mrs. Clinton said she will address questions about what she 
believes in and the skills and interests she would bring to the 
job. 

</P>
<P>
	Ferry on Fire Off Coast of Sweden  
</P>
<P>
	GOTEBORG, Sweden (AP) -- A ferry en route from Germany to Norway  
with about 1,339 passengers and crew was disabled by fire near this 
west coast Swedish city and was being evacuated early Thursday, the 
national news agency TT reported. Merchant ships and helicopters 
were near the scene shortly before dawn to aid the rescue. The 
Princess Ragnhild, which was traveling from Kiel, Germany, to Oslo, 
Norway, is owned by the Color Line. The ship suffered a fire in the 
machine room, TT reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Paroled Suspect Arrested in Calif.  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A prison parolee accused of stabbing two  
teen-age girls and leaving them for dead was arrested Wednesday 
after passersby spotted him lying on a city plaza bench and 
recognized his tattoo. Donald Paul Gatson, 22, was the subject of 
an intense police manhunt after the attack Monday, two days after 
he was released from San Quentin prison. The girls were each 
stabbed more than 15 times and left in a ditch to die. The victims, 
who were in critical condition early Wednesday, had improved 
dramatically and were no longer in critical, Fremont Det. Dennis 
Madsen said. 

</P>
<P>
	Gang Battles Spur Jamaica Curfew  
</P>
<P>
	KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) -- A spate of gang violence in a poor  
Kingston neighborhood caused residents to flee Wednesday and 
prompted authorities to send in police and military units to impose 
a dusk-to-dawn curfew. Five people have been killed since Monday in 
a gang battle in Park Lane, part of a crime wave sweeping the 
Jamaican capital. In the last five days, 25 people have been killed 
in the city of 800,000 people. 

</P>
<P>
	Nikkei Rises in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's key stock index rose in early trading. The  
Nikkei gained 32.44 to 17,991.34. In New York, the Dow industrials 
gained 52.24 to close at a record high of 11,187.36. 

</P>
<P>
	Cardinals Top Reds 2-1  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Darren Bragg's two-run homer in the bottom of  
the ninth inning gave the St. Louis Cardinals a 2-1 win over the 
Cincinnati Reds on Wednesday night. Scott Williamson had pitched 
two hitless innings before blowing the game in the ninth. It was 
just the sixth loss in the last 27 road games for Cincinnati, which 
lost the first two games in St. Louis. The Reds have the best road 
record in the league (26-12). 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
  	   	
</P>
