<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup of Recent Editorials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers in the  
United States and abroad: 

</P>
<P>
	July 3  
</P>
<P>
	The (Portland) Oregonian, on Medicare:  
</P>
<P>
	The growing economy has provided President Clinton with an  
opportunity to do something to help the elderly, and the naysayers 
are already picking the proposal apart. 
</P>
<P>
	In a revised budget that projects much-larger-than-expected  
revenue surpluses, Clinton has proposed adding prescription drug 
coverage to Medicare. The proposed benefit is admittedly modest -- 
$1,000 a year -- and requires a $24 monthly premium payment. 
</P>
<P>
	But he had scarcely cleared his throat before the critics  
launched into all the things they think are wrong with the idea. 
It's enough to make you gag. 
</P>
<P>
	Coverage for medicine is a long-sought-after benefit for the  
elderly. Earlier this year, U.S. Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., outlined a 
more modest plan he was working on with Sen. Olympia Snowe, 
R-Maine. Theirs would begin with prescription coverage for the most 
vulnerable seniors, those who must choose between food and 
medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	At least they're proposing solutions, not simply whining. ...  
</P>
<P>
	The critics should stop carping and come up with some proposals  
of their own. 

</P>
<P>
	June 30  
</P>
<P>
	The Index-Journal of Greenwood, S.C., on Clinton's tax plan:  
</P>
<P>
	Too ambitious. That's how Republican and Democratic lawmakers  
alike described President Clinton's proposal to expand Medicare so 
that all 39 million Americans covered could get prescription drug 
benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Republican Sen. Phil Gramm noted that two-thirds of Micare  
recipients already have prescription coverage, either through the 
Medicaid program for the poor or through private Medigap policies. 
That leaves about 15 million beneficiaries with no coverage. ... 
</P>
<P>
	There shouldn't be one member of Congress who doesn't understand  
that Clinton would make every American dependent upon government if 
he could get away with it. 

</P>
<P>
	July 3  
</P>
<P>
	Denton (Texas) Record-Chronicle, on political gender gap:  
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Ted Stevens, a Republican from Alaska, has whale blubber  
where his brains ought to be. 
</P>
<P>
	He said this week that women want to spend money on ``touchy  
feely'' things and that makes them less supportive of defense 
spending than men, which is bad for the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Has Sen. Stevens ever run into Madeleine Albright or Kay Bailey  
Hutchison during his stint in Washington? We're not going to argue 
with Sen. Stevens' premise if, by ``touchy feely,'' he means such 
frippery as health care, education, quality of life for the 
elderly, and civil rights. 
</P>
<P>
	It is true that the majority of women do exhibit an interest in  
topics relating to the health and welfare of individuals, families 
and communities. And that's just why we need them active at all 
levels of public life. The feminine point of view has been almost 
entirely absent from the power groups that directed most of human 
history, and we haven't been better for it. 

</P>
<P>
	July 1  
</P>
<P>
	The Cincinnati Enquirer, on the Supreme Court and disability:  
</P>
<P>
	Certain government agencies think airlines should hire extremely  
nearsighted pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department and the Equal Employment Opportunity  
Commission also thought a supermarket chain should hire a partially 
blind truck driver. 
</P>
<P>
	Recently, the U.S. Supreme Court rejected those ``rights'' and  
restricted the definition of disability to restore legitimacy to 
the Americans with Disabilities Act. 
</P>
<P>
	Two pilots with 20/200 vision sued because United Airlines  
refused to hire them. The court rejected their claim. 
</P>
<P>
	A Kansas truck driver who failed a Department of Transportation  
vision test was fired and also sued. The court rejected his claim. 
</P>
<P>
	The government is currently trying to force Exxon to hire former  
alcoholics and drug addicts unless Exxon can prove it would pose a 
``direct threat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The oil company paid billions for hiring a former alcoholic who  
ran a supertanker aground in Alaska, causing a notorious oil spill. 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court ruling should curb excess by federal agencies.  
Further abuse of the ADA will repeal protections for genuinely 
disabled Americans. 

</P>
<P>
	June 30  
</P>
<P>
	The Miami Herald, on U.S. refugee policy:  
</P>
<P>
	Ugly is the word that comes to mind, followed by shameful and  
sad and senseless. With the unblinking stare of live television, 
countless numbers of viewers witnessed the arbitrary and too-often 
cruel application of U.S. refugee policy. ... 
</P>
<P>
	This drama unfolded just a few hundred yards off the beach of  
Surfside when the Coast Guard was alerted to the plight of six 
Cuban men in a tiny wooden boat paddling toward shore. ... 
</P>
<P>
	A shocking confrontation ensued as Coast Guard crewmen on a  
larger boat turned a water cannon on the refugees; a second Coast 
Guardsman unnecessarily doused one of the six Cubans with noxious 
spray as the refugee was treading water. ... 
</P>
<P>
	But also subject to review should be the U.S. refugee policy  
that caused this ugly scene, guiding the Coast Guard's action. ... 
</P>
<P>
	The difference between freedom and a return to tyranny was the  
ability to touch the sand on Surfside's beach. That's the law. 
There must be a better way, for the sake of those seeking freedom 
and for the sake of our Coast Guard, which shouldn't be made to act 
as guards for Castro's jail. 

</P>
<P>
	July 1  
</P>
<P>
	San Diego Union-Tribune, on anthrax vaccine:  
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon's decision to inoculate American military personnel  
against highly lethal anthrax contamination is firmly supported by 
potential battlefield threats and sound medical science. Defense 
Secretary William Cohen should not abandon this necessary program 
because of the tiny minority of soldiers, airmen, sailors and 
Marines who have refused to take the vaccine based on 
unsubstantiated claims about its safety. 
</P>
<P>
	There is ample evidence Iraq has developed an array of  
biological weapons, including anthrax, which can be spread over a 
battlefield in dustlike spores. Once inhaled, anthrax toxins cause 
internal bleeding and, in 90 percent of cases, death if left 
untreated. 
</P>
<P>
	The military services would be derelict if they failed to  
protect U.S. personnel from the anthrax threat, especially when a 
vaccine is readily available to counter it. Moreover, it would 
undermine good order and discipline ... if the Pentagon allowed 
some personnel to refuse the vaccine. 

</P>
<P>
	July 2  
</P>
<P>
	Quad-City Times of Davenport, Iowa, on Holbrooke nomination:  
</P>
<P>
	In addition to being a good senator who looks out for the  
interests of Iowans, Chuck Grassley is a man of ethics and high 
principles. Even when he takes what others consider to be the wrong 
course of action, he does so for all the right reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	So it is with his decision to place a hold on the nomination of  
Richard Holbrooke for U.S. ambassador to the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley says he'll invoke a Senate rule that allows one senator  
to delay such nominations unless the State Department rescinds a 
decision to transfer one of its employees who has been critical of 
the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	What does that transfer have to do with Holbrooke?  
</P>
<P>
	Nothing.  
</P>
<P>
	The employee, Linda Shenwick, until recently worked as a senior  
civil service employee at the U.S. mission to the United Nations in 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley questions whether her transfer to a lesser job in  
Washington was in retaliation for her efforts to reveal alleged 
waste and mismanagement at the U.N. 
</P>
<P>
	So now he's calling for negotiations with the State Department  
on resolving her case. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke ... doesn't deserve to have his job put on ice over an  
issue he's uninvolved in and is incapable of resolving. 

</P>
<P>
	July 5  
</P>
<P>
	Der Bund of Bern, Switzerland, on Northern Ireland:  
</P>
<P>
	Tony Blair's timetable didn't work: the British prime minister  
had set his ``final deadline'' for the Northern Ireland parties so 
that the Protestants would have signed up to the provincial 
government before the beginning of the summer marching season. 
Instead of that, the arguments over the realization of the peace 
agreement have heated up. 
</P>
<P>
	The Unionists are crashing into it not only with their  
determined columns of marchers but also with heavy verbal attacks 
that their loyalty to Great Britain should be forbidden in this 
way. Blair has ``betrayed'' them with the proposal to create the 
government first and then to begin the disarming of the Catholic 
IRA underground army.'' 

</P>
<P>
	July 6  
</P>
<P>
	Die Welt of Berlin, on new Israeli government:  
</P>
<P>
	The path was arduous, the coalition negotiations dragged on.  
Ehud Barak succeeded at the last moment to gather his men from all 
possible parties to unite behind him in a government coalition, 
which with 75 of 120 parliament seats finally holds a solid 
majority. 
</P>
<P>
	The choice of his colleagues already indicates Barak's course.  
The future government chief took partners -- whether orthodox or 
secular, whether right or left -- who are willing to level things 
with the Arabs. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak will quickly now start negotiations with Syria (if that  
isn't already being done secretly), speedily come together with 
Arafat, and rapidly improve the disturbed stand with Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	In short he will do everything that was not, or only slightly  
possible, with the Likud. With interior policies Barak will 
certainly have it more difficult. Schas and his rigid rightist 
religious nationalists partners will force him to replace the 
announced course of secularism with a decisive either or policy. 

</P>
<P>
	July 6  
</P>
<P>
	Le Figaro of Paris, on Algeria's decision to grant amnesty to  
Islamic militants: 
</P>
<P>
	Is Abdelaziz Bouteflika in a position to win his bet? ... He  
came to power in the worst conditions. ... He represented a 
detestable past, that of the FLN, which, with its Marxist 
wheeler-dealer police regime, exploited the country to its bones. 
</P>
<P>
	In the blink of an eye, Mr. Bouteflika has changed his regime.  
... He has pleaded for a market economy and denounced corruption. 
... And he has held his hand out to terrorists repenting 
fundamentalism. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Will Algeria finally be able to turn the page? Mr. Bouteflika  
cannot fail. At a time when the terrorists are showing signs of 
weakness, his policy of reconciliation ... is beginning to bear 
fruit. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Now, the wounds must be healed. That is Mr. Bouteflika's  
mission. But he will only succeed if he ... completely follows a 
democratic path, without limiting the right to expression of an 
impertinent press that gave the world lessons in courage. 

</P>
<P>
	July 6  
</P>
<P>
	Asahi Shimbun of Tokyo, on development aid:  
</P>
<P>
	The government has entered the final phase of putting together a  
medium-term policy on official development assistance, which will 
serve as the guideline for Japan's economic aid to poor countries 
in the next five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's official assistance to other countries has exceeded 1.5  
trillion yen ($12.5 billion) this fiscal year. Japanese aid has 
been larger than that of any other countries for eight consecutive 
years. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Government ministries concerned with official development  
assistance only seem to care about protecting their vested 
interests in the allocation of assistance money. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, moreover, there have been increased calls to  
use the assistance as leverage for achieving immediate diplomatic 
goals, such as votes for the developing countries at the United 
Nations. If the Japanese government is too shortsighted, it would 
soon lose interest in the developing world. And international trust 
in Japan would only dwindle. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	July 5  
</P>
<P>
	The Jordan Times of Amman, on Kosovo:  
</P>
<P>
	Albanian and Serb leaders in Kosovo are trying desperately to  
heal wounds and bring their respective communities into terms with 
new realities. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides have condemned the atrocities committed by Belgrade  
but called on Kosovars not to vent their anger by avenging the 
crimes against humanity committed by Serb forces. 
</P>
<P>
	If in fact the war launched by Belgrade against the Kosovars was  
the making of a ultranationalist Serbs and did not enjoy grassroots 
support, then the task of reconciliation should not be too 
difficult. If on the other hand, the Serbs militancy enjoyed public 
support, then the mission of bringing the two peoples together 
could be very difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	The international community should press ahead with the  
objective of democratization in Yugoslavia as soon as possible. A 
democratic Yugoslavia would readily accept to grant the Kosovars 
the right to determine their future. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
