<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 15:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ESPN Scores High With Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- On a day devoted to barbecues and fireworks,  
ESPN managed to set a record for soccer coverage when the U.S. 
women beat Brazil on the Fourth of July. 
</P>
<P>
	The game was watched in 2.9 million homes. It was the largest  
number of households to watch a soccer telecast on the cable 
network. 
</P>
<P>
	The viewership topped the 1994 men's World Cup game between the  
United States and Colombia. That game attracted 2.7 million homes 
and had a 4.3 cable rating. 
</P>
<P>
	The women's 2-0 victory over Brazil posted a 3.8 cable rating.  
</P>
<P>
	The victory nearly doubled the 2.19 mark that the women  
registered in their quarterfinal win over Germany, which was also 
on ESPN. 
</P>
<P>
	The semifinal boosted ESPN's overall Women's World Cup ratings  
to a 1.5 in seven telecasts, with an average of 1.1 million 
households. ESPN2 has a .5 mark in 23 telecasts. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 men's World Cup had a .94 rating in 27 ESPN telecasts  
and a .5 mark on 23 games shown on ESPN2. However, many games were 
shown at poor times for American viewers because the tournament was 
in France. Also, the United States finished last in the 32-team 
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN averaged a 1.6 rating in 34 telecasts for the 1994 men's  
World Cup, which was held in the United States. However, the only 
U.S. game broadcast by the cable network was the game against 
Colombia. 
</P>
<P>
	The American women's tournament-opening win over Denmark last  
month was watched in 1.7 million homes on ABC. Their victory 
against Nigeria was seen in 1.4 million homes on ESPN. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States advanced to the quarterfinals last Sunday with  
a win against North Korea. The game received a 1.96 rating and was 
seen in 1.3 million homes. It was the highest rating for any soccer 
match on ESPN2. 
</P>
<P>
	The rating is the percentage of TV households in the United  
States tuned to a program. Each cable point represents 766,000 
homes on ESPN and 644,000 homes on ESPN2. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 12:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reds' Wohlers Has Elbow Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Reliever Mark Wohlers, determined to keep  
alive his faltering baseball career, has had major reconstructive 
elbow surgery and hopes to pitch for the Cincinnati Reds next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Atlanta Braves closer never played for the Reds after  
they acquired him in April. 
</P>
<P>
	The 29-year-old Wohlers had the operation Tuesday in Birmingham,  
Ala. Orthopedic surgeon James Andrews and Reds team physician 
Timothy Kremchek grafted a tendon from Wohlers' left forearm into 
his right elbow. 
</P>
<P>
	He agreed to the reconstructive surgery in hopes of rescuing his  
career after a magnetic resonance imaging test detected the torn 
ligament last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Wohlers felt a burning sensation after throwing a pitch during  
his minor league rehabilitation assignment two weeks ago and became 
concerned when the elbow didn't improve. That led to the MRI 
examination. 
</P>
<P>
	Wohlers got the final three outs in the Braves' World Series  
championship in 1995, but suddenly lost his ability to throw 
strikes last season. Since his trade to Cincinnati, he had been 
pitching in the minor leagues in hopes of regaining his control and 
working his way back to the majors. 
</P>
<P>
	His elbow injury has thrown his playing future into doubt.  
</P>
<P>
	Wohlers set a Braves record with 39 saves in 1996 and had 33 the  
following season. He pulled a muscle in his left side early last 
year and lost his control in May. 
</P>
<P>
	He was sent to the Braves' Triple-A Richmond affiliate twice to  
try to regain his control, but never found it. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Braves tried to send him back to the minors, he  
declined the assignment, prompting the trade to the Reds. The 
Braves agreed to pay Wohlers' $5.2 million salary this season and 
the $800,000 buyout for next year, the last on his contract. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990707.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 19:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hyundai Sues Boeing for $750M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Hyundai's aerospace affiliate has sued  
Boeing Co. for $750 million, accusing the aircraft giant of 
bad-faith dealings in Hyundai's contract to supply wings for a new 
Boeing passenger jet. 
</P>
<P>
	Hyundai Space &AMP; Aircraft Co. said Boeing and a subsidiary  
stalled on parts deliveries, made thousands of design changes, 
failed to provide skilled workers, fabricated performance 
requirements and falsely accused Hyundai of contract violations. 
</P>
<P>
	The purpose was to induce Hyundai to walk away from the contract  
so a Boeing subsidiary could take over the wing supplies, the South 
Korean company said Tuesday in a lawsuit filed in U.S. District 
Court. 
</P>
<P>
	``Boeing's interference has thwarted (Hyundai's) efforts to  
expand its commercial aerospace business,'' the suit said. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing spokesman John Thom said Wednesday the company would not  
comment on an ongoing suit. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Hyundai was one of 16 major suppliers for the 717 jet, a  
twin-engine, 100-seat plane designed for short-haul trips. 
</P>
<P>
	Hyundai entered the contract in 1996 with McDonnell Douglas  
Corp., which Boeing took over in 1997. A McDonnell Douglas 
subsidiary in Canada, now a Boeing subsidiary, was a subcontractor. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit said Hyundai spent more than $300 million to build a  
manufacturing plant in Seosan, South Korea, and Boeing promised to 
provide trained workers but never did. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing's Toronto subsidiary, which is supposed to provide parts  
for the wings, regularly ships them late and often sends the wrong 
parts, the suit said. It said Boeing and a subsidiary have imposed 
more than 4,000 design changes on Hyundai and its subcontractors in 
less than three years, drastically increasing costs. 
</P>
<P>
	After one Boeing subsidiary failed to deliver wing assemblies to  
Hyundai last October, Boeing withdrew part of its order to Hyundai, 
said another Boeing company would handle that part of the project, 
and demanded that Hyundai pay the extra production costs, the suit 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of Boeing's design changes and delays, Hyundai's  
subcontractors have threatened to end their agreements with Hyundai 
unless they received substantial price increases, Hyundai said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
