<HEADLINE> Shooting Suspect Warned of Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Racial shooting rampage suspect Benjamin Smith  
warned in a recent video that violence and terrorism was 
``inevitable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The video was shown today on ABC's ``Good Morning America,''  
which told viewers ABC News had purchased it. 
</P>
<P>
	The network didn't disclose how much it paid but ABC News  
spokeswoman Sonya McNair said later it was made by a student 
documentary filmmaker working on a project on white supremacy 
groups in Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC said the video was recorded three weeks ago. Smith is seen  
driving his car in Peoria and tossing pamphlets out the window 
while complaining of police harassment and the ``Jewish 
occupational government.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``To want to live in a world where blacks have power over  
whites, where Jews are in control, I think that's a sickness and 
I'd like to eradicate that sickness. In some ways it's inevitable -- 
racial holy war,'' Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith told his interviewer that he was involved in what he  
called ``a life or death struggle for the future of our race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities blame the 21-year-old white supremacist for a  
two-state shooting spree that began Friday in the Chicago area and 
ended Sunday with his suicide in southern Illinois. Two other 
people were killed and nine were wounded in Illinois and Indiana -- 
all of them black, Jewish or of Asian descent. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's ``Today'' show broadcast portions of its own interview  
with Smith on Tuesday and today. The network did not pay for the 
interview, which was acquired through something of a lucky break. 
</P>
<P>
	A student intern at ``Today'' had interviewed Smith for a school  
project at Indiana University in September 1998. He retrieved the 
tapes in time to use them on the morning broadcast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
