<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Businesses in Poor Areas Struggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Leon Singleton's South Los Angeles hair salon  
has been looted by rioting mobs and battered by an earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
	But the most difficult time came later, when the 61-year-old  
entrepreneur applied for a loan to rebuild. Three banks and three 
finance companies turned him down. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd say it was the biggest challenge because I didn't think I  
could get a loan,'' Singleton said in an interview. ``At my age I 
was like washed up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Singleton, who eventually got a loan through a redevelopment  
agency, said his problem is not unique among minority 
small-business owners in America's economically blighted 
communities. 
</P>
<P>
	He and others hope things will improve when President Clinton  
visits South Los Angeles on Thursday to discuss a plan to bring a 
mix of private and public investment to the nation's poor 
communities. 
</P>
<P>
	The visit is part of a national tour designed to focus attention  
on America's chronically underserved towns and cities. 
</P>
<P>
	In coming to the South LA, Clinton also is returning to an area  
he first visited as a candidate in May 1992, a few days after the 
city was decimated by three days of rioting that left 55 people 
dead and 720 buildings destroyed or damaged by fire. 
</P>
<P>
	This week's visit is important not only for the money Clinton is  
proposing to invest, but because it could help convince more banks 
and corporations that they can make money by doing business in 
underserved communities, local leaders say. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really applaud what he is doing. I think if there's any  
constructive criticism, we all wish this kind of bully pulpit had 
been used earlier,'' said John Bryant, founder of Operation Hope, a 
private foundation that has partnered with banks to arrange $45 
million in home and business loans for residents of South and East 
Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton will find that things have changed in South LA since his  
first visit. After the riots, banks and federal redevelopment 
programs have made millions of dollars in loans and grants to local 
businesses, and many damaged areas have been rebuilt. 
</P>
<P>
	And while residents welcome the government's help, there is a  
thriving spirit of free-enterprise and self-reliance. 
</P>
<P>
	The Baldwin Hills Crenshaw Plaza mall, boosted by a Magic  
Johnson movie theater and its proximity to affluent black 
neighborhoods, is booming with an occupancy rate of more than 90 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In other areas, retailers have opened new stores. Three banks,  
Washington Mutual, Wells Fargo and Hawthorne Savings, partnered 
with Operation Hope to open banking centers where residents can 
apply for loans and take classes on managing their finances. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a spirit of self-reliance that has built on itself  
since 1992,'' Bryant said. ``That I can't rely on anybody else to 
take care of me but me. ... What people are basically saying now is 
give me a hand up, not a hand out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The improvements, however, have been spotty. Many neighborhoods  
such as Singleton's, in the heart of South LA, still struggle with 
crime and unemployment. Singleton got his loan through the 
Community Financial Resource Center, where officials were eager to 
stop the decline. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency arranged for a $40,000 loan to repair the shop that  
Singleton opened in 1969. Since rebuilding, Singleton has made just 
enough money to cover his expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Sometimes, he thinks of moving out. He stays to show young  
people that free enterprise is a better route than crime. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like I've got to leave something. I shouldn't just walk  
away,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Community leaders credit Clinton with fostering an environment  
that has helped minority-owned businesses survive and grow. And 
programs such as the one Clinton is proposing could help if it 
actually reaches entrepreneurs who create jobs, said Patricia 
Means, publisher of Turning Point magazine, a publication that 
focuses on African-Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	``There seems to be less reliance on government involvement,  
more on private sector involvement,'' she said. ``We have seen in 
the past that there are so many strings attached to government 
involvement, usually the programs are written so that only a small 
percentage of people can take advantage of them.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
