<DOCNO> APW19990707.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 12:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Charged in Supremacist Gun Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PEORIA, Ill. (AP) -- A man was charged today with illegally  
selling guns used by a white supremacist who went on a deadly 
shooting spree. An affidavit said that the alleged dealer's records 
had been seized last week -- the day before the shootings began. 
</P>
<P>
	Donald R. Fiessinger, 64, of the central Illinois town of Pekin,  
was scheduled to appear in federal court today on charges that he 
sold the guns to Benjamin Smith without a license, according to 
Sharon Paul, a spokeswoman for the U.S. attorney's office in 
Springfield. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, 21, killed himself Sunday as police tried to arrest him,  
ending a string of shootings in Illinois and Indiana from Friday to 
Sunday that killed two people and wounded nine others -- all of them 
black, Jewish or of Asian descent. 
</P>
<P>
	Fiessinger had been under investigation for illegal gun sales  
before the shooting spree, according to Jerry Singer, special agent 
for the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	The guns allegedly sold to Smith last month were among ``dozens  
of guns'' that Fiessinger is charged with selling illegally, Singer 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to an affidavit by Daniel Volk, agent with the federal  
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, Fiessinger advertised 
weapons in the classified section of a local newspaper. Based on 
those ads, two undercover ATF agents arranged to buy weapons from 
Fiessinger on Thursday -- only days after he allegedly sold the guns 
to Smith and the day before the series of shootings began. 
</P>
<P>
	Later Thursday evening, federal agents recovered 27 firearms,  
$330 in cash and records of firearms sales during a search of 
Fiessinger's home, the affidavit said. Volk said Fiessinger told 
him that he thought he was keeping the required federal and state 
records for firearms but knew that he should have obtained a 
license. 
</P>
<P>
	After the weekend's shootings, Fiessinger called Volk on Tuesday  
and told him he remembered selling Smith the two guns found with 
his body, the affidavit said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fiessinger said Smith told him he was going to use the guns for  
hunting. He also said he didn't know of Smith's white supremacist 
beliefs or potential for violence, according to the affidavit. The 
affidavit wasn't clear on whether Smith's name had been in the 
records seized the previous Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal authorities began investigating Fiessinger as an illegal  
guns dealer after a handgun he bought was seized from another 
person during a traffic stop, Volk said. Records showed Fiessinger 
had bought 65 handguns legally from one Pekin store, the Old 
Prairie Trading Post. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked today to comment about the affidavit, Old Prairie owner  
Robert Hayes sounded surprised and said he had no comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith had been rejected by a regular gun dealer last month  
because a background check showed that an ex-girlfriend who says he 
had abused her had taken out a protection order against him. 
</P>
<P>
	Lt. Dave Sanders, a spokesman for the Illinois State Police,  
said the state issued Smith the gun owner's ID card June 18. That 
background check didn't turn up the protection order because the 
order had Smith's middle initial and other details wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith tried to buy two 9 mm handguns and a shotgun on June 23 at  
Heights Gun and Hunter Supplies in Peoria Heights, Singer said. 
After the second background check led to his rejection, Smith 
bought a Bryco .380-caliber semiautomatic handgun on June 26 and 
.22-caliber pistol on June 29 from the unlicensed dealer, Singer 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith's experience and the devastation he wrought has renewed  
the debate over gun control just weeks after Congress considered -- 
but did not agree on -- new restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	``This unfortunately hits home the point that we have to start  
regulating the secondary market as well,'' including gun shows, 
unlicensed gun dealers and sales over the Internet, said Lisa Morel 
Las, the director of the Illinois Council Against Handgun Violence. 
</P>
<P>
	The arguments echo those in the wake of the April massacre at  
Columbine High School in Colorado and the recent debate in 
Congress: Gun control activists say the case demonstrates the 
inadequacy of the nation's gun laws, while the gun lobby says the 
problem is lax enforcement. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Rifle Association argues the system broke down even  
before Smith stepped out of the store and into the world of illegal 
gun dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal law prohibits convicted felons and anyone under such an  
order from purchasing a firearm. Smith's application was denied at 
the gun shop, and the NRA says he should also have been arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal authorities say it's not that simple. Singer said that a  
denial can trigger an investigation, but authorities simply do not 
have enough information to make an immediate arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, a member of a white supremacist group called the World  
Church of the Creator, distributed hate literature while he was a 
student at the University of Illinois and later a student at 
Indiana University in Bloomington. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities say his holiday rampage included shootings in  
Chicago, two of its suburbs, three Downstate Illinois cities and 
Bloomington. Killed were former Northwestern University basketball 
coach Ricky Byrdsong and Won-Joon Yoon, a South Korean doctoral 
student at Indiana University. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities are trying to determine Smith's motive and if he had  
any outside assistance. FBI agent Doug Garrison said Matt Hale, the 
supremacist group's leader, would not be implicated in the spree 
simply for his beliefs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
