<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 14:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mazda Recalling New Minivan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Mazda Motor Corp. has recalled the first of its  
new 2000 MPV minivans because they were fitted with a wrong 
combination of engine parts, which could cause a fuel leak. 
</P>
<P>
	The recall announced Wednesday came just days after the  
redesigned MPV went on sale at some dealers. Only 87 of the 
affected minivans reached consumers, most on the West Coast, and 
each owner has been contacted by phone to get the necessary 
repairs, Mazda spokesman Brian Betz said. 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of the vehicles were in dealer, port or distribution  
inventories and were being fixed, said Duke Hale, vice president of 
customer service for Mazda North America operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the minivans were built with the wrong combination of  
lower intake manifold, fuel injector and fuel rail assembly, which 
could cause a rough idle or a fuel leak. Mazda said it was unaware 
of any leaks arising from the mistake, however. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
