<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 16:20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doyle Is a Favorite in Senior Open  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- For a budding golf star, Allen  
Doyle is about as low key as they come. 
</P>
<P>
	He has an unorthodox swing that looks more like a slap shot in  
hockey. Upon graduating from the senior tour qualifying school, he 
went all out and bought himself a truck. He didn't even turn pro 
until he was 46 and did so partly to make a few extra bucks to pay 
for his daughters' college. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet there he sat, with three senior tour victories and more than  
$1 million already in the bank this year, talking about his role as 
one of the favorites in the U.S. Senior Open, which starts 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am legitimate, I think,'' Doyle said. ``I wouldn't mind  
seeing the fairways a little tighter. Then I might be a little more 
confident of my chances. But I am capable. There is not anything 
that anybody would like more than me than to win the U.S. Senior 
Open.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doyle has been sensational in his first full season on the  
senior tour, one of the few areas in sports where it's an advantage 
to be a rookie. 
</P>
<P>
	He ranks second in earnings to Bruce Fleisher, also a senior  
rookie, and his three victories include one of the majors, a 
2-stroke win at the PGA Seniors Championship at Palm Beach Garden, 
Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	His other victories came at the ACE Group Classic and the NFL  
Golf Classic. And the more he wins, the higher he has to set his 
goals. Doyle had started out on the modest side, hoping only to 
finish among the top 31, which would have automatically qualified 
him for next year's Tour, and maybe win a tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would have been thrilled with that,'' he said. ``After you  
win once, you change your goal to top 20 and two wins. After you 
win again, then you want a fourth win and you want top five.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Having played in the U.S. Open several times as an amateur,  
getting that fourth win in the Senior Open would be special. He'll 
be among 156 golfers playing the 6,888-yard, par-72 Des Moines Golf 
and Country Club course, which is the site of a major tournament 
for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleisher, who has won four tournaments in his first year as a  
senior, also is entered, and so is defending champion Hale Irwin, 
who after a slow start this year has won three of his last five 
tournaments. 
</P>
<P>
	Others in the field include Larry Nelson, No. 3 on the money  
list; Vicente Fernandez, last year's runner-up; Graham Marsh, 
winner of The Tradition this year; and Christy O'Connor, coming off 
a victory in the State Farm Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	They'll have to contend with a course that will put a premium on  
approach shots and putting. The golfers have found the undulating 
greens to be especially challenging in their practice rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think anyone that thinks they are just going to tear this  
golf course up is wrong,'' said Arnold Palmer, who at 69 is the 
tournament's oldest competitor. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Connor suggested that a guy could be in contention without  
breaking par. Irwin won last year at Riviera near Los Angeles at 
1-over-par. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't mind sitting here at about 2-over (on Sunday),''  
said O'Connor, whose victory last Sunday was his first on the 
senior tour. ``I would be very, very happy. I'd let the rest of the 
field play. I think if it blows any, I would be very, very 
comfortable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doyle said it will be important to stay patient and not get  
frustrated by a couple of bad shots. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to handle it properly and realize there is a long way  
to go,'' he said. ``It's not so much the guy who makes the most 
birdies that is going to win, but the guy who makes the fewest 
bogeys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irwin, the top player on the tour last year, is trying to become  
the third to win back-to-back titles in the Senior Open. He won 
last year after opening with a 77, the highest one-round score for 
a winner in the history of the senior tour. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly this championship, from a career perspective, will  
always be at the top of my list,'' Irwin said. ``I would love to 
repeat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Open will be the biggest golf event staged in Iowa and  
already has been a stunning success at the gate. The tournament was 
sold out in advance for the first time and the practice rounds drew 
crowds of 25,000 Monday, 27,000 Tuesday and 29,000 Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Irwin was amazed at the large gallery on Monday, when the  
temperatures climbed into the 90s. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was probably the biggest crowd I have seen on a Monday  
anywhere in a tournament,'' he said. ``It was an unbelievable 
display of support and enthusiasm.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
