<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DuPont To Close Six Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- DuPont will close six plants in the wake  
of its $1.8 billion takeover in March of Herberts, a leading 
European manufacturer of automotive and industrial paints. 
</P>
<P>
	The consolidation will eliminate 500 manufacturing positions and  
800 corporate, marketing and staff positions, DuPont said 
Wednesday. The plants to be closed are located in Caieiras, Brazil; 
Piobesi, Italy; Dagenham, England; Ocoyoacac, Mexico; Porto, 
Portugal; and Saffle, Sweden, the company announced. 
</P>
<P>
	Production will be shifted to the remaining 40 plants.  
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal is to minimize staff redundancies in our merged  
organization,'' said Louis F. Savelli, president of DuPont 
Performance Coatings. 
</P>
<P>
	DuPont formed its Performance Coatings unit following the  
acquisition of Herberts, making it the world's leading manufacturer 
of automotive coatings and the third-largest coatings supplier, the 
company said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to automotive coatings such as finishes and primers,  
the division produces industrial coatings, inks used in ink-jet 
printers, and specialty colorants. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, DuPont said its Performance Coatings division would  
have annual sales of more than $3.8 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The cost of the consolidation will be included in the accounting  
for the Herbert acquisition and will not result in any charges to 
1999 earnings, DuPont said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of DuPont fell 81 1/4 cents to close at $69.93 3/4 on the New  
York Stock Exchange. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
