<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 11:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Exchanges Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
        LONDON (AP) -- Share prices finished lower on European markets  
today, with one of the heaviest hits absorbed by the telecommunications 
group Ericsson. 
</P>
<P>
        The resignation of Ericsson president and chief executive Sven-Christer  
Nilsson as president and chief executive late in the European trading 
day drove Ericsson stock down 8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
        The Stockholm SXG index closed down 2.2 percent, the worst  
among weak European markets Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
        The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 594 European companies closed  
down 1.82 points, or 0.6 percent, at 323.42, while the Dow Jones Euro 
Stoxx Index, which tracks 295 companies in countries that joined the 
euro single currency, finished down 1.46 points at 335.07. 
</P>
<P>
        The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index ended down 18.50 points at  
3950.49, while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index was down 32.96 points at 3901. 
68. 
</P>
<P>
        Basic resource stocks were up 1.4 percent across Europe, as  
investors moved out of other sectors. London-listed mining group Billiton 
was among the beneficiaries, rising 2.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
        European chemical stocks ended flat, but speculation returned  
that Swiss chemicals group Clariant may come in with a bid for the 
British company, Laporte. Laporte shares jumped 6.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
        Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index closed down 0.4 percent; the Paris  
CAC-40 index was down 0.7 percent, Milan's MIBtel index fell 0.2 percent, 
and Madrid's IBEX-35 index was down 0.7 percent. London's FTSE-100 
index was down 0.4 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
