<DOCNO> APW19990707.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 07:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A Break in East's Heat Wave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The heat wave that has brought sweaty misery and  
even death eased today as a cool front moved through the East, but 
a power outage in upper Manhattan left tens of thousands of people 
in the dark overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Record highs and power demands were set again Tuesday as  
utilities scrambled to keep electricity flowing around flaming 
transformers and melting power lines. But the forecast for today 
was for an end to triple-digit temperatures. 
</P>
<P>
	``It feels like somebody's thrown buckets of hot water in your  
face,'' said Pat Renaghan, an elevator operator in a subway station 
at 168th Street in New York City. ``Sometimes when you take the 
elevator down, the air feels so thick you feel like you could chew 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 68,000 electricity customers above 155th Street in  
Manhattan were without power through the night, Con Edison 
spokesman Joe Petta said. The outage also affect subway service in 
the area this morning. There were a handful of attempted store 
break-ins and nine arrests in the affected area, police said. Fire 
trucks with portable lights illuminated the streets overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The electric company, Consolidated Edison, ``is there and gets  
paid to make sure that doesn't happen,'' said a frustrated Mayor 
Rudolph Giuliani. ``They've got to be ready.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other scattered outages, usually briefer, affected hundreds of  
thousands of customers across the region. 
</P>
<P>
	The welcome cold front moving in from the Midwest arrived in  
deadly fashion Tuesday, triggering violent storms in upstate New 
York and New England. 
</P>
<P>
	A camper in Lake George, N.Y., died when he was struck by a tree  
snapped by the storms. In Hatfield, Mass., a man was killed and two 
people were hurt when a branch fell on their car during the fierce 
winds. Another man was killed when a tree fell on his car in 
Sanbornton, N.H. 
</P>
<P>
	The intense heat already had contributed to at least 17 other  
deaths: seven in Pennsylvania, three in New York City, three in New 
Jersey, two in Massachusetts and two in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Today was expected to be markedly less humid and slightly  
cooler, with highs in the 70s and 80s in much of New England and in 
the 90s farther south. 
</P>
<P>
	High temperature records started falling again before the sun  
even reached its peak Tuesday, as Atlantic City, N.J., hit 98 
before noon, with humidity of about 40 percent. The mercury hit 
record highs of 102 at Newark, N.J., 101 in New York, 102 in 
Raleigh-Durham, N.C., and 103 at Washington's Reagan National 
Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	School officials in Philadelphia, New York and Washington sent  
thousands of summer-school students home because many buildings had 
no air conditioning. 
</P>
<P>
	A generator failure at a Dagsboro, Del., power plant belonging  
to Conectiv led to rolling blackouts that affected about 400,000 of 
the utility's 1 million customers in New Jersey, Delaware and 
Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York City, many office workers were advised to leave  
early, only to be stalled by some subways and commuter rail lines 
that were hit with scattered outages. More than a dozen schools 
were opened to provide air-conditioned places to sleep. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't remember hotter days than the last several and  
particularly hotter nights,'' said Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of other utility customers elsewhere in the region  
lost power, either to the crippling demands caused by the heat wave 
or storms that toppled trees and downed lines. To some, the nasty 
weather was worth it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a thermometer in my house and it was about 92  
degrees,'' said Denise Dubreuil of North Adams, Mass. ``Then the 
storm came, and it cooled it down to 74. ... It was awesome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The relief, however small, was welcome to Timothy Hearn, who  
spent Monday painting a house in Cherry Hill, N.J., and almost 
passed out in the heat. After a nearly sleepless night, he admitted 
himself Tuesday to a hospital where his body fluids were being 
replenished intravenously. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just felt like the end of the world,'' Hearn said from in  
his hospital bed at Temple University Hospital. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
